WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:26.360 --> 00:00:29.380
&gt;&gt; Dr. Carla Hayden: Good
afternoon and thank you

00:00:29.380 --> 00:00:32.670
for coming and welcome to
the Library of Congress.

00:00:32.670 --> 00:00:33.970
I'm Carla Hayden.

00:00:33.970 --> 00:00:37.510
The 14th Library of
Congress and we're looking --

00:00:37.510 --> 00:00:42.050
[ Applause ]

00:00:42.050 --> 00:00:43.350
Thank you.

00:00:43.350 --> 00:00:44.650
And we're looking
forward to a very,

00:00:44.650 --> 00:00:48.590
very exciting afternoon
celebrating the 50th anniversary

00:00:48.590 --> 00:00:51.360
of the signing by
President Lyndon Johnson

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:56.510
of the Public Broadcasting
Act of 1967.

00:00:56.510 --> 00:01:00.630
And we have four star
studded panel s in store

00:01:00.630 --> 00:01:03.360
for you featuring
many great names

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:06.370
of public broadcasting
both in radio,

00:01:06.370 --> 00:01:08.680
on radio and in television.

00:01:08.680 --> 00:01:12.820
And I want to take this
opportunity to single out one

00:01:12.820 --> 00:01:15.240
of our guests here today.

00:01:15.240 --> 00:01:19.540
His name is Mr. Henry
Morgenthau, III.

00:01:19.540 --> 00:01:24.550
And he said I could
tell you this.

00:01:24.550 --> 00:01:27.510
He is 100 years old.

00:01:27.510 --> 00:01:36.610
[ Applause ]

00:01:36.610 --> 00:01:40.780
And he was working
at WGBH 50 years ago

00:01:40.780 --> 00:01:45.800
when the act was passed and
his grandfather was Henry

00:01:45.800 --> 00:01:50.500
Morgenthau, Jr. who was
FDR's treasury secretary.

00:01:50.500 --> 00:01:53.020
And I am proud to
say that the Library

00:01:53.020 --> 00:01:56.640
of Congress has the
papers of his grandfather.

00:01:56.640 --> 00:02:00.580
And so sir, we are truly honored
that you are here with us today.

00:02:00.580 --> 00:02:02.380
Thank you.

00:02:02.380 --> 00:02:08.910
[ Applause ]

00:02:08.910 --> 00:02:10.940
Many of you may know
that the Library

00:02:10.940 --> 00:02:14.200
of Congress is the largest and
most comprehensive collection

00:02:14.200 --> 00:02:17.830
of motion pictures, television
programs, radio broadcast

00:02:17.830 --> 00:02:21.180
and sound recordings
in the world is honored

00:02:21.180 --> 00:02:24.060
to host this event with WGBH,

00:02:24.060 --> 00:02:27.800
Educational Foundation
our collaborators

00:02:27.800 --> 00:02:33.720
in the American Archive of
Public Broadcasting or AAPB.

00:02:33.720 --> 00:02:37.130
The Library received its first
public television programs in -

00:02:37.130 --> 00:02:43.490
and at the Library of Congress
I get my centuries mixed up.

00:02:43.490 --> 00:02:48.480
1964 from the precursor to PBS,

00:02:48.480 --> 00:02:52.810
the National Educational
Television and Radio Center

00:02:52.810 --> 00:02:56.290
and incidentally just last
month we digitized two

00:02:56.290 --> 00:02:59.880
of these programs so that they
could be more accessible via the

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:01.680
Library's website.

00:03:01.680 --> 00:03:06.590
Now the Library's public
broadcasting holdings have grown

00:03:06.590 --> 00:03:11.600
exponentially since 1964 to
include tens of thousands

00:03:11.600 --> 00:03:16.630
of film, video and
audio masters from NET,

00:03:16.630 --> 00:03:19.590
PBS, NPR, WNET and WETA.

00:03:19.590 --> 00:03:23.500
And in addition to the thousands

00:03:23.500 --> 00:03:30.630
of access copies we routinely
acquire as copyright deposits

00:03:30.630 --> 00:03:32.520
from public broadcasting
stations

00:03:32.520 --> 00:03:35.430
and producers across the nation.

00:03:35.430 --> 00:03:39.490
And as the chief steward of
Americas and the World's Record

00:03:39.490 --> 00:03:42.600
of Knowledge we took
to heart the television

00:03:42.600 --> 00:03:47.030
and video preservation study
commissioned 20 years ago

00:03:47.030 --> 00:03:48.730
by the Library of Congress,

00:03:48.730 --> 00:03:50.950
which characterized
public television

00:03:50.950 --> 00:03:56.220
as "the richest audio visual
source of cultural history

00:03:56.220 --> 00:03:58.380
in the United States".

00:03:58.380 --> 00:04:01.860
And so we are proud to
join with WGBH to ensure

00:04:01.860 --> 00:04:07.680
that public television's legacy
survives for future generations.

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:10.300
Now at this time I'd
like to make some news

00:04:10.300 --> 00:04:13.300
and that's why I'm
kind of excited.

00:04:13.300 --> 00:04:16.060
I want to announce some
exciting new acquisitions

00:04:16.060 --> 00:04:19.900
and projects related to public
broadcasting preservation.

00:04:19.900 --> 00:04:24.380
First of all, and as a Library
you don't get to break news

00:04:24.380 --> 00:04:29.770
that often, so you news
people bear with me.

00:04:29.770 --> 00:04:33.360
I want to thank Mr.
Dick Cavett for donating

00:04:33.360 --> 00:04:35.130
to the Library his collection,

00:04:35.130 --> 00:04:38.510
ooh I heard a little
something going on.

00:04:38.510 --> 00:04:43.090
[ Applause ]

00:04:43.090 --> 00:04:44.920
&gt;&gt; Mr. Dick Cavett for
donating to the Library

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:49.210
of Congress his collection
of approximately 2,500 shows

00:04:49.210 --> 00:04:57.200
from 1968 to 1996, including
the 1,000 shows he made for PBS.

00:04:57.200 --> 00:05:02.090
He interviewed more than
5,000 guests for these shows.

00:05:02.090 --> 00:05:05.890
And the list is astonishing,
and a testament to his ability

00:05:05.890 --> 00:05:10.630
to draw people not normally
seen on late night television,

00:05:10.630 --> 00:05:14.490
Katherine Hepburn,
Alfred Hitchcock,

00:05:14.490 --> 00:05:18.460
Angela Davis, Marlon Brando.

00:05:18.460 --> 00:05:21.660
And on one of the more memorable

00:05:21.660 --> 00:05:26.510
and notorious shows Gore
Vidal and Norman Mailer.

00:05:26.510 --> 00:05:30.090
[ Applause ]

00:05:30.090 --> 00:05:33.640
And he also featured rock and
roll musicians to a degree,

00:05:33.640 --> 00:05:37.390
pretty unusual for the
time including John Lennon

00:05:37.390 --> 00:05:43.610
and Yoko Ono, Jimi Hendrix,
Janis Joplin, David Bowie,

00:05:43.610 --> 00:05:46.090
Judy Collins and Joni Mitchell.

00:05:46.090 --> 00:05:51.050
So, I was pretty excited to
announce also that today,

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:55.780
the AAPB will launch an amazing
new exhibit on its website

00:05:55.780 --> 00:06:00.270
that will make public
television's first coverage

00:06:00.270 --> 00:06:03.910
of the senate Watergate
hearings available -

00:06:03.910 --> 00:06:07.130
I'm breaking news all over.

00:06:07.130 --> 00:06:10.320
Television's full coverage

00:06:10.320 --> 00:06:14.050
of the senate Watergate
hearings available online

00:06:14.050 --> 00:06:16.720
for the very first time.

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:18.520
This was one of the -

00:06:18.520 --> 00:06:23.040
[ Applause ]

00:06:23.040 --> 00:06:25.310
This was one of the
most popular series

00:06:25.310 --> 00:06:28.180
in public broadcasting history.

00:06:28.180 --> 00:06:31.560
And the Library of
Congress has digitized all

00:06:31.560 --> 00:06:35.280
of the master videotapes of the
coverage we received from WETA

00:06:35.280 --> 00:06:41.010
in 1989 and with their
permission are making them

00:06:41.010 --> 00:06:45.430
accessible online to
anyone in the United States.

00:06:45.430 --> 00:06:50.270
The broadcast created what Dick
Cavett has called Watergate

00:06:50.270 --> 00:06:53.700
junkies, to refer to
himself and others

00:06:53.700 --> 00:06:56.730
who watched the hearings
obsessively.

00:06:56.730 --> 00:07:00.010
The exhibit was created
this summer by a Library

00:07:00.010 --> 00:07:05.400
of Congress junior fellow,
Amanda Ricobec, a history major

00:07:05.400 --> 00:07:07.930
from Yale who is with us today.

00:07:07.930 --> 00:07:10.510
Could you please
stand up Amanda?

00:07:10.510 --> 00:07:20.230
[ Applause ]

00:07:20.230 --> 00:07:24.550
We sent the detailed background
essay she wrote to Jim Lehrer,

00:07:24.550 --> 00:07:28.940
who anchored the coverage
with Robert MacNeil.

00:07:28.940 --> 00:07:30.990
Jim also is here today.

00:07:30.990 --> 00:07:33.980
And after reading the
essay he wrote back "It is

00:07:33.980 --> 00:07:36.570
as terrific as it is accurate".

00:07:36.570 --> 00:07:39.830
And two years after
hearings MacNeil

00:07:39.830 --> 00:07:42.430
and Lehrer worked together again

00:07:42.430 --> 00:07:46.350
on another landmark public
broadcasting program.

00:07:46.350 --> 00:07:49.140
I think you've all heard
of it and the rest of it is

00:07:49.140 --> 00:07:51.290
as they say is history.

00:07:51.290 --> 00:07:54.130
Jim has commented
that without Watergate

00:07:54.130 --> 00:08:00.460
"there would have been no
anything called MacNeil Lehrer".

00:08:00.460 --> 00:08:04.290
Jim will be on a panel later
today and will show a few clips

00:08:04.290 --> 00:08:05.900
from the Watergate coverage.

00:08:05.900 --> 00:08:09.160
AABP also is in the process

00:08:09.160 --> 00:08:12.910
of making available online
full interviews conducted

00:08:12.910 --> 00:08:16.070
for a number of landmark
PBS series.

00:08:16.070 --> 00:08:20.040
Ken Burns' the Civil
War, Eyes on the Prize

00:08:20.040 --> 00:08:25.410
and the definitive series on
the Civil Rights Movement,

00:08:25.410 --> 00:08:28.670
Eyes on the Prize and the
American Masters Biography

00:08:28.670 --> 00:08:31.660
Series and American Experience.

00:08:31.660 --> 00:08:36.400
So, they are telling me to get
off the stage because there is

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:39.140
so much more I could tell
you about the project,

00:08:39.140 --> 00:08:40.980
but I've run out of time.

00:08:40.980 --> 00:08:45.110
So I want to think Ms. Patricia
Harrison, President and CEO

00:08:45.110 --> 00:08:49.320
of the Corporation for Public
Broadcasting for their support

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:51.110
of the Library of Congress.

00:08:51.110 --> 00:08:52.750
Unfortunately we're learning

00:08:52.750 --> 00:08:55.680
that Pat's flight has been
delayed and she won't be able

00:08:55.680 --> 00:08:57.140
to join us this afternoon

00:08:57.140 --> 00:09:01.510
but could you please give
her a hand in absenteeism?

00:09:01.510 --> 00:09:07.040
[ Applause ]

00:09:07.040 --> 00:09:09.230
And I'd like to introduce
Letitia King,

00:09:09.230 --> 00:09:12.600
Senior Vice President of
Communications for CPB

00:09:12.600 --> 00:09:16.510
to speak on her behalf.

00:09:16.510 --> 00:09:32.050
[ Applause ]

00:09:32.050 --> 00:09:33.730
&gt;&gt; Letitia King: Thank you
Dr. Hayden and thank you

00:09:33.730 --> 00:09:36.990
for your leadership and also for
hosting this important gathering

00:09:36.990 --> 00:09:39.160
at the Library of Congress.

00:09:39.160 --> 00:09:42.130
I would like to recognize
Senator Markey and thank him

00:09:42.130 --> 00:09:43.630
for his important support,

00:09:43.630 --> 00:09:47.360
not only for his home
town station WGVH but also

00:09:47.360 --> 00:09:50.210
for his leadership
advocating for and helping

00:09:50.210 --> 00:09:54.510
to sustain a vital public
media system for all Americans.

00:09:54.510 --> 00:10:01.370
[ Applause ]

00:10:01.370 --> 00:10:05.430
It is largely because of his
and others consistent support

00:10:05.430 --> 00:10:08.900
of public media that we are
here today celebrating the 50th

00:10:08.900 --> 00:10:11.340
anniversary of the
Public Broadcasting Act.

00:10:11.340 --> 00:10:14.430
The 1967 Act articulates
a vision

00:10:14.430 --> 00:10:17.760
of a strong public media
service providing access

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:21.480
to every American to the
highest quality of educational

00:10:21.480 --> 00:10:25.220
and informational content
for free and commercial free.

00:10:25.220 --> 00:10:30.620
The goal then as is now, to
strengthen our civil society

00:10:30.620 --> 00:10:32.220
through content that
would result

00:10:32.220 --> 00:10:36.540
in educated informed
and engaged citizens.

00:10:36.540 --> 00:10:40.460
The three pillars of
a vibrant democracy.

00:10:40.460 --> 00:10:45.770
From 1967 to 2017 the Act
continues to provide us

00:10:45.770 --> 00:10:48.220
with an evergreen
mission and vision

00:10:48.220 --> 00:10:51.750
for public medias important
role in American life.

00:10:51.750 --> 00:10:54.670
And one that the Corporation
for Public Broadcasting,

00:10:54.670 --> 00:10:57.930
CPB is proud to advance.

00:10:57.930 --> 00:11:02.460
Because the Act created CPB and
designated us as the steward

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:04.260
of the Federal Appropriation,

00:11:04.260 --> 00:11:06.490
tasking us with insuring
these funds went

00:11:06.490 --> 00:11:09.280
to public media stations
to serve underserved

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:12.430
and unserved communities,
from our youngest

00:11:12.430 --> 00:11:14.840
to our oldest citizens.

00:11:14.840 --> 00:11:18.800
We are directed to utilize
technology and innovative ways

00:11:18.800 --> 00:11:21.700
of connecting to new
generations to serve

00:11:21.700 --> 00:11:24.260
as American's largest classroom

00:11:24.260 --> 00:11:27.530
to help inspire life-long
learning and to invest

00:11:27.530 --> 00:11:31.720
in journalism that is fact
based, in depth and committed

00:11:31.720 --> 00:11:34.390
to editorial integrity.

00:11:34.390 --> 00:11:39.150
Today PBS, NPR and nearly
1,500 local public television

00:11:39.150 --> 00:11:42.770
and radio stations in rural,
small town and urban communities

00:11:42.770 --> 00:11:45.480
across the country are
fulfilling the mission

00:11:45.480 --> 00:11:48.400
and vision of the
Public Broadcasting Act.

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:52.630
Reaching 99% of an increasingly
diverse America with content

00:11:52.630 --> 00:11:57.520
that continues to be a value
long after the initial broadcast

00:11:57.520 --> 00:11:59.770
or digital presentation.

00:11:59.770 --> 00:12:03.670
Content that has cultural and
historical relevance provides us

00:12:03.670 --> 00:12:06.440
with insights about
the way that we were

00:12:06.440 --> 00:12:09.780
and about the way we
are now as a people,

00:12:09.780 --> 00:12:13.700
as a civil society,
as a democracy.

00:12:13.700 --> 00:12:16.420
The value of this
content is priceless.

00:12:16.420 --> 00:12:19.840
But it was deteriorating and
would no longer be accessible

00:12:19.840 --> 00:12:21.910
to future generations.

00:12:21.910 --> 00:12:26.100
That is why following a two
year pilot that began in 2009,

00:12:26.100 --> 00:12:31.400
CPB provided almost $3
million in grants in 2011

00:12:31.400 --> 00:12:34.240
to public media stations
so they could inventory

00:12:34.240 --> 00:12:37.510
and protect their
station archives.

00:12:37.510 --> 00:12:40.350
That first step helped
to build the foundation

00:12:40.350 --> 00:12:43.310
for the American archive
of Public Broadcasting.

00:12:43.310 --> 00:12:49.100
But CPB did not do this along
and we are appreciative of WGBH,

00:12:49.100 --> 00:12:51.740
the Library of Congress
and many others

00:12:51.740 --> 00:12:55.510
for their ongoing commitment
to this important initiative.

00:12:55.510 --> 00:12:59.690
So in addition to thanking Dr.
Hayden and Senator Markey I want

00:12:59.690 --> 00:13:02.450
to thank Jon Abbott
the President and CEO

00:13:02.450 --> 00:13:04.750
of WGBH for his leadership.

00:13:04.750 --> 00:13:08.810
WGBH is an innovative community
focused station providing public

00:13:08.810 --> 00:13:10.600
broadcasting for New England

00:13:10.600 --> 00:13:15.020
and is also PBS's leading
content provider, producer

00:13:15.020 --> 00:13:17.950
and a major supplier of
programming for public radio

00:13:17.950 --> 00:13:20.530
and digital content nationwide.

00:13:20.530 --> 00:13:23.920
Jon's leadership has resulted
in a strong partnership

00:13:23.920 --> 00:13:25.520
with the Library of Congress

00:13:25.520 --> 00:13:28.210
to preserve public
media's legacy content

00:13:28.210 --> 00:13:31.150
through the American Archive
of Public Broadcasting.

00:13:31.150 --> 00:13:34.000
And we are so appreciative
of his commitment.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:35.800
Please welcome Jon Abbott.

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:45.530
[ Applause ]

00:13:45.530 --> 00:13:46.830
&gt;&gt; Jon Abbott: What a gathering.

00:13:46.830 --> 00:13:51.620
What an honor to be with so many
of these extraordinary leaders

00:13:51.620 --> 00:13:53.260
through the history of
public broadcasting.

00:13:53.260 --> 00:13:54.560
Thank you Tish.

00:13:54.560 --> 00:13:57.780
Let me add my welcome to all
of you who have joined us today

00:13:57.780 --> 00:14:01.040
for this extraordinary
meeting, this opportunity

00:14:01.040 --> 00:14:04.560
to share these panels and these
reflections, this history.

00:14:04.560 --> 00:14:08.430
And my special thanks to
Dr. Hayden for hosting us.

00:14:08.430 --> 00:14:10.660
The Library of Congress
is a fitting location

00:14:10.660 --> 00:14:13.040
to mark this milestone
for public media.

00:14:13.040 --> 00:14:16.170
As many of you know WGBH and
the Library came together

00:14:16.170 --> 00:14:20.020
as Tish mentioned four years
ago to form the American Archive

00:14:20.020 --> 00:14:21.670
of Public Broadcasting

00:14:21.670 --> 00:14:24.550
to collect the significant
historical content created

00:14:24.550 --> 00:14:29.680
by public television and radio
stations over these 50 years.

00:14:29.680 --> 00:14:32.440
Because of the vision and
support of Pat Harrison,

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:36.620
CPB and its board the American
Archive is preserving the

00:14:36.620 --> 00:14:39.090
programs that witness
our collective history

00:14:39.090 --> 00:14:41.840
and tell America's stories.

00:14:41.840 --> 00:14:45.070
More than 100 public
television and radio stations

00:14:45.070 --> 00:14:47.350
across the country from Maine

00:14:47.350 --> 00:14:51.190
to Guam have shared their
content with the archive.

00:14:51.190 --> 00:14:55.930
The collection now has over
50,000 hours of content

00:14:55.930 --> 00:15:00.270
and we are adding
25,000 hours every year.

00:15:00.270 --> 00:15:01.570
And in keeping with the mission

00:15:01.570 --> 00:15:04.900
of public media the American
Archive is available directly

00:15:04.900 --> 00:15:09.700
to the public with some
23,000 programs in addition

00:15:09.700 --> 00:15:15.660
to resources available daily
for educators and researchers.

00:15:15.660 --> 00:15:18.880
WGBH is proud to be working in
partnership with the Library

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:22.250
of Congress to preserve
these historic treasures

00:15:22.250 --> 00:15:25.070
and to make them available
for future generations.

00:15:25.070 --> 00:15:28.140
And I'd like to acknowledge our
dedicated American Archive team

00:15:28.140 --> 00:15:33.510
Sue Canterwicz, Karen Cariani
and Casey Davis-Sucoughlin.

00:15:33.510 --> 00:15:40.670
[ Applause ]

00:15:40.670 --> 00:15:43.400
And on this anniversary as
we celebrate the legislation

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:44.930
that created public
broadcasting,

00:15:44.930 --> 00:15:47.710
we note with gratitude the
federal government's investment

00:15:47.710 --> 00:15:53.340
in our work, consistent,
persistent and forward looking.

00:15:53.340 --> 00:15:56.600
For SGBH one individual in
particular of course embodies

00:15:56.600 --> 00:16:00.310
that support and that is
our senator Edward Markey.

00:16:00.310 --> 00:16:02.880
Now he had very much
hoped to be with us today

00:16:02.880 --> 00:16:04.740
and we're sorry he
couldn't join us.

00:16:04.740 --> 00:16:07.810
He has served on the advisory
council for the American Archive

00:16:07.810 --> 00:16:11.880
and has served on the hill for
40 of the public broadcasting,

00:16:11.880 --> 00:16:14.500
of public broadcasting's
50 years.

00:16:14.500 --> 00:16:17.250
He knows our work very well

00:16:17.250 --> 00:16:20.820
and throughout he has been
a star work champion of all

00:16:20.820 --> 00:16:22.790
that we aspire to do
for the American people

00:16:22.790 --> 00:16:24.230
across the country.

00:16:24.230 --> 00:16:26.980
Our thanks to all of you for
being with us here today.

00:16:26.980 --> 00:16:28.650
I'm very much looking
forward to hearing

00:16:28.650 --> 00:16:29.950
from our extraordinary group

00:16:29.950 --> 00:16:32.610
of panelists assembled
for this occasion.

