00:17:47.990 --> 00:17:49.660
So, here we are and we're going

00:17:49.660 --> 00:17:51.850
to roll a clip with
Newton Minow.

00:17:51.850 --> 00:17:55.690
He was the FCC Chairman
during 1961 to 1963

00:17:55.690 --> 00:17:57.680
and very instrumental in
getting the Public Broadcasting

00:17:57.680 --> 00:17:58.980
Act launched.

00:17:58.980 --> 00:18:04.200
&gt;&gt; Mr. Chairman hasn't something
happened this week speaking

00:18:04.200 --> 00:18:06.680
about the government
and television

00:18:06.680 --> 00:18:10.780
that has really revolutionized
the passing of this bill

00:18:10.780 --> 00:18:12.100
for educational television?

00:18:12.100 --> 00:18:16.160
&gt;&gt; Yes, the President
this week signed a bill,

00:18:16.160 --> 00:18:20.710
which for the first time
will commit to federal funds

00:18:20.710 --> 00:18:24.220
for the construction of
if you'll pardon the term,

00:18:24.220 --> 00:18:26.470
educational television stations.

00:18:26.470 --> 00:18:29.370
And to link these
stations together.

00:18:29.370 --> 00:18:33.050
This will be the first time
that it's on a matching basis

00:18:33.050 --> 00:18:36.760
with states and private
institutions.

00:18:36.760 --> 00:18:39.600
The federal funds, public
funds will be committed

00:18:39.600 --> 00:18:41.420
with this purpose.

00:18:41.420 --> 00:18:43.340
I think it's a landmark.

00:18:43.340 --> 00:18:44.660
You know in many
countries the government

00:18:44.660 --> 00:18:45.960
operates broadcasting.

00:18:45.960 --> 00:18:49.120
We've taken a different course
in this country of ours.

00:18:49.120 --> 00:18:51.480
We said that broadcasting
should be in private hands,

00:18:51.480 --> 00:18:55.370
and the commercial side
for private profit.

00:18:55.370 --> 00:18:58.950
But in the public interest and
now we're hoping to develop

00:18:58.950 --> 00:19:04.320
and build an alternative service
for those people who want it.

00:19:04.320 --> 00:19:06.100
&gt;&gt; Newton Minow: Wish I
could be with you in person

00:19:06.100 --> 00:19:10.220
to welcome you to this
important anniversary.

00:19:10.220 --> 00:19:14.230
But in my 90's it's tough
to travel so I'm going

00:19:14.230 --> 00:19:18.280
to communicate a little
history to you this way.

00:19:18.280 --> 00:19:20.310
What I want to do really
is to tell you a couple

00:19:20.310 --> 00:19:23.920
of stories about history.

00:19:25.020 --> 00:19:32.590
My involvement really
stems 61 years ago.

00:19:32.590 --> 00:19:38.190
In 1956 during the
presidential campaign,

00:19:38.190 --> 00:19:42.760
my roommate in the campaign
travels was Robert Kennedy

00:19:42.760 --> 00:19:47.260
who had been sent by the
Kennedy family to learn

00:19:47.260 --> 00:19:49.370
about national campaigns.

00:19:49.370 --> 00:19:51.430
They were looking
forward I think

00:19:51.430 --> 00:19:54.880
to Jack Kennedy becoming
a candidate one day.

00:19:54.880 --> 00:19:57.900
And Bob and I were the same age,

00:19:57.900 --> 00:20:02.250
so we were often
roommates on the travel.

00:20:02.250 --> 00:20:08.020
We got to Springfield, Illinois
and Bob turned to me and he said

00:20:08.020 --> 00:20:11.750
"You and I have heard the
same speech 5,000 times.

00:20:11.750 --> 00:20:13.220
If we've got time to walk

00:20:13.220 --> 00:20:16.670
over to Abraham Lincoln's
house so I could see it.

00:20:16.670 --> 00:20:19.920
I've never been in Springfield
and then we'll get back

00:20:19.920 --> 00:20:21.220
in time to catch the plane".

00:20:21.220 --> 00:20:26.220
I said, "It's only six or
seven minutes, let's go".

00:20:26.220 --> 00:20:28.190
So we went over and
saw Lincoln's house

00:20:28.190 --> 00:20:31.910
and on the way back
Bob Kennedy said to me,

00:20:31.910 --> 00:20:37.770
he said "You know you and I each
have young children, families".

00:20:37.770 --> 00:20:41.020
He said, "When I grew
up", Bob said, he said,

00:20:41.020 --> 00:20:45.140
"I thought there were three
great influences on a child.

00:20:45.140 --> 00:20:50.620
The home, the school
and the church".

00:20:50.620 --> 00:20:53.770
He said, "I realize now raising
my own children there's a

00:20:53.770 --> 00:20:56.950
fourth, and its television".

00:20:56.950 --> 00:20:58.760
He said, "My kids
are on television -

00:20:58.760 --> 00:21:02.170
watching television, they're
fascinated by television.

00:21:02.170 --> 00:21:03.930
Can't we do something
to improve it?

00:21:03.930 --> 00:21:08.320
Make it more educational
and informative for kids"?

00:21:08.320 --> 00:21:11.630
Well that started
a relationship.

00:21:11.630 --> 00:21:17.270
Then four years later when his
brother was elected president

00:21:17.270 --> 00:21:22.590
the day after the election I
got a call saying would I please

00:21:22.590 --> 00:21:25.870
consider joining
the administration.

00:21:25.870 --> 00:21:30.870
And I really said no,
because I couldn't afford it.

00:21:30.870 --> 00:21:33.750
We had young children,
had no money.

00:21:33.750 --> 00:21:37.040
But they pressed and they
knew how interested I was

00:21:37.040 --> 00:21:41.940
in television and they
offered me the job at age 34

00:21:41.940 --> 00:21:45.720
of being Chairman of the Federal
Communications Commission,

00:21:45.720 --> 00:21:48.270
how could I resist that?

00:21:48.270 --> 00:21:50.580
We moved to Washington.

00:21:50.580 --> 00:21:55.950
The FCC had been in
a series of scandals.

00:21:55.950 --> 00:21:58.370
The place was a mess.

00:21:58.370 --> 00:22:01.790
And my job was to clean it up.

00:22:01.790 --> 00:22:04.220
The first day I was on the job,

00:22:04.220 --> 00:22:09.110
the first issue I faced was
senate wanted our testimony

00:22:09.110 --> 00:22:13.250
on a pending bill
to use federal funds

00:22:13.250 --> 00:22:17.660
to help what was then called
educational television.

00:22:17.660 --> 00:22:20.310
My colleagues all
said, in other words

00:22:20.310 --> 00:22:22.790
at that time there were
seven commissioners.

00:22:22.790 --> 00:22:25.680
They all said "No we don't
take a position on that".

00:22:25.680 --> 00:22:28.150
I said, "Wait a minute,
our job here is

00:22:28.150 --> 00:22:31.550
to protect the public
interest, certainly this is

00:22:31.550 --> 00:22:33.350
in the public interest".

00:22:33.350 --> 00:22:39.040
So by a vote 6:1 with my
single descent we testified

00:22:39.040 --> 00:22:40.550
to the senate.

00:22:40.550 --> 00:22:43.720
I was the one who said
that we were very much

00:22:43.720 --> 00:22:46.060
for this legislation.

00:22:46.060 --> 00:22:48.600
And I brought today something

00:22:48.600 --> 00:22:55.100
that long preceded the public
television act of 19 - later -

00:22:55.100 --> 00:22:57.950
this is the first act.

00:22:57.950 --> 00:23:01.740
You see President Kennedy; I'm
sort of hidden in the background

00:23:01.740 --> 00:23:03.910
with the senators
and congressman.

00:23:03.910 --> 00:23:07.630
This was passed and
the President signed it

00:23:07.630 --> 00:23:10.790
on May 1, 1962.

00:23:10.790 --> 00:23:15.390
President John F. Kennedy
signing the TV Educational Bill

00:23:15.390 --> 00:23:21.060
Senate 205 on May 1, 1962.

00:23:21.060 --> 00:23:25.060
The - I was privileged
to do that in person.

00:23:25.060 --> 00:23:33.410
I realized I had come to the FCC
from Chicago where we had WTTW.

00:23:33.410 --> 00:23:36.110
President Kennedy had
come to the White House

00:23:36.110 --> 00:23:37.800
from Boston, that was WGBH.

00:23:37.800 --> 00:23:45.040
Little did we know that there
was no public television station

00:23:45.040 --> 00:23:48.810
in Washington DC, the
capital of the United States,

00:23:48.810 --> 00:23:51.090
not in New York City,
the largest city

00:23:51.090 --> 00:23:53.030
in the United States, not

00:23:53.030 --> 00:23:57.680
in Los Angeles the largest
city on the West Coast.

00:23:57.680 --> 00:24:00.690
There were very few stations.

00:24:00.690 --> 00:24:05.510
So I felt the first thing we
had to do was get more stations

00:24:05.510 --> 00:24:08.820
and the way we did that
was to pass two laws.

00:24:08.820 --> 00:24:11.670
One was called the All
Channel Receiver Act

00:24:11.670 --> 00:24:15.730
which made television
sets have a UHF tuner,

00:24:15.730 --> 00:24:18.940
which enabled news
stations to come on air.

00:24:18.940 --> 00:24:22.380
The other was to provide
some funding for communities

00:24:22.380 --> 00:24:25.660
to build public television
station.

00:24:25.660 --> 00:24:31.370
So, we launched what later
became what is now today the

00:24:31.370 --> 00:24:34.030
Nationwide system.

00:24:34.030 --> 00:24:35.740
We also helped public radio

00:24:35.740 --> 00:24:40.020
which had preceded
television in any way we could.

00:24:41.100 --> 00:24:47.400
I always think that without
a station in New York

00:24:47.400 --> 00:24:50.410
and without a station in Los
Angeles, without a station

00:24:50.410 --> 00:24:53.110
in Washington it
would be impossible

00:24:53.110 --> 00:24:55.630
to build a national system.

00:24:55.630 --> 00:24:56.960
So, I'm very proud of that.

00:24:56.960 --> 00:24:59.670
President Kennedy
was very proud of it.

00:24:59.670 --> 00:25:03.590
And later when I
left the government,

00:25:03.590 --> 00:25:06.270
went home to Chicago,
I became involved

00:25:06.270 --> 00:25:11.930
in our local station WTTW,
later became Chairman of it.

00:25:11.930 --> 00:25:14.950
Public broadcasting
has grown and developed

00:25:14.950 --> 00:25:17.870
because it was bipartisan.

00:25:17.870 --> 00:25:22.370
I tell our board here at WTTW

00:25:22.370 --> 00:25:29.150
that the most important asset
we have is that the word trust.

00:25:29.150 --> 00:25:32.500
It doesn't show up in
a financial statement.

00:25:32.500 --> 00:25:37.960
But everyone trusts us, everyone
trusts PBS, everyone trusts MPR

00:25:37.960 --> 00:25:40.670
as being honest and fair.

00:25:40.670 --> 00:25:44.380
And that's why it's so
important that now we archive

00:25:44.380 --> 00:25:47.490
and preserve the great
things we've done.

00:25:47.490 --> 00:25:50.330
We celebrate the
50th anniversary

00:25:50.330 --> 00:25:54.510
of the Public Television Act.

00:25:54.510 --> 00:26:03.150
[ Applause ]

00:26:03.150 --> 00:26:05.090
&gt;&gt; Karen Cariani: So if the
first panelist could come

00:26:05.090 --> 00:26:07.460
up to the stage,
that would be great.

00:26:07.460 --> 00:26:11.020
In that first piece with Eleanor
Roosevelt was actually thank you

00:26:11.020 --> 00:26:13.270
to Henry Morgenthau, it
was one of the programs

00:26:13.270 --> 00:26:15.510
that he produced for WGBH.

00:26:15.510 --> 00:26:21.160
[ Applause ]

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:23.710
Our first panel is about the
origins of public broadcasting

00:26:23.710 --> 00:26:25.990
and our moderator
will be Cokie Roberts.

00:26:25.990 --> 00:26:28.200
Cokie Roberts is a
political commentator -

00:26:28.200 --> 00:26:29.500
&gt;&gt; Don't do all that.

00:26:29.500 --> 00:26:32.530
&gt;&gt; Karen Cariani: Please, please
I have it all written out.

00:26:32.530 --> 00:26:36.710
Well I'm dying to at least say
she was cited by American Women

00:26:36.710 --> 00:26:39.790
in Radio and Television as
one of the 50 greatest women

00:26:39.790 --> 00:26:41.390
in the history of broadcasting.

00:26:41.390 --> 00:26:43.150
And in 2008 the Library

00:26:43.150 --> 00:26:44.640
of Congress named
her a living legend,

00:26:44.640 --> 00:26:46.510
which we totally agree with.

00:26:46.510 --> 00:26:53.470
[ Applause ]

00:26:53.470 --> 00:26:55.930
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts:
Well I am thrilled

00:26:55.930 --> 00:26:58.060
to be moderating this
panel because this is one

00:26:58.060 --> 00:27:00.970
of the rare times in my
life that I'm the kid.

00:27:07.040 --> 00:27:12.160
I joined NPR 10 years after
the Public Broadcasting Act was

00:27:12.160 --> 00:27:15.210
signed, so I've been
there 40 years.

00:27:15.210 --> 00:27:21.000
And these gents preceded me as -

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:22.300
&gt;&gt; Pre-deceased you?

00:27:22.300 --> 00:27:23.600
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: No, no, no.

00:27:23.600 --> 00:27:25.750
Not - I didn't say deceased.

00:27:25.750 --> 00:27:29.930
They were there at
the beginning.

00:27:29.930 --> 00:27:33.390
And so they each have a
wonderful story to tell.

00:27:33.390 --> 00:27:36.950
Ervin Duggan who is
immediately to my left was

00:27:36.950 --> 00:27:40.470
in the White House at the
time that the bill was passed.

00:27:40.470 --> 00:27:43.050
And then has been very active

00:27:43.050 --> 00:27:49.470
as both an FCC Commissioner
and as head of PBS.

00:27:49.470 --> 00:27:56.120
Nick Johnson was at the FCC
and a troublemaker all the time

00:27:56.120 --> 00:28:01.890
and did PBS programs
as well as columns.

00:28:01.890 --> 00:28:04.510
But was very involved
with public broadcasting

00:28:04.510 --> 00:28:06.490
after he left the FCC.

00:28:06.490 --> 00:28:09.740
Bill Siemering was really
one of the founders of NPR

00:28:09.740 --> 00:28:13.730
and was the creator of
all things considered.

00:28:13.730 --> 00:28:17.410
And Bill is still at it
running developing radio.

00:28:17.410 --> 00:28:20.030
He would be happy to
accept contributions.

00:28:20.030 --> 00:28:24.010
And so I think we'll
just start Ervin with you

00:28:24.010 --> 00:28:25.980
and tell us what it was like.

00:28:25.980 --> 00:28:28.940
How did you get the bill passed?

00:28:28.940 --> 00:28:34.300
&gt;&gt; Ervin Duggan: Well we had
Lyndon Johnson who was a master

00:28:34.300 --> 00:28:38.370
of politics and there
is really a hidden story

00:28:38.370 --> 00:28:41.400
about how this came about.

00:28:41.400 --> 00:28:45.350
And I hope that someday
a historian will delve

00:28:45.350 --> 00:28:48.000
into what we call the
legislative task force.

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:51.540
As much as the great society
legislation including the Public

00:28:51.540 --> 00:28:54.850
Broadcasting Act was crafted
outside the White House

00:28:54.850 --> 00:28:56.320
and even outside Washington.

00:28:56.320 --> 00:28:58.440
The Carnegie Corporation
Commission

00:28:58.440 --> 00:29:00.510
on Public Broadcasting
for example,

00:29:00.510 --> 00:29:03.140
the corporation headed
in New York.

00:29:03.140 --> 00:29:07.120
Johnson decreed and Bill Moyers
was I think the point man

00:29:07.120 --> 00:29:08.420
on this.

00:29:08.420 --> 00:29:11.150
That the great society
legislation should be crafted

00:29:11.150 --> 00:29:14.330
by these legislative task
forces in the universities

00:29:14.330 --> 00:29:16.970
and the foundations
all across the country.

00:29:16.970 --> 00:29:20.690
This really accomplished two
things; it removed the process

00:29:20.690 --> 00:29:25.140
of drafting policy from
the eyes of the press

00:29:25.140 --> 00:29:27.740
and from the atmosphere
of partisan politics.

00:29:27.740 --> 00:29:29.970
It hid the process somewhat -

00:29:29.970 --> 00:29:31.270
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: It was secret.

00:29:31.270 --> 00:29:33.770
&gt;&gt; Ervin Duggan: I would
call a benign secrecy.

00:29:33.770 --> 00:29:35.940
And I don't think the
history has ever been written,

00:29:35.940 --> 00:29:38.020
but if you look at
the 15 members

00:29:38.020 --> 00:29:42.640
of the Carnegie Commission
you see the man JC Kellum

00:29:42.640 --> 00:29:47.290
who headed LBJ's
television stations in Texas.

00:29:47.290 --> 00:29:52.250
You see a Texan Oveta Culp
Hobby, you see the President

00:29:52.250 --> 00:29:53.880
of the United Auto Workers.

00:29:53.880 --> 00:29:59.090
Why? Because Johnson wanted
a tremendous lobbying push

00:29:59.090 --> 00:30:04.330
and if the chairman of the UAW
in Detroit was one of the people

00:30:04.330 --> 00:30:06.880
who crafted the idea
for the Corporation

00:30:06.880 --> 00:30:09.280
for Public Broadcasting.

00:30:09.280 --> 00:30:11.610
That meant that the
immense lobbying power then

00:30:11.610 --> 00:30:13.960
of the United Auto Workers
would be behind the bill

00:30:13.960 --> 00:30:15.440
when it came to the hill.

00:30:15.440 --> 00:30:20.670
So, all of this was a part
of LBJ's legislative genius

00:30:20.670 --> 00:30:24.010
and as I said earlier I hope
someday a historian will delve

00:30:24.010 --> 00:30:26.540
into these legislative task
forces because it seems

00:30:26.540 --> 00:30:27.870
to me one of the most creative

00:30:27.870 --> 00:30:30.960
and really praise worthy
despite the secrecy,

00:30:30.960 --> 00:30:34.650
one of the most praise worthy
things in that history.

00:30:34.650 --> 00:30:37.940
And it's all a part
of a larger story.

00:30:37.940 --> 00:30:41.930
Were it not for the
dark cloud of Vietnam,

00:30:41.930 --> 00:30:44.640
I think the LBJ presidency
would be remembered

00:30:44.640 --> 00:30:49.460
as the new deal is remembered,
as a flowering of creativity

00:30:49.460 --> 00:30:52.200
and positive legislation
on behalf of the well-being

00:30:52.200 --> 00:30:53.500
of the American people.

00:30:53.500 --> 00:30:56.430
I see it - I see the
great society chapter,

00:30:56.430 --> 00:30:59.900
which really ended at about 1967

00:30:59.900 --> 00:31:03.850
after the Congress changed
its composition in '66.

00:31:03.850 --> 00:31:07.240
I see it as the concluding
chapter of the new deal.

00:31:07.240 --> 00:31:10.310
Johnson told Bill Moyers on the
plane coming back from Dallas

00:31:10.310 --> 00:31:12.020
that he wanted to
do all the things

00:31:12.020 --> 00:31:14.990
that Franklin had
been unable to do.

00:31:14.990 --> 00:31:18.830
And so there was this tremendous
election majority that brought

00:31:18.830 --> 00:31:21.760
on the coattails into the
congress a tremendous working

00:31:21.760 --> 00:31:26.790
majority and he used that
majority to pass Medicare,

00:31:26.790 --> 00:31:31.710
more than 60 education bills
including the great corporation

00:31:31.710 --> 00:31:33.770
for public broadcasting bill.

00:31:33.770 --> 00:31:38.040
The other thing and Newton Minow
mentioned it was bipartisanship.

00:31:38.040 --> 00:31:42.130
The commission was made up
of Republicans and Democrats.

00:31:42.130 --> 00:31:46.230
The support on Capitol Hill came
from Republicans and Democrats.

00:31:46.230 --> 00:31:49.680
To this day if you look at
the trustees of the stations

00:31:49.680 --> 00:31:53.000
around the country, when
I was traveling for PBS,

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:55.740
speak to trustees and
fund raising dinners

00:31:55.740 --> 00:31:58.170
around the country
for the stations.

00:31:58.170 --> 00:32:00.760
It was city arts and
business leadership

00:32:00.760 --> 00:32:03.740
of every metropolitan
area in the country made

00:32:03.740 --> 00:32:05.950
up largely of Republicans.

00:32:05.950 --> 00:32:08.100
And what they could
be counted upon

00:32:08.100 --> 00:32:11.950
when these periodic
outbursts of insanity occur

00:32:11.950 --> 00:32:15.660
of misguided people wanting
to wound, they can't kill,

00:32:15.660 --> 00:32:18.420
but wanting to wound
public broadcasting.

00:32:18.420 --> 00:32:20.930
These Republican trustees
from all over the country get

00:32:20.930 --> 00:32:23.100
on the phone and say
"What are you doing"?

00:32:23.100 --> 00:32:24.400
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts:
They're still doing it.

00:32:24.400 --> 00:32:25.700
&gt;&gt; Erven Duggan: They are.

00:32:25.700 --> 00:32:27.000
And we can count on that.

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:29.440
John, Senator Warner then of
the previous Senator Warner

00:32:29.440 --> 00:32:31.040
from Virginia told me once

00:32:31.040 --> 00:32:34.980
that the Congress would never
kill public broadcasting

00:32:34.980 --> 00:32:36.900
because it now is the
only way that a member

00:32:36.900 --> 00:32:38.600
of Congress can get
on television

00:32:38.600 --> 00:32:40.400
in his local community.

00:32:40.400 --> 00:32:44.480
And so I hope that they
are inviting their members

00:32:44.480 --> 00:32:46.750
of Congress to appear
frequently.

00:32:46.750 --> 00:32:49.100
But I went to the White House

00:32:49.100 --> 00:32:53.710
after the great landslide
of '64.

00:32:53.710 --> 00:32:58.100
A really sort of gopher for
Douglas Cader who was in charge

00:32:58.100 --> 00:33:00.190
of shepherding the corporation

00:33:00.190 --> 00:33:04.080
for public broadcasting
into realty.

00:33:04.080 --> 00:33:05.560
And our office in the basement

00:33:05.560 --> 00:33:07.860
of the west wing really
became a sort of workshop

00:33:07.860 --> 00:33:09.160
where the members

00:33:09.160 --> 00:33:11.900
of the Carnegie Commission
first John Gardener

00:33:11.900 --> 00:33:14.610
of the Carnegie Commission
and then Ellen Pfeifer

00:33:14.610 --> 00:33:17.300
around the conference
table in the office.

00:33:17.300 --> 00:33:19.900
I would like to claim
some creative role in this

00:33:19.900 --> 00:33:21.480
but I really was - I came

00:33:21.480 --> 00:33:24.330
to the White House having
been a green reporter

00:33:24.330 --> 00:33:26.440
for the Washington Post;
so I was a kind of gopher.

00:33:26.440 --> 00:33:28.300
But I was also a watcher.

00:33:28.300 --> 00:33:32.700
And what I watched was visionary
people doing amazing things

00:33:32.700 --> 00:33:34.390
and it had a shaping influence.

00:33:34.390 --> 00:33:37.090
It was a great graduate
school of my life.

00:33:37.090 --> 00:33:40.200
And my boss hated
to write speeches

00:33:40.200 --> 00:33:43.400
and because I had been a
newspaper reporter he would

00:33:43.400 --> 00:33:46.190
shove all the speech
writing off to me.

00:33:46.190 --> 00:33:49.890
And when we passed the
legislation and Johnson had

00:33:49.890 --> 00:33:53.990
to make a speech, signing the
bill, I was given the task

00:33:53.990 --> 00:33:55.290
of writing the speech.

00:33:55.290 --> 00:33:58.150
And about 48 hours before the
speech was locked up and sent

00:33:58.150 --> 00:34:00.650
into what was called the
presidents night reading,

00:34:00.650 --> 00:34:05.040
John Gardner by now the
Secretary of HEW called

00:34:05.040 --> 00:34:08.320
and he said "We need
to extend the vision

00:34:08.320 --> 00:34:12.260
of this speech beyond
broadcasting and talk

00:34:12.260 --> 00:34:14.500
about all public media".

00:34:14.500 --> 00:34:19.150
And he didn't even know
what that meant at the time,

00:34:19.150 --> 00:34:22.500
but he suggested language and I
want to quote a little bit of it

00:34:22.500 --> 00:34:24.330
and then I will stop talking.

00:34:24.330 --> 00:34:28.690
Because it is so prestian and so
visionary and so symbolic of all

00:34:28.690 --> 00:34:32.270
that was going on in that
fertile period of our time.

00:34:32.270 --> 00:34:33.930
Right in the middle
of the speech,

00:34:33.930 --> 00:34:36.540
signing the bill
Johnson said these words,

00:34:36.540 --> 00:34:40.470
"I want to create a great
network for knowledge.

00:34:40.470 --> 00:34:44.390
Not just a broadcast system but
one that employs every means

00:34:44.390 --> 00:34:47.450
of sending and storing
information.

00:34:47.450 --> 00:34:50.210
Think of the lives
that this could change.

00:34:50.210 --> 00:34:53.580
The student in a small
college could tap the resources

00:34:53.580 --> 00:34:55.420
of a great university.

00:34:55.420 --> 00:34:57.030
The country doctor
could get help

00:34:57.030 --> 00:35:00.240
from a distant laboratory
or teaching hospital.

00:35:00.240 --> 00:35:02.800
A scholar in Atlanta
might draw instantly

00:35:02.800 --> 00:35:05.110
on a library in New York.

00:35:05.110 --> 00:35:08.250
Now all this is 30 years
before the internet.

00:35:08.250 --> 00:35:12.080
But suddenly the chrysalis
is beginning to form.

00:35:12.080 --> 00:35:15.730
And the creative vision of
a network for knowledge.

00:35:15.730 --> 00:35:20.420
The stations of NPR and PBS
have not always been receptive,

00:35:20.420 --> 00:35:22.560
I'm sorry to say
to new technology.

00:35:22.560 --> 00:35:24.650
They are more on the
broadcast technology

00:35:24.650 --> 00:35:26.980
and a station manager once
said to me when we were trying

00:35:26.980 --> 00:35:31.700
to create PBS.org, "Every hour
that a viewer spends looking

00:35:31.700 --> 00:35:33.910
at a computer screen is an hour

00:35:33.910 --> 00:35:35.820
that he is not watching
my station".

00:35:35.820 --> 00:35:39.190
And so there's been
a certain hostility.

00:35:39.190 --> 00:35:43.140
But we know that right
there in the womb,

00:35:43.140 --> 00:35:44.900
when the bill was
signed the President

00:35:44.900 --> 00:35:47.310
of the United States was
envisioning something called

00:35:47.310 --> 00:35:49.370
networks for knowledge.

00:35:49.370 --> 00:35:53.130
May that increase, may it
grow, may the commitment

00:35:53.130 --> 00:35:54.970
of all public broadcasters

00:35:54.970 --> 00:35:58.460
to public media flourish
in the future.

00:35:58.460 --> 00:36:00.190
But it was great fun to be

00:36:00.190 --> 00:36:02.820
in on the beginning though
I can't claim anything other

00:36:02.820 --> 00:36:04.120
than a gopher's role.

00:36:04.120 --> 00:36:06.050
But what a great thing we did.

00:36:06.050 --> 00:36:08.370
It is now embedded
in the culture.

00:36:08.370 --> 00:36:13.680
It is a part of American life
in the way that Medicare,

00:36:13.680 --> 00:36:17.510
other great achievements
at that time are sewn

00:36:17.510 --> 00:36:19.520
into the fabric of
American life.

00:36:19.520 --> 00:36:22.830
And heroes of that
movement are in this room,

00:36:22.830 --> 00:36:25.510
may their tribe increase.

00:36:25.510 --> 00:36:33.040
[ Applause ]

00:36:33.040 --> 00:36:34.670
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: So
Nick, what was the role

00:36:34.670 --> 00:36:37.160
of the FCC in all of this?

00:36:37.160 --> 00:36:38.460
&gt;&gt; Nick Johnson: Well I would

00:36:38.460 --> 00:36:40.470
like to go back a
little further.

00:36:40.470 --> 00:36:42.380
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: Okay.

00:36:42.380 --> 00:36:44.670
&gt;&gt; Nick Johnson: Since
I believe Mr. Morgenthau

00:36:44.670 --> 00:36:55.130
and I are amongst the more - age
of experience you know and so -

00:36:55.130 --> 00:36:56.690
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: The wise men.

00:36:56.690 --> 00:37:01.270
&gt;&gt; Nick Johnson: Well not
necessarily as we often see,

00:37:01.270 --> 00:37:06.770
but to go back to
the 18th century.

00:37:06.770 --> 00:37:11.410
Because there are other
presidents involved

00:37:11.410 --> 00:37:14.350
in this besides Lyndon Johnson.

00:37:14.350 --> 00:37:18.000
With regard to whom I might add
an anecdote that he brought me

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:22.830
in February of '64 and
shortly thereafter a memo went

00:37:22.830 --> 00:37:25.100
out to all presidential
appointees,

00:37:25.100 --> 00:37:28.340
you may recall this
saying "I want you

00:37:28.340 --> 00:37:31.820
to tell me what you think
would be in the best interest

00:37:31.820 --> 00:37:36.160
of our nation with the area for
which you have responsibility".

00:37:36.160 --> 00:37:40.210
And in my case at
that time it was ports

00:37:40.210 --> 00:37:42.010
and ship building and shipping.

00:37:42.010 --> 00:37:45.000
He made me Maritime
Administrator,

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:48.130
just exactly what
you would think a boy

00:37:48.130 --> 00:37:52.070
from Iowa would -
the coasts of Iowa.

00:37:52.070 --> 00:37:57.330
The coasts of Iowa and - should
the experience be limited

00:37:57.330 --> 00:38:02.290
to operating a canoe on the Iowa
River but not very successfully.

00:38:02.290 --> 00:38:05.630
Something that thankfully the
commerce committee found fully

00:38:05.630 --> 00:38:08.950
adequate to justify
the appointment.

00:38:08.950 --> 00:38:15.250
But I think that's another thing
to say about Lyndon Johnson.

00:38:15.250 --> 00:38:19.930
That compared with
other presidents perhaps

00:38:19.930 --> 00:38:23.450
who will go unnamed, that there
would actually be that focus

00:38:23.450 --> 00:38:24.980
on what's in the best
national interest.

00:38:24.980 --> 00:38:28.490
But I want to go
back to Madison,

00:38:28.490 --> 00:38:31.690
who I just learned today is
referred to by those who work

00:38:31.690 --> 00:38:35.770
at the Library of
Congress as Jimmy Madison.

00:38:35.770 --> 00:38:39.490
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: He was
Jimmy, spelled J-E-M-M-Y.

00:38:39.490 --> 00:38:41.140
&gt;&gt; Nick Johnson: Is that
right, was it James Madison?

00:38:41.140 --> 00:38:42.440
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: Jemmy.

00:38:42.440 --> 00:38:43.740
&gt;&gt; Nick Johnson: I'll be darned.

00:38:43.740 --> 00:38:45.040
What, did your father
tell you that?

00:38:45.040 --> 00:38:47.230
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts:
No I write history -

00:38:47.230 --> 00:38:49.480
&gt;&gt; Nick Johnson: He was a
great - they would be so proud

00:38:49.480 --> 00:38:51.740
of you now and everything
you've done.

00:38:51.740 --> 00:38:53.570
No, I'm serious.

00:38:53.570 --> 00:38:56.620
Hale and Lindy Boggs,
great people.

00:38:56.620 --> 00:39:03.500
Well anyhow I wanted to
go back to Jemmy Madison,

00:39:03.500 --> 00:39:05.720
however you spell his name.

00:39:05.720 --> 00:39:07.690
And there is an inscription
as you came

00:39:07.690 --> 00:39:09.640
into this building
you may have noticed.

00:39:09.640 --> 00:39:12.000
And I'm going to link this
up with Thomas Jefferson

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:17.020
and then ultimately with public
broadcasting and try to do it

00:39:17.020 --> 00:39:19.550
in five minutes or less
if that's all right.

00:39:19.550 --> 00:39:20.850
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: All right.

00:39:20.850 --> 00:39:22.150
&gt;&gt; Nick Johnson: Yeah,
let's less would be better.

00:39:22.150 --> 00:39:23.450
Less is more.

00:39:23.450 --> 00:39:27.360
Yeah. And it contains
this line "People who mean

00:39:27.360 --> 00:39:32.040
to be their own governor's must
arm themselves with the power

00:39:32.040 --> 00:39:34.260
which knowledge gives".

00:39:34.260 --> 00:39:36.430
That's Madison's quote.

00:39:36.430 --> 00:39:39.490
Jefferson and many
of you may know this,

00:39:39.490 --> 00:39:43.940
but when writing his own
epitaph chose to be remembered

00:39:43.940 --> 00:39:48.800
as the father of the University
of Virginia and made no mention

00:39:48.800 --> 00:39:52.730
of the fact that he'd been
President of the United States.

00:39:52.730 --> 00:39:55.050
Now this is very
significant I think

00:39:55.050 --> 00:40:00.490
because what these folks
were doing was recognizing

00:40:00.490 --> 00:40:03.510
and establishing
and making efforts

00:40:03.510 --> 00:40:08.830
to maintain fundamental
pillars of democracy.

00:40:08.830 --> 00:40:12.200
Many of which have
always been and continue

00:40:12.200 --> 00:40:15.430
to be today under attack.

00:40:15.430 --> 00:40:18.710
One obviously is
extending the franchise

00:40:18.710 --> 00:40:24.030
from originally white
male land owners over 21

00:40:24.030 --> 00:40:26.890
to where now we even
let women vote.

00:40:26.890 --> 00:40:28.880
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: Took a while.

00:40:28.880 --> 00:40:31.630
&gt;&gt; Nick Johnson: It
did take a long while.

00:40:31.630 --> 00:40:38.770
And 18 year olds,
but then the addition

00:40:38.770 --> 00:40:44.400
of free public education,
a fundamental element

00:40:44.400 --> 00:40:47.260
and pillar of democracy.

00:40:47.260 --> 00:40:52.590
And then the idea of
independent media protected

00:40:52.590 --> 00:40:56.160
by the First Amendment.

00:40:56.160 --> 00:41:01.120
For Jefferson also said
famously as you all know

00:41:01.120 --> 00:41:03.920
and writing Edward
Carrington, "Were it left to me

00:41:03.920 --> 00:41:07.610
to decide whether we should have
a government without newspapers

00:41:07.610 --> 00:41:10.960
or newspapers without a
government I should not hesitate

00:41:10.960 --> 00:41:13.830
a moment to prefer the latter".

00:41:13.830 --> 00:41:16.520
And then went on in the
next sentence to say,

00:41:16.520 --> 00:41:19.670
"But I should mean that every
person should receive those

00:41:19.670 --> 00:41:22.630
papers and be capable
of reading them".

00:41:22.630 --> 00:41:29.530
Again, tying it to education,
subsequently we added the idea

00:41:29.530 --> 00:41:35.410
of free public libraries where
every American could have access

00:41:35.410 --> 00:41:38.270
to the resources of kings.

00:41:38.270 --> 00:41:42.810
And indeed, this library was
contributed to by Jefferson

00:41:42.810 --> 00:41:47.370
in 1815 as you probably know.

00:41:47.370 --> 00:41:52.950
Something that is often not
thought about in this context

00:41:52.950 --> 00:41:54.930
but relates to what
John Gardener -

00:41:54.930 --> 00:41:58.200
incidentally he wrote two
wonderful books - he wrote a lot

00:41:58.200 --> 00:42:03.080
of stuff but that our paperback
books, one called Excellence,

00:42:03.080 --> 00:42:06.530
one called Self-Renewal,
which I think are always worth

00:42:06.530 --> 00:42:10.170
re-reading at least
every 20 or 30 years.

00:42:11.790 --> 00:42:20.630
Because the other thing we did
was to establish reduced rates

00:42:20.630 --> 00:42:24.530
for sending newspapers
and books and magazines

00:42:24.530 --> 00:42:26.640
through the postal system.

00:42:26.640 --> 00:42:33.930
Subsidizing what was at that
time the communications network

00:42:33.930 --> 00:42:39.050
of the 19th century
was the post office.

00:42:39.050 --> 00:42:42.880
And then we added telegraph
and telephone and so on.

00:42:42.880 --> 00:42:50.520
But that was how it began and as
all of you know the early time

00:42:50.520 --> 00:42:54.260
of radio and I want to tell
just one story about Iowa City

00:42:54.260 --> 00:42:55.610
and then I'm done, is that okay?

00:42:55.610 --> 00:42:57.500
Yeah, all right.

00:42:57.500 --> 00:43:03.890
The early days of radio
involved numerous,

00:43:03.890 --> 00:43:08.990
72 in the very early days,
educational institutions

00:43:08.990 --> 00:43:12.460
that did not only the
technological work

00:43:12.460 --> 00:43:15.320
of creating this box in
which little people lived

00:43:15.320 --> 00:43:20.250
and could talk, but also the
programming and the focus

00:43:20.250 --> 00:43:25.210
on the use of this as an
instrument of education.

00:43:25.210 --> 00:43:29.640
Iowa City, Iowa from whence
I come, a city designated

00:43:29.640 --> 00:43:33.170
by the United Nations as
one of three global cities

00:43:33.170 --> 00:43:38.800
of literature, was created the
first educational radio station

00:43:38.800 --> 00:43:40.270
west of the Mississippi.

00:43:40.270 --> 00:43:44.410
That was in 1911, all right?

00:43:44.410 --> 00:43:47.750
So this goes back before 1967,

00:43:47.750 --> 00:43:51.860
for those who are younger
among us here today.

00:43:53.040 --> 00:43:58.900
In 1971 WSUI became
a charter member

00:43:58.900 --> 00:44:03.550
of NPR, one of the early few.

00:44:03.550 --> 00:44:08.780
And one of the 90 stations to
carry the inaugural broadcast

00:44:08.780 --> 00:44:11.520
of Bills, All things considered.

00:44:11.520 --> 00:44:17.770
In 1916 it began transmitting
educational content,

00:44:17.770 --> 00:44:21.810
ultimately including my
father's lectures in the 1940's.

00:44:21.810 --> 00:44:24.440
By the last 1920's,
remember this,

00:44:24.440 --> 00:44:30.890
1920's they had educational
television broadcasting

00:44:30.890 --> 00:44:36.440
television images of
classroom content.

00:44:36.440 --> 00:44:39.710
A station that would
ultimately be one

00:44:39.710 --> 00:44:44.220
of the founding stations
creating Iowa Public Television

00:44:44.220 --> 00:44:47.510
and thus end the
reading for today.

00:44:47.510 --> 00:44:56.100
[ Applause ]

00:44:56.100 --> 00:44:59.280
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: Well Bill,
that nicely gets us to you.

00:44:59.280 --> 00:45:02.610
The fact is that we heard
all about educational TV

00:45:02.610 --> 00:45:07.000
and even though radio came
before it was something

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:09.900
of an afterthought in terms
of public broadcasting.

00:45:09.900 --> 00:45:11.470
And you are the person
who changed that.

00:45:11.470 --> 00:45:13.120
&gt;&gt; Bill Siemering: It
was actually Scotch taped

00:45:13.120 --> 00:45:16.620
at the last minute
onto the legislation.

00:45:16.620 --> 00:45:18.320
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: And radio.

00:45:18.320 --> 00:45:22.620
It's like the Civil Rights
Law putting "and sex" in

00:45:22.620 --> 00:45:24.690
and changing women's
lives forever.

00:45:24.690 --> 00:45:26.150
But so -

00:45:26.150 --> 00:45:31.020
&gt;&gt; Nick Johnson: If I can note,
I took the position at that time

00:45:31.020 --> 00:45:35.500
that we ought to forget about
television and start with radio.

00:45:35.500 --> 00:45:39.790
You've got literally 10
times more for your dollar

00:45:39.790 --> 00:45:41.670
with radio than with television.

00:45:41.670 --> 00:45:42.970
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts:
That's still true.

00:45:42.970 --> 00:45:44.270
&gt;&gt; Nick Johnson:
Really, that's right.

00:45:44.270 --> 00:45:49.370
Build a really strong national
political base in support

00:45:49.370 --> 00:45:53.470
of public radio that would
then clammer and demand

00:45:53.470 --> 00:45:55.840
of Congress Public Television.

00:45:55.840 --> 00:45:59.330
But to start with Public
Television and under fund it,

00:45:59.330 --> 00:46:04.000
I didn't think was the
right political move, Bill.

00:46:05.510 --> 00:46:08.040
[ Applause ]

00:46:08.040 --> 00:46:09.340
&gt;&gt; Bill Siemering:
Because you're all,

00:46:09.340 --> 00:46:12.500
or many of you are
historians and we've -

00:46:12.500 --> 00:46:16.540
the history of the university
is I'd like to just go back.

00:46:16.540 --> 00:46:18.730
A couple weeks ago I
was out in Madison,

00:46:18.730 --> 00:46:21.280
Wisconsin celebrating
the 100th anniversary

00:46:21.280 --> 00:46:22.920
of the oldest station in the -

00:46:22.920 --> 00:46:25.600
the oldest educational
station, continuous -

00:46:25.600 --> 00:46:27.680
&gt;&gt; Nick Johnson: But
east of the Mississippi.

00:46:27.680 --> 00:46:29.200
&gt;&gt; Bill Siemering: That's right.

00:46:29.200 --> 00:46:33.530
We can arm wrestle
about this one.

00:46:33.530 --> 00:46:36.540
And tracing this back
to the university

00:46:36.540 --> 00:46:39.060
because I think it
raises a good point.

00:46:39.060 --> 00:46:44.130
About 11 years before radio
was invented the university

00:46:44.130 --> 00:46:46.310
president of [Inaudible]
at Wisconsin said,

00:46:46.310 --> 00:46:49.190
"I want the beneficence
of the university to be

00:46:49.190 --> 00:46:51.690
in every home in the state".

00:46:51.690 --> 00:46:55.260
And it became the motto of
the so called Wisconsin idea.

00:46:55.260 --> 00:46:58.870
The boundaries of the campus
are the boundaries of the state.

00:46:58.870 --> 00:47:03.720
And so that was the idea of
extending those resources.

00:47:03.720 --> 00:47:07.410
And at that time the
very first broadcast east

00:47:07.410 --> 00:47:08.710
of the Mississippi

00:47:08.710 --> 00:47:13.110
and educational station
was information to farmers,

00:47:13.110 --> 00:47:18.760
weather information, 60%
were - 61% literacy rate

00:47:18.760 --> 00:47:21.020
at that time in Wisconsin.

00:47:21.020 --> 00:47:25.280
And as just a side
bar Cokie mentioned

00:47:25.280 --> 00:47:27.980
that I have an organization
developing radio partners

00:47:27.980 --> 00:47:31.200
and we're working in Zambia
to improve the weather

00:47:31.200 --> 00:47:35.930
and farming information where
the literacy rate is 61%.

00:47:35.930 --> 00:47:39.050
So, radio continues
to be used this way.

00:47:39.050 --> 00:47:44.390
So anyway, that idea continued

00:47:44.390 --> 00:47:47.510
and so the beginnings
really were there

00:47:47.510 --> 00:47:52.930
and I started my career in
public radio as an engineer

00:47:52.930 --> 00:47:57.470
in 1952 working my way through
the University of Wisconsin.

00:47:57.470 --> 00:48:03.140
So, that's where I - my roots
are there and there was a center

00:48:03.140 --> 00:48:08.090
for innovation and
audio invitation,

00:48:08.090 --> 00:48:10.040
innovation and so on.

00:48:10.040 --> 00:48:15.030
They're producing radio
plays by David Mamet

00:48:15.030 --> 00:48:18.010
and Arthur Colpert and so on.

00:48:18.010 --> 00:48:24.750
Anyway, it was that
experience that informed me.

00:48:24.750 --> 00:48:26.820
I left there and was in Buffalo

00:48:26.820 --> 00:48:31.430
and developed a store front
center broadcast facility

00:48:31.430 --> 00:48:33.420
in the heart of the
black community

00:48:33.420 --> 00:48:37.320
where 27 hours a week
came from that source.

00:48:37.320 --> 00:48:40.410
So I was, at that time giving
voice or helping give voice

00:48:40.410 --> 00:48:43.420
to folks that had no - there
were no people of color really

00:48:43.420 --> 00:48:46.550
in media at that time.

00:48:46.550 --> 00:48:49.490
And we had discussions
about race on air,

00:48:49.490 --> 00:48:52.980
what is it like to be an
African American in our society.

00:48:52.980 --> 00:48:54.280
I had done some -

00:48:54.280 --> 00:48:55.580
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: What
year are we in now?

00:48:55.580 --> 00:49:00.510
&gt;&gt; Bill Siemering:
We're in 1964 and 1964.

00:49:00.510 --> 00:49:02.970
And I did a series on
the Iroquois Confederacy,

00:49:02.970 --> 00:49:06.860
some portraits of that - of that
culture, Nation within a Nation.

00:49:06.860 --> 00:49:11.140
Anyway, so when I was tasked as
a member of the founding board

00:49:11.140 --> 00:49:16.430
to write the mission statement I
felt very strongly about radio,

00:49:16.430 --> 00:49:18.650
that our first meeting
with a corporation

00:49:18.650 --> 00:49:19.950
for public broadcasting.

00:49:19.950 --> 00:49:22.010
I was on the radio
advisory committee.

00:49:22.010 --> 00:49:24.890
And John Macy said to us,
"Well you know, of course,

00:49:24.890 --> 00:49:26.790
television has to go first".

00:49:26.790 --> 00:49:29.990
Of course, television
always goes first.

00:49:29.990 --> 00:49:36.750
And I was really always
frustrated by this of course,

00:49:36.750 --> 00:49:39.260
because - so I started a program

00:49:39.260 --> 00:49:40.970
in Buffalo called
"This is radio".

00:49:40.970 --> 00:49:45.380
This is radio dammit,
pay attention.

00:49:45.380 --> 00:49:47.790
Look what - listen
to what radio can do.

00:49:47.790 --> 00:49:51.120
I'm still saying the same
thing in development.

00:49:51.120 --> 00:49:57.420
Anyway, so the task was to try
to, for me, differentiate it

00:49:57.420 --> 00:50:01.010
from the educational radio,
from commercial radio,

00:50:01.010 --> 00:50:04.280
from PBS that was of
course up and running.

00:50:04.280 --> 00:50:08.870
To capitalize on the strengths
of radio as a sound medium,

00:50:08.870 --> 00:50:12.660
getting out of the
studio, telling stories.

00:50:12.660 --> 00:50:18.180
And to be somewhat
aspirational but also practical.

00:50:18.180 --> 00:50:20.400
So that was what
I was trying to do

00:50:20.400 --> 00:50:22.060
when I wrote the
mission statement.

00:50:22.060 --> 00:50:28.410
If you don't mind I'll just
read a few paragraphs of that.

00:50:28.410 --> 00:50:31.610
National Public Radio
will serve the individual.

00:50:31.610 --> 00:50:33.900
It will promote personal growth.

00:50:33.900 --> 00:50:37.100
It will regard individual
differences with respect

00:50:37.100 --> 00:50:40.940
and joy, rather than
division and hate.

00:50:40.940 --> 00:50:44.530
It will celebrate the human
experiences infinitely varied

00:50:44.530 --> 00:50:45.830
rather than vacuous [Inaudible].

00:50:45.830 --> 00:50:49.090
It will encourage
a sense of active,

00:50:49.090 --> 00:50:51.680
constructive participation
rather

00:50:51.680 --> 00:50:54.030
than apathetic helplessness.

00:50:54.030 --> 00:50:57.130
The total service
should be trustworthy,

00:50:57.130 --> 00:50:59.420
enhanced intellectual
development.

00:50:59.420 --> 00:51:04.630
Expand knowledge, deepen
oral aesthetic enjoyment,

00:51:04.630 --> 00:51:09.120
increase the pleasure of living
in a pluralistic society.

00:51:09.120 --> 00:51:11.440
And result in a service
to listeners,

00:51:11.440 --> 00:51:15.090
which makes them more
responsive informed human beings

00:51:15.090 --> 00:51:17.610
and intelligent responsible
citizens

00:51:17.610 --> 00:51:20.530
of their communities
and the world.

00:51:20.530 --> 00:51:23.130
And then in the first
description of what became

00:51:23.130 --> 00:51:25.740
of all things considered I said

00:51:25.740 --> 00:51:28.500
that it would not substitute
superficial blindness

00:51:28.500 --> 00:51:33.080
for genuine diversity of
regions, values and cultural

00:51:33.080 --> 00:51:37.230
and ethnic minorities, which
comprise American society.

00:51:37.230 --> 00:51:42.610
It would speak with many
voices and many dialects.

00:51:42.610 --> 00:51:47.120
The editorial attitude would
be that of inquiry, curiosity,

00:51:47.120 --> 00:51:51.050
concern for the quality
of life, critical,

00:51:51.050 --> 00:51:54.650
problem solving and life loving.

00:51:54.650 --> 00:51:57.050
The listener should come
to rely upon it as a source

00:51:57.050 --> 00:51:59.280
of information of consequence.

00:51:59.280 --> 00:52:01.220
That having listened
has made a difference

00:52:01.220 --> 00:52:04.560
in their attitude toward their
environment and themselves.

00:52:04.560 --> 00:52:07.810
And then the concluding
paragraph for now,

00:52:07.810 --> 00:52:12.400
philosophically time is measured
by the intensity of experience,

00:52:12.400 --> 00:52:14.050
waiting for a bus and walking

00:52:14.050 --> 00:52:17.380
through an art gallery may
occupy the same duration of time

00:52:17.380 --> 00:52:20.910
but not the same
time experience.

00:52:20.910 --> 00:52:23.190
Listeners should feel
that the time spent

00:52:23.190 --> 00:52:28.350
with NPR was among their most
rewarding in media contact.

00:52:28.350 --> 00:52:32.750
National Public Radio will not
regard its audience as a market

00:52:32.750 --> 00:52:35.670
or in terms of its
disposable income,

00:52:35.670 --> 00:52:39.710
but as curious complex
individuals who are looking

00:52:39.710 --> 00:52:46.510
for some understanding, meaning
and joy in the human experience.

