Robert MacNeil Report and I was
the Washington Correspondent

01:01:40.180 --> 01:01:43.690
and then it became
-my mother interceded

01:01:43.690 --> 01:01:46.210
and it became the
McNeil Lehrer Report.

01:01:46.210 --> 01:01:49.530
It was one story a day for
30 minutes when we started

01:01:49.530 --> 01:01:51.760
and then - that was '75.

01:01:51.760 --> 01:01:54.500
And then in '83 it went to an
hour, became the news hour.

01:01:54.500 --> 01:01:55.800
&gt;&gt; Judy Woodruff: And
that's where I want to bring

01:01:55.800 --> 01:01:58.680
in Sharon Rockefeller because
Sharon you were already active

01:01:58.680 --> 01:02:01.040
in public broadcasting
and you knew what Jim

01:02:01.040 --> 01:02:02.910
and Robert were trying to do.

01:02:02.910 --> 01:02:06.240
What were you up against when
they tried to go to an hour?

01:02:06.240 --> 01:02:09.480
&gt;&gt; Sharon Rockefeller: The
stations in many senses.

01:02:09.480 --> 01:02:12.080
I was working - I was familiar

01:02:12.080 --> 01:02:14.440
with West Virginia Educational
Broadcasting Authority,

01:02:14.440 --> 01:02:15.970
not on the board at that time

01:02:15.970 --> 01:02:17.440
because my husband
wasn't governor.

01:02:17.440 --> 01:02:19.710
And that was a gubernatorial
appointment.

01:02:19.710 --> 01:02:25.070
At the time actually I asked
for one thing from my husband,

01:02:25.070 --> 01:02:30.170
"Can I be appointed to the
WVEBA" and he said, "Yes".

01:02:30.170 --> 01:02:33.070
And no one ever thought
twice about it,

01:02:33.070 --> 01:02:34.570
but that was my training.

01:02:34.570 --> 01:02:36.800
That's where I learned.

01:02:36.800 --> 01:02:39.500
But the Watergate
hearings actually,

01:02:39.500 --> 01:02:41.720
I watched every single
day, all day long.

01:02:41.720 --> 01:02:45.940
Jay had lost an election by the
largest margin in the history

01:02:45.940 --> 01:02:50.740
of the state in 1972, we
had four years in exile

01:02:50.740 --> 01:02:54.430
in Buckhannon, West Virginia,
three hours north of Charleston,

01:02:54.430 --> 01:02:56.730
three hours south of Pittsburgh.

01:02:56.730 --> 01:02:59.360
But an hour and a half from
the Morgantown West Virginia

01:02:59.360 --> 01:03:01.330
University Station.

01:03:01.330 --> 01:03:04.280
So, when the Watergate
hearings were on in that,

01:03:04.280 --> 01:03:08.060
I could not receive the
Washington Post by mail

01:03:08.060 --> 01:03:12.060
until two days after
it was published.

01:03:12.060 --> 01:03:14.600
I started watching full time.

01:03:14.600 --> 01:03:17.710
My kids were watching
Sesame Street.

01:03:17.710 --> 01:03:21.710
I loved history, Adam's
Chronical, Masterpiece, but news

01:03:21.710 --> 01:03:25.610
and public affairs was
my main attraction.

01:03:25.610 --> 01:03:27.510
It was what we had to offer.

01:03:27.510 --> 01:03:32.440
We at that point was
little old public television

01:03:32.440 --> 01:03:35.790
and it was the turnaround.

01:03:35.790 --> 01:03:39.150
I also came on the WETA
board at the same time

01:03:39.150 --> 01:03:41.080
through another vehicle,
a friend of mine

01:03:41.080 --> 01:03:44.470
on the Stanford University
Board, which had one woman

01:03:44.470 --> 01:03:47.040
on the board and I
was taking her place.

01:03:47.040 --> 01:03:52.080
She was the founder of - this
is in the 70's, lest we forget.

01:03:52.080 --> 01:03:55.380
She was the founder of
KQED, Caroline Charles,

01:03:55.380 --> 01:03:56.680
so she said "Where do you live"?

01:03:56.680 --> 01:04:00.650
I said, "West Virginia",
San Francisco, thank you.

01:04:00.650 --> 01:04:02.210
She said, "Where's that"?

01:04:02.210 --> 01:04:06.560
She said, "Is that
near the Dakotas"?

01:04:06.560 --> 01:04:10.520
"Is it near the Carolinas".

01:04:10.520 --> 01:04:13.070
But she knew Mrs. Campbell

01:04:13.070 --> 01:04:16.340
and she called her
immediately and I was 29.

01:04:16.340 --> 01:04:19.540
She said "You have to
talk to this young woman".

01:04:19.540 --> 01:04:21.060
I didn't know what about.

01:04:21.060 --> 01:04:24.790
But Mrs. Campbell called me
in a very authoritarian way,

01:04:24.790 --> 01:04:28.810
"You must come to Washington
right now", which I did.

01:04:28.810 --> 01:04:32.090
I've always taken my orders
from Elizabeth Campbell.

01:04:32.090 --> 01:04:35.520
And that's how I got
involved with WETA.

01:04:35.520 --> 01:04:38.740
So I had a very small
[Inaudible] and at

01:04:38.740 --> 01:04:43.730
that point WETA was not
as wealthy as it is today.

01:04:43.730 --> 01:04:48.020
It had a budget of 4 million;
now we're at 97 million.

01:04:48.020 --> 01:04:50.030
But we've clawed our way up.

01:04:50.030 --> 01:04:52.030
And it's really through
news and public affairs.

01:04:52.030 --> 01:04:56.320
The Watergate hearings put
public television on the map

01:04:56.320 --> 01:05:01.170
and WETA and the News Hour,
which came about in 1983

01:05:01.170 --> 01:05:03.920
because we thought we
should be the first,

01:05:03.920 --> 01:05:07.550
and that all stations were
going to go to one hour of news.

01:05:07.550 --> 01:05:13.720
In fact, they never did, we did
but we won, if you recall Robin

01:05:13.720 --> 01:05:17.830
and Jim and I went around to
visit stations, speak to them

01:05:17.830 --> 01:05:21.730
and they didn't really want it.

01:05:21.730 --> 01:05:23.370
We did not want it -

01:05:23.370 --> 01:05:26.650
&gt;&gt; Jim Lehrer: We divided
up - we divided up the 300

01:05:26.650 --> 01:05:29.610
and some public television
stations

01:05:29.610 --> 01:05:34.730
and we called every station
manager or program manager

01:05:34.730 --> 01:05:40.190
because Irv's successor
as president of PBS said

01:05:40.190 --> 01:05:42.720
"It's a great idea
to go to an hour,

01:05:42.720 --> 01:05:44.610
but I don't have
the power to do it.

01:05:44.610 --> 01:05:46.360
You're going to have to
get the stations to -

01:05:46.360 --> 01:05:47.660
get the stations to do it".

01:05:47.660 --> 01:05:50.340
So we physically called
them on the phone,

01:05:50.340 --> 01:05:52.210
and then there was a vote.

01:05:52.210 --> 01:05:54.500
We won by six votes.

01:05:54.500 --> 01:05:59.150
To go to an hour and
out of 300 and some

01:05:59.150 --> 01:06:02.230
and that felt like,
oh never mind.

01:06:02.230 --> 01:06:04.530
&gt;&gt; Sharon Rockefeller:
All you need is one more

01:06:04.530 --> 01:06:05.830
than the other guy.

01:06:05.830 --> 01:06:07.130
&gt;&gt; Jim Lehrer: Democracy won.

01:06:07.130 --> 01:06:08.430
&gt;&gt; Judy Woodruff: And as
they say the rest is history.

01:06:08.430 --> 01:06:12.410
So, Dick Cavett, while all this
was going on in the daily news,

01:06:12.410 --> 01:06:15.970
daily journalism world, you
had a very successful career

01:06:15.970 --> 01:06:18.890
as an interviewer in
commercial television.

01:06:18.890 --> 01:06:22.040
What was the appeal
of public television?

01:06:22.040 --> 01:06:25.490
&gt;&gt; Dick Cavett: Well I noticed
in something about today

01:06:25.490 --> 01:06:28.030
that among the things
that I thought might come

01:06:28.030 --> 01:06:32.750
up would be the question
of why I moved my show

01:06:32.750 --> 01:06:37.030
from network television to PBS.

01:06:37.030 --> 01:06:38.830
I was fired.

01:06:38.830 --> 01:06:44.060
[ Laughter ]

01:06:44.060 --> 01:06:45.880
I hope that's not too
loquacious a way to put it

01:06:45.880 --> 01:06:49.320
but that's pretty
much what happened.

01:06:49.320 --> 01:06:54.280
So opened the door, paved the
way, whatever cliché you prefer.

01:06:54.280 --> 01:07:00.790
It was a wonderful change
with network television.

01:07:00.790 --> 01:07:02.820
I was of course delighted
to get a show.

01:07:02.820 --> 01:07:06.060
Terrified and very
nervous at first.

01:07:06.060 --> 01:07:08.330
And the trouble there,
the kind that would come

01:07:08.330 --> 01:07:12.350
up on network so-called
non-public television

01:07:12.350 --> 01:07:15.270
so to speak starting
on the first day.

01:07:15.270 --> 01:07:19.110
I thought I had a
wonderful show,

01:07:19.110 --> 01:07:23.230
Present them is my first show
to be played about a week later.

01:07:23.230 --> 01:07:27.000
Mohammad Ali, Gore Vidal

01:07:27.000 --> 01:07:32.710
and Angela Lansbury did a
wonderful talking lively show.

01:07:32.710 --> 01:07:36.500
And foolish boy from Nebraska
that I am, I went backstage

01:07:36.500 --> 01:07:41.000
to be congratulated by
ABC Vice President sort

01:07:41.000 --> 01:07:43.760
of shepherded the show.

01:07:43.760 --> 01:07:46.170
And I saw his expression
didn't seem appropriate

01:07:46.170 --> 01:07:47.860
for a show that he loved.

01:07:47.860 --> 01:07:54.880
I think it was worded "Who the",
let's say hell gives a damn,

01:07:54.880 --> 01:07:59.210
that's a better word
"what Mohammad Ali

01:07:59.210 --> 01:08:03.330
and Gore Vidal think
about Vietnam"?

01:08:03.330 --> 01:08:06.660
Well obviously that had come up.

01:08:06.660 --> 01:08:10.010
Second brilliant part
of his reaction was

01:08:10.010 --> 01:08:13.350
"We can't really air that as
the first show because of that"

01:08:13.350 --> 01:08:16.560
and "We're going to air
it as the second show".

01:08:16.560 --> 01:08:19.590
And I seem to remember
saying "Are you going

01:08:19.590 --> 01:08:20.890
to be like this all along".

01:08:20.890 --> 01:08:27.190
And I saw agent Sam Kohn
wince over in the corner.

01:08:27.190 --> 01:08:29.720
And they did.

01:08:29.720 --> 01:08:31.020
They did that.

01:08:31.020 --> 01:08:34.790
I did a second show that was
nice and we had them both

01:08:34.790 --> 01:08:37.840
and they aired the
second show first.

01:08:37.840 --> 01:08:43.150
And it got mildly
enthusiastic reaction.

01:08:43.150 --> 01:08:45.520
And then they aired the
first show the second night

01:08:45.520 --> 01:08:47.680
and reviewers were
reviewing the whole week,

01:08:47.680 --> 01:08:51.860
so almost everybody said
about the second show,

01:08:51.860 --> 01:08:55.510
"the Cavett show really found
itself on the second show".

01:08:55.510 --> 01:08:59.300
[ Laughter ]

01:08:59.300 --> 01:09:02.770
I was sure that - the man who
had been waiting backstage for -

01:09:02.770 --> 01:09:06.930
to congratulate me, got a
copy of that [Inaudible].

01:09:06.930 --> 01:09:11.150
So that sort of thing happened
and then there were other kinds

01:09:11.150 --> 01:09:13.250
of troubles that I
would not have gotten

01:09:13.250 --> 01:09:17.030
on and didn't on PBS.

01:09:17.030 --> 01:09:20.440
One involved that
lovable old couple;

01:09:20.440 --> 01:09:24.430
the John Lennon's
and they come on.

01:09:24.430 --> 01:09:26.650
And that was an event and
other people were jealous

01:09:26.650 --> 01:09:29.070
and the reviews were big
and the ratings were big.

01:09:29.070 --> 01:09:33.610
And that was nice, and
they even came back.

01:09:33.610 --> 01:09:36.880
John when I met him a week
earlier before the first one

01:09:36.880 --> 01:09:40.190
said - I said, "Why do you
want to do this really?

01:09:40.190 --> 01:09:42.890
There can't be much you
need at this point".

01:09:42.890 --> 01:09:47.430
And he said, "You have the
only half-way intelligent show

01:09:47.430 --> 01:09:48.730
on television".

01:09:48.730 --> 01:09:50.030
And I said, "Why
would you want to be

01:09:50.030 --> 01:09:53.300
on a half-way intelligent show"?

01:09:53.300 --> 01:09:55.140
And he laughed as
many of you did

01:09:55.140 --> 01:09:57.940
and we were friends
from that point on.

01:09:57.940 --> 01:10:03.330
But, on the second show who'd
have guessed the agreement had

01:10:03.330 --> 01:10:05.110
been that we would do
one of their songs.

01:10:05.110 --> 01:10:09.380
And John said, "Why don't
we do one of Yoko's songs"?

01:10:09.380 --> 01:10:13.910
It had the catchy title "Woman
is the Nigger of the World".

01:10:13.910 --> 01:10:20.320
And I thought are they kidding.

01:10:20.320 --> 01:10:26.670
By God, we did the song
and nothing happened.

01:10:26.670 --> 01:10:30.970
But, before it was aired I was
told that it would not be aired,

01:10:30.970 --> 01:10:34.710
the song, and I complained.

01:10:34.710 --> 01:10:37.630
And they said, "Well all
right, we will air it,

01:10:37.630 --> 01:10:40.100
but our decision is that
you will make a statement

01:10:40.100 --> 01:10:46.160
beforehand" about the dangers
of watching it I guess.

01:10:46.160 --> 01:10:48.990
I remember one of the -

01:10:48.990 --> 01:10:56.490
and there were 412 perhaps
protests about the song.

01:10:56.490 --> 01:11:00.630
None of them about the song
though, but as one woman put it,

01:11:00.630 --> 01:11:03.090
about that mealy
mouthed speech you made -

01:11:03.090 --> 01:11:07.110
delivered just before.

01:11:07.110 --> 01:11:10.050
By delivery sort
of encouraged that?

01:11:10.050 --> 01:11:15.280
So, getting to PBS was going
into a green meadow in a way.

01:11:15.280 --> 01:11:16.910
&gt;&gt; Judy Woodruff: Well
I want to hear more

01:11:16.910 --> 01:11:19.890
about the green meadow, but
Cokie I want to come to you

01:11:19.890 --> 01:11:21.380
because we heard Bill Siemering

01:11:21.380 --> 01:11:25.030
and I think Ervin Duggan
both say words to the effect

01:11:25.030 --> 01:11:29.980
that they felt that NPR should
have had the early head start,

01:11:29.980 --> 01:11:32.390
early boost that PBS did.

01:11:32.390 --> 01:11:34.180
Did you feel that
when you first went -

01:11:34.180 --> 01:11:35.480
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: Oh sure.

01:11:35.480 --> 01:11:36.780
It's still true to some degree.

01:11:36.780 --> 01:11:40.970
But it turned out to be a
blessing I think in the end;

01:11:40.970 --> 01:11:43.890
Bill could probably
talk about this more.

01:11:43.890 --> 01:11:49.240
That it was kind of a secret
at first because at the point

01:11:49.240 --> 01:11:51.880
when Nixon did go
after television

01:11:51.880 --> 01:11:56.650
and basically the television
network committed suicide.

01:11:56.650 --> 01:11:58.680
The NPR was still there.

01:11:58.680 --> 01:12:01.960
And there was no
necessity to disband it

01:12:01.960 --> 01:12:04.050
because it wasn't on the radar.

01:12:04.050 --> 01:12:09.330
And so the ability to just grow

01:12:09.330 --> 01:12:13.750
and thrive was much
easier in that environment.

01:12:13.750 --> 01:12:15.050
But then the growing

01:12:15.050 --> 01:12:18.630
and thriving became something
quite dramatic and as

01:12:18.630 --> 01:12:22.370
of today we are listened
to by more people

01:12:22.370 --> 01:12:24.910
than the three you know
morning editions listened

01:12:24.910 --> 01:12:29.690
to by more people than the three
network morning shows combined.

01:12:29.690 --> 01:12:32.270
It is listened to by more
people than anything other

01:12:32.270 --> 01:12:35.220
than Rush Limbaugh and
I keep saying you know,

01:12:35.220 --> 01:12:37.700
Steve Inskeep should get
what Rush gets, right?

01:12:37.700 --> 01:12:40.620
But because of the
different in ratings is

01:12:40.620 --> 01:12:42.940
about a half million people.

01:12:42.940 --> 01:12:48.620
And so it is wildly successful
and really the primary source

01:12:48.620 --> 01:12:50.570
of news for millions
and millions

01:12:50.570 --> 01:12:51.870
of people around the world.

01:12:51.870 --> 01:12:53.480
&gt;&gt; Judy Woodruff: And
commercial radio has pulled back

01:12:53.480 --> 01:12:55.500
from that dramatically
over the years.

01:12:55.500 --> 01:12:56.800
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts:
That's also true.

01:12:56.800 --> 01:12:58.100
&gt;&gt; Judy Woodruff:
Leaving a big opening.

01:12:58.100 --> 01:13:01.310
So you Hugo Morales, you
were paying attention

01:13:01.310 --> 01:13:03.520
to all this in California.

01:13:03.520 --> 01:13:07.400
But you and some of your
friends decided there was

01:13:07.400 --> 01:13:08.700
something missing.

01:13:08.700 --> 01:13:10.000
What did you see?

01:13:10.000 --> 01:13:12.060
&gt;&gt; Hugo Morales: First
of all I was a little -

01:13:12.060 --> 01:13:17.120
at that time little or no news
on radio and that is true today.

01:13:17.120 --> 01:13:21.320
In Spanish language commercial
radio there is no news.

01:13:21.320 --> 01:13:23.540
I mean that sounds - we still
have [Inaudible] those of us

01:13:23.540 --> 01:13:26.910
who believe in the
mission, but it's absent.

01:13:26.910 --> 01:13:31.470
I mean it's a shocking truth
that there is - there is no news

01:13:31.470 --> 01:13:33.360
in Spanish radio
except for [Inaudible].

01:13:33.360 --> 01:13:39.310
And when we got started back
in '76, let's take the -

01:13:39.310 --> 01:13:45.600
we got started in 1976, but -
we got started on July 4, 1980.

01:13:45.600 --> 01:13:50.580
But 1980 the population
of Latinos in the US was

01:13:50.580 --> 01:13:56.920
around 15 million which is about
6.5 % of the US population.

01:13:56.920 --> 01:14:03.670
Now it's 58 million and 185
of the population and 72%

01:14:03.670 --> 01:14:07.860
of Latinos speak
Spanish at home.

01:14:07.860 --> 01:14:11.310
So, this is not something
of the past, you know some

01:14:11.310 --> 01:14:14.110
of us were young at
that time, right?

01:14:14.110 --> 01:14:15.910
And that we had big dreams.

01:14:15.910 --> 01:14:21.370
And - but rather something
that is very relevant today.

01:14:21.370 --> 01:14:24.790
And yet there is no news

01:14:24.790 --> 01:14:28.240
in Spanish language
commercial radio.

01:14:28.240 --> 01:14:30.010
&gt;&gt; Judy Woodruff: Stunning.

01:14:30.010 --> 01:14:32.370
&gt;&gt; Hugo Morales: It is
very, very stunning.

01:14:32.370 --> 01:14:37.060
It's a story that some of us
don't want to perhaps believe

01:14:37.060 --> 01:14:43.270
but it is true and so back in
1976 when we started organizing

01:14:43.270 --> 01:14:47.160
or I started organizing
Bilingue in Fresno.

01:14:47.160 --> 01:14:52.500
It's a community that I came to
because I was born in Oaxaca,

01:14:52.500 --> 01:14:56.570
and raised in Sonoma County
where the fires were recently.

01:14:56.570 --> 01:14:59.250
And then went to
the Silicon Valley

01:14:59.250 --> 01:15:01.490
because it was the largest
concentration of farm workers

01:15:01.490 --> 01:15:05.340
in the United States, which
is still it, is today.

01:15:05.340 --> 01:15:09.260
You know it's - in the amount
of people that I came in contact

01:15:09.260 --> 01:15:11.060
with they saw the same thing.

01:15:11.060 --> 01:15:15.340
All these Chicanos,
Mexican Americans,

01:15:15.340 --> 01:15:17.740
all of them were US
born except for me.

01:15:17.740 --> 01:15:19.410
I was the only immigrant.

01:15:19.410 --> 01:15:24.680
And all of us were
bilingual and educated.

01:15:24.680 --> 01:15:28.660
We were the first
generation of Latinos

01:15:28.660 --> 01:15:31.980
to be open the doors
to higher education.

01:15:31.980 --> 01:15:35.720
So that contributed a lot to
why Radio Bilingue was founded

01:15:35.720 --> 01:15:39.740
because we saw this
degree of limitation

01:15:39.740 --> 01:15:42.100
of public broadcasting,
but not public -

01:15:42.100 --> 01:15:45.380
just public broadcasting
but I mean you know,

01:15:45.380 --> 01:15:48.430
English language media
that we as Latinos,

01:15:48.430 --> 01:15:53.870
our families could not access
just because of the language

01:15:53.870 --> 01:15:56.840
and so - but it's not
just the language.

01:15:56.840 --> 01:16:02.920
The language and I see everybody
here you know there's much more

01:16:02.920 --> 01:16:05.170
than the language, the
culture, the history

01:16:05.170 --> 01:16:07.600
and the nuances of language.

01:16:07.600 --> 01:16:09.320
There's a literature,
there's a poetry,

01:16:09.320 --> 01:16:11.520
there's arts, there's all that.

01:16:11.520 --> 01:16:16.380
And that was absent in terms of
- and we as young people thought

01:16:16.380 --> 01:16:20.120
"Well wow, it seems
like our treasures,

01:16:20.120 --> 01:16:22.990
our community treasures,
our hidden treasures",

01:16:22.990 --> 01:16:26.610
we have so much you
know wealth of history.

01:16:26.610 --> 01:16:29.200
We have so much wealth of art.

01:16:29.200 --> 01:16:33.810
And so forth in our communities
and we should be able to share

01:16:33.810 --> 01:16:35.360
that and learn from one another.

01:16:35.360 --> 01:16:37.310
So that's why we
establish Radio Bilingue

01:16:37.310 --> 01:16:41.680
in 1976 [Inaudible]
on the air in 1980.

01:16:41.680 --> 01:16:42.980
&gt;&gt; Judy Woodruff:
And it's still going.

01:16:42.980 --> 01:16:44.280
&gt;&gt; Hugo Morales: And
it's still going.

01:16:44.280 --> 01:16:45.580
And we also believe of course,

01:16:45.580 --> 01:16:47.550
that public affairs
[Inaudible] had to be part of it

01:16:47.550 --> 01:16:51.430
because what we wanted to do
is just like in this situation,

01:16:51.430 --> 01:16:56.680
we wanted to us, as Chicanos,
Mexican Americans and Latinos

01:16:56.680 --> 01:17:01.050
to tell the story have our
own narrative to be inclusive.

01:17:01.050 --> 01:17:02.350
I mean if you look

01:17:02.350 --> 01:17:05.310
at for example the
prison population today

01:17:05.310 --> 01:17:06.610
in the United States.

01:17:06.610 --> 01:17:11.250
You know something
like 1% of the

01:17:11.250 --> 01:17:15.070
in prison population
in the US is Latino.

01:17:15.070 --> 01:17:19.470
So a lot of our communities in
need, the highest dropout rates

01:17:19.470 --> 01:17:24.540
from high schools continue to
be Latinos in the United States.

01:17:24.540 --> 01:17:27.900
And yet you see the figures
of how we are significant now

01:17:27.900 --> 01:17:31.930
in number of - and we'll
project it to go even larger.

01:17:31.930 --> 01:17:33.550
So, that's when we
find it rather bleak

01:17:33.550 --> 01:17:35.040
because we wanted
that to happen.

01:17:35.040 --> 01:17:39.340
So, we've been able to document
and follow some of the stories

01:17:39.340 --> 01:17:42.540
that some of the
other media have not.

01:17:42.540 --> 01:17:49.000
For example there's a case
of indigenous woman living

01:17:49.000 --> 01:17:55.590
in the south who was denied
you know, parenting her child

01:17:55.590 --> 01:18:01.510
at birth because she could
not communicate in English

01:18:01.510 --> 01:18:06.940
or Spanish because she
spoke a native language

01:18:06.940 --> 01:18:10.060
from my home state of Oaxaca.

01:18:10.060 --> 01:18:13.330
So it's that kind of a case

01:18:13.330 --> 01:18:18.190
where you some community
folks there

01:18:18.190 --> 01:18:21.950
from I think it was
Alabama called our station

01:18:21.950 --> 01:18:23.250
and told them the story.

01:18:23.250 --> 01:18:26.940
We broke the story and the
news media picked it up

01:18:26.940 --> 01:18:30.530
and eventually she recovered
her child but that's the kind

01:18:30.530 --> 01:18:32.220
of stories that we covered.

01:18:32.220 --> 01:18:35.590
Or, right now what's happening
is talk about the need,

01:18:35.590 --> 01:18:40.090
there's a lot of fear
among our families

01:18:40.090 --> 01:18:42.790
about you know deportations.

01:18:42.790 --> 01:18:46.610
And maybe to those of us in this
room it's just another topic

01:18:46.610 --> 01:18:48.770
but to people who listen to us

01:18:48.770 --> 01:18:52.620
or listeners it's
very, very personal.

01:18:52.620 --> 01:18:54.620
I mean just I think
about a month,

01:18:54.620 --> 01:19:00.270
a couple months ago we had a
call from a mother, from Teresa,

01:19:00.270 --> 01:19:04.560
California, where we opened the
lines and also given information

01:19:04.560 --> 01:19:06.090
that at that time the
opportunity to renew [Inaudible]

01:19:06.090 --> 01:19:09.790
and she was saying
that her son had gone

01:19:09.790 --> 01:19:12.450
into depression after
the election.

01:19:12.450 --> 01:19:14.800
He knew what was
about to happen.

01:19:14.800 --> 01:19:17.230
And he was a [Inaudible]
recipient.

01:19:17.230 --> 01:19:21.220
And he had quit his college
upon after the election.

01:19:21.220 --> 01:19:25.780
And soon later he quit his job.

01:19:25.780 --> 01:19:28.460
So the mother was very
worried about her son

01:19:28.460 --> 01:19:30.000
and what was about to happen.

01:19:30.000 --> 01:19:31.340
So that's the kind of stories

01:19:31.340 --> 01:19:33.370
and narratives that
are [Inaudible].

01:19:33.370 --> 01:19:34.990
&gt;&gt; Judy Woodruff:
You're touching stories

01:19:34.990 --> 01:19:39.370
of all American lives and
that's what public broadcasting,

01:19:39.370 --> 01:19:41.610
public media was founded to do.

01:19:41.610 --> 01:19:46.300
Jim let's talk next for a
few minutes about how hard

01:19:46.300 --> 01:19:50.260
or not it's been to survive
as public media as news

01:19:50.260 --> 01:19:52.270
and public affairs
and public media.

01:19:52.270 --> 01:19:54.260
A lot of competition
out there, the news,

01:19:54.260 --> 01:20:00.320
the commercial news environment
has changed so drastically.

01:20:00.320 --> 01:20:05.090
Why has public media remained,
news and public affairs remained

01:20:05.090 --> 01:20:07.040
as strong as it has
do you think?

01:20:07.040 --> 01:20:10.530
&gt;&gt; Jim Lehrer: Well first of
all we - MacNeil and I said

01:20:10.530 --> 01:20:15.110
at the very beginning and
that if people started -

01:20:15.110 --> 01:20:17.920
if commercial television came
along when cable started growing

01:20:17.920 --> 01:20:21.690
in fact, particularly if they
started doing what we're doing

01:20:21.690 --> 01:20:22.990
we quit doing it.

01:20:22.990 --> 01:20:28.440
There's no point in our doing
what's available elsewhere.

01:20:28.440 --> 01:20:30.200
We'll go on and do
something else.

01:20:30.200 --> 01:20:34.630
And we had a lot of ideas about
the things that we could do,

01:20:34.630 --> 01:20:39.940
but as we sit here now
nobody is doing it right.

01:20:39.940 --> 01:20:42.500
And in fact there is more -

01:20:42.500 --> 01:20:48.260
now more than ever they would
say the kind of journalism

01:20:48.260 --> 01:20:52.080
that is practiced on the
news hour is more needed now

01:20:52.080 --> 01:20:55.020
than ever before
because journalism

01:20:55.020 --> 01:20:59.760
on television has had its
own growth and its own kinds

01:20:59.760 --> 01:21:04.300
of changes and those changes
have been away from the kind

01:21:04.300 --> 01:21:08.990
of separation of straight
reporting from analysis,

01:21:08.990 --> 01:21:11.620
from opinion and that sort
of thing which is still true

01:21:11.620 --> 01:21:14.320
of the news hour but not
true in some elements

01:21:14.320 --> 01:21:18.560
of commercial television,
particularly cable television.

01:21:18.560 --> 01:21:24.760
And so the reason for our
being, let's cut to the chase,

01:21:24.760 --> 01:21:27.190
the reason for our
being is stronger now

01:21:27.190 --> 01:21:30.380
than it has ever been.

01:21:30.380 --> 01:21:31.680
&gt;&gt; Good point.

01:21:31.680 --> 01:21:32.980
&gt;&gt; Judy Woodruff: I will
let that just sit there

01:21:32.980 --> 01:21:34.780
because I think it's right.

01:21:34.780 --> 01:21:38.220
[ Applause ]

01:21:38.220 --> 01:21:41.160
Sharon, as somebody who
has to look at this both

01:21:41.160 --> 01:21:44.320
as you know journalists very
well, but you have to think

01:21:44.320 --> 01:21:47.100
about it as a manager,
as an executive.

01:21:47.100 --> 01:21:51.510
How hard has it been to keep
news and public affairs going?

01:21:51.510 --> 01:21:55.110
And we should add, I mean you
- you over see the Ken Burns,

01:21:55.110 --> 01:21:58.830
it's not just the news
hour and Washington Week.

01:21:58.830 --> 01:22:01.390
It's the Ken Burns
Show and many others.

01:22:01.390 --> 01:22:02.690
&gt;&gt; Sharon Rockefeller:
I think what's one

01:22:02.690 --> 01:22:03.990
of the things that's great

01:22:03.990 --> 01:22:05.380
about the public
television audience is

01:22:05.380 --> 01:22:07.850
that it's pretty well educated.

01:22:07.850 --> 01:22:10.900
Above all, it continues
to want to learn.

01:22:10.900 --> 01:22:14.770
So keeping up on a daily
basis is important,

01:22:14.770 --> 01:22:18.230
but putting in context
weekly as we do

01:22:18.230 --> 01:22:21.780
on Washington Week
is very important.

01:22:21.780 --> 01:22:25.910
And history, the arts, science,

01:22:25.910 --> 01:22:30.320
kids all of the rest means we
serve so many different people

01:22:30.320 --> 01:22:32.620
in so many different ways

01:22:32.620 --> 01:22:36.370
but our signature is the
news and public affairs.

01:22:36.370 --> 01:22:38.850
It's the hardest to fund and

01:22:38.850 --> 01:22:43.550
yet our membership money
essentially helps subsidize

01:22:43.550 --> 01:22:46.230
although we raise d a
lot for the news hour.

01:22:46.230 --> 01:22:49.080
We raised a good bit
for Washington week,

01:22:49.080 --> 01:22:51.530
but we never make a profit,
let's put it that way.

01:22:51.530 --> 01:22:54.270
We always reinvest
in the product

01:22:54.270 --> 01:22:57.400
and could spend a lot
more than we take in.

01:22:57.400 --> 01:23:01.030
I think it is our
trademark, our signature.

01:23:01.030 --> 01:23:04.120
We're very proud of it and I
think our audience is proud

01:23:04.120 --> 01:23:07.450
to be associated
with what we do.

01:23:07.450 --> 01:23:08.990
&gt;&gt; Jim Lehrer: But it's
always been difficult

01:23:08.990 --> 01:23:11.250
to keep it funded, always.

01:23:11.250 --> 01:23:15.900
We never had - we don't even -
the word surplus doesn't even -

01:23:15.900 --> 01:23:18.040
it's not even in our vocabulary.

01:23:18.040 --> 01:23:22.000
We're always under - way over
- either over budget or having

01:23:22.000 --> 01:23:25.200
to cut back and that's
been from day one.

01:23:25.200 --> 01:23:28.820
And I hate to say this
but at the very beginning

01:23:28.820 --> 01:23:33.750
when we first started which was
now 37-38 years ago there was a

01:23:33.750 --> 01:23:36.850
commercial television guy
named Marvin Kalb I ran

01:23:36.850 --> 01:23:38.150
into him socially.

01:23:38.150 --> 01:23:41.530
We'd been on the air a
year or two at that point

01:23:41.530 --> 01:23:43.720
and I didn't know Marvin Kalb.

01:23:43.720 --> 01:23:46.540
And he said, "Well you
guys are doing things" -

01:23:46.540 --> 01:23:49.280
he said "Let me give
you a warning"

01:23:49.280 --> 01:23:50.580
and I said, "Yeah what's that"?

01:23:50.580 --> 01:23:53.990
He said, "Don't let them
give you too much money".

01:23:53.990 --> 01:23:57.480
And I said, "That's
not a problem.

01:23:57.480 --> 01:24:01.030
But just for the hell
of it tell me why"?

01:24:01.030 --> 01:24:05.560
And he told quick story
and he had scads of them.

01:24:05.560 --> 01:24:10.260
But one in particular
nightly news, CBS news,

01:24:10.260 --> 01:24:14.070
Czechoslovakia has been invaded.

01:24:14.070 --> 01:24:16.630
He was going to do a minute,
a minute and a half thing on

01:24:16.630 --> 01:24:19.100
and it's going to
be a major story.

01:24:19.100 --> 01:24:21.050
They kept cutting it
back, cutting it back,

01:24:21.050 --> 01:24:23.820
cutting it back, and
about a minute before air

01:24:23.820 --> 01:24:28.110
or two minutes before air they
got some great fire footage

01:24:28.110 --> 01:24:29.730
from downtown Little Rock.

01:24:29.730 --> 01:24:34.740
Now nobody was hurt in the fire,
just great pictures of fires.

01:24:34.740 --> 01:24:38.350
And they cut his report
back to 20 seconds.

01:24:38.350 --> 01:24:41.410
And he said if they
hadn't had the money to buy

01:24:41.410 --> 01:24:46.200
that fire footage I would
have had my minute and a half.

01:24:46.200 --> 01:24:49.150
So it - and it was -
it stuck in my mind

01:24:49.150 --> 01:24:51.170
because I just told
the story again.

01:24:51.170 --> 01:24:54.510
And - but - and McNeil
always said that too.

01:24:54.510 --> 01:24:59.120
If you get too fat and
sassy you'll - you will -

01:24:59.120 --> 01:25:04.220
you'll do things that you would
do - you'll do things that you -

01:25:04.220 --> 01:25:05.710
that are not required.

01:25:05.710 --> 01:25:09.690
This way you're limited
by - money limits you

01:25:09.690 --> 01:25:12.280
to do what you must rather

01:25:12.280 --> 01:25:14.490
than what you just
kind of want to do.

01:25:14.490 --> 01:25:16.630
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: In radio
that's really not true

01:25:16.630 --> 01:25:19.440
because what we're doing
is opening bureaus all

01:25:19.440 --> 01:25:20.740
over the place.

01:25:20.740 --> 01:25:24.170
And when we're living in
a world where what happens

01:25:24.170 --> 01:25:29.720
in Syntagma Square in Athens
affects your 401k then you need

01:25:29.720 --> 01:25:32.620
to have more international
coverage rather than less.

01:25:32.620 --> 01:25:35.590
And of course more national
coverage understanding what's

01:25:35.590 --> 01:25:37.190
going on in this country.

01:25:37.190 --> 01:25:40.150
And so really the money goes

01:25:40.150 --> 01:25:44.780
to those very expensive
foreign bureaus which are very,

01:25:44.780 --> 01:25:50.310
very difficult to do but I would
argue essential in this time.

01:25:50.310 --> 01:25:53.700
And so we need all the
money we can get, thank you.

01:25:53.700 --> 01:25:59.170
&gt;&gt; Jim Lehrer: It's probably
a story I shouldn't have told.

01:25:59.170 --> 01:26:00.760
&gt;&gt; Sherry Rockefeller: Judy
the one thing I would say is -

01:26:00.760 --> 01:26:05.610
sorry to interrupt, that
corporations in the early days,

01:26:05.610 --> 01:26:10.800
we went to AT&amp;T, etc.,
etc. without huge amounts

01:26:10.800 --> 01:26:12.760
of money in retrospect.

01:26:12.760 --> 01:26:15.690
That has diminished drastically

01:26:15.690 --> 01:26:18.590
but foundations have
really upped the ante.

01:26:18.590 --> 01:26:22.440
And they understand, they're
more visionary, they have a lot

01:26:22.440 --> 01:26:26.610
of money now and it's not
we've never had a surplus.

01:26:26.610 --> 01:26:31.110
But foundations and individuals
who support the program.

01:26:31.110 --> 01:26:34.180
We have, you know you
can give as an individual

01:26:34.180 --> 01:26:38.060
to support the PBS news hour,
which was never possible before.

01:26:38.060 --> 01:26:40.910
But we're doing that in
a membership kind of way.

01:26:40.910 --> 01:26:46.650
&gt;&gt; Did the funding situation
effect the work you were able

01:26:46.650 --> 01:26:50.190
to do, do you think
in any way, you?

01:26:50.190 --> 01:26:52.250
&gt;&gt; Dick Cavett: I
recognized my name,

01:26:52.250 --> 01:26:56.480
but it wasn't - see
I like fires.

01:26:59.010 --> 01:27:02.060
What a story that is.

01:27:02.060 --> 01:27:06.640
I was never thoughtful
or thinking

01:27:06.640 --> 01:27:09.450
about such things as funding.

01:27:09.450 --> 01:27:13.810
It's a bad habit sort
of frame of mind for me.

01:27:13.810 --> 01:27:18.570
And I had to be urged every now
and then to make a phone call

01:27:18.570 --> 01:27:20.500
or make an effort,
something like that.

01:27:20.500 --> 01:27:24.640
But I was thinking of
shows that I was able to do

01:27:24.640 --> 01:27:25.940
and people said,
"Oh you're going

01:27:25.940 --> 01:27:28.930
under public television now,
that's for intellectuals".

01:27:28.930 --> 01:27:33.840
I - intellectual is a very
dangerous label to have put

01:27:33.840 --> 01:27:37.000
on you when you're in
television whether it's public

01:27:37.000 --> 01:27:39.550
or the other sort.

01:27:39.550 --> 01:27:44.080
But I remember appreciating
the fact

01:27:44.080 --> 01:27:48.440
that ABC would have gotten a
little nervous when I would have

01:27:48.440 --> 01:27:54.120
on England's great entertaining
performer, actor, philosopher,

01:27:54.120 --> 01:27:56.880
teacher, John - the
great Jonathan Miller -

01:27:56.880 --> 01:27:59.370
one of the greatest
intellectuals in captivity.

01:27:59.370 --> 01:28:03.060
And would have him on five
nights in a row a couple

01:28:03.060 --> 01:28:06.050
of times and people wanted more.

01:28:06.050 --> 01:28:12.240
I can imagine trying to do
that elsewhere shall we say.

01:28:12.240 --> 01:28:14.850
So, I really wasn't
conscious of funding in ways

01:28:14.850 --> 01:28:16.660
that probably were harmful to me

01:28:16.660 --> 01:28:19.070
because I'm sure I might have
been able to help with it

01:28:19.070 --> 01:28:22.950
if I had pitched
in in certain ways.

01:28:22.950 --> 01:28:24.510
&gt;&gt; Judy Woodruff: But
did you feel the freedom

01:28:24.510 --> 01:28:25.810
to do pretty much
what you wanted

01:28:25.810 --> 01:28:27.210
when you were working at PBS?

01:28:27.210 --> 01:28:31.420
Interview the people you
wanted and do the kind

01:28:31.420 --> 01:28:33.630
of programming you wanted to do?

01:28:33.630 --> 01:28:34.930
&gt;&gt; Dick Cavett: I did ; yes.

01:28:34.930 --> 01:28:38.200
I usually just did the kind
of program I wanted to do

01:28:38.200 --> 01:28:40.430
and in the [Inaudible]
I got away with it.

01:28:40.430 --> 01:28:43.470
I'm not aware of any
particular gripes

01:28:43.470 --> 01:28:45.860
of the sort I was
used to on ABC.

01:28:45.860 --> 01:28:51.440
&gt;&gt; Judy Woodruff: Well
good, we'll take that.

01:28:51.440 --> 01:28:53.810
&gt;&gt; Dick Cavett: Am I
disgustingly happy?

01:28:53.810 --> 01:28:57.350
&gt;&gt; Judy Woodruff: I'm
going to come back to Hugo

01:28:57.350 --> 01:28:59.870
because I mean how do
you see this picture,

01:28:59.870 --> 01:29:01.170
question of resources?

01:29:01.170 --> 01:29:03.370
I mean how much of
an issue was it?

01:29:03.370 --> 01:29:04.870
Are you able to ignore it?

01:29:04.870 --> 01:29:09.180
I mean how does it affect
what you're able to do?

01:29:09.180 --> 01:29:10.480
&gt;&gt; Hugo Morales: Well
first of all I want to say

01:29:10.480 --> 01:29:12.630
that is really, really
important that we maintain

01:29:12.630 --> 01:29:14.950
that independence of public
broadcasting whether it be

01:29:14.950 --> 01:29:16.250
on radio or television.

01:29:16.250 --> 01:29:18.880
That's a value that
we always have shared

01:29:18.880 --> 01:29:21.200
in something we have
to be militant about.

01:29:21.200 --> 01:29:23.060
And that is true also
for Radio Bilingue,

01:29:23.060 --> 01:29:25.820
so how do you build
not just a station

01:29:25.820 --> 01:29:27.830
but in this case a network?

01:29:27.830 --> 01:29:29.890
We have [Inaudible] and
we have 60 affiliates.

01:29:29.890 --> 01:29:31.190
How do you build a network?

01:29:31.190 --> 01:29:33.880
What are you serving people

01:29:33.880 --> 01:29:37.840
with literally no
disposable income, right?

01:29:37.840 --> 01:29:41.370
I mean so it's - so part

01:29:41.370 --> 01:29:45.460
of it is the employees
subsidize the service in part,

01:29:45.460 --> 01:29:48.690
spend the history of public
television, public radio

01:29:48.690 --> 01:29:49.990
at least at the beginning.

01:29:49.990 --> 01:29:51.290
&gt;&gt; Judy Woodruff:
Subsidized how?

01:29:51.290 --> 01:29:54.670
&gt;&gt; Hugo Morales: Well
with salaries for example.

01:29:54.670 --> 01:29:57.460
For starters, and the
other is to be able -

01:29:57.460 --> 01:30:01.660
to keep those employees,
you know that's a real,

01:30:01.660 --> 01:30:03.320
real challenge for us.

01:30:03.320 --> 01:30:07.340
But the other is that it's
foundations that have -

01:30:07.340 --> 01:30:10.750
we manage to attract
but as the competition

01:30:10.750 --> 01:30:15.960
for that has grown our
share of that has lower

01:30:15.960 --> 01:30:19.050
for public affairs and for news

01:30:19.050 --> 01:30:21.240
and for information
from the foundation.

01:30:21.240 --> 01:30:22.810
That's competition
for this [Inaudible].

01:30:22.810 --> 01:30:25.660
So it's really, really
difficult for us.

01:30:25.660 --> 01:30:30.430
And so I would say that -
that for news and information

01:30:30.430 --> 01:30:33.460
in Spanish [Inaudible] is
really, really difficult

01:30:33.460 --> 01:30:35.360
for us to maintain that.

01:30:35.360 --> 01:30:36.660
&gt;&gt; Judy Woodruff: So that leads

01:30:36.660 --> 01:30:37.960
to my last question
for all of you.

01:30:37.960 --> 01:30:39.940
How do you see the
future of news?

01:30:39.940 --> 01:30:42.940
The future of public affairs
in radio and television?

01:30:42.940 --> 01:30:44.830
Do you feel confident about it?

01:30:44.830 --> 01:30:48.290
I mean I like to feel
very confident about it

01:30:48.290 --> 01:30:50.110
because wherever I go I get -

01:30:50.110 --> 01:30:52.460
I hear good things
about the news hour.

01:30:52.460 --> 01:30:56.490
But what do you want,
what do you hear?

01:30:56.490 --> 01:30:58.220
&gt;&gt; Cokie Roberts: I think
that one of the things

01:30:58.220 --> 01:31:02.540
that we're learning is that
Congress actually likes NPR.

01:31:02.540 --> 01:31:09.750
And they can't always say it
out loud, but the truth is

01:31:09.750 --> 01:31:12.210
that it gets back to what
Nick was saying earlier,

01:31:12.210 --> 01:31:14.360
they're all - they're on.

01:31:14.360 --> 01:31:18.630
And it's in all of the districts
and it is the source of news.

01:31:18.630 --> 01:31:23.480
But of course the federal
funding is a tiny percentage

01:31:23.480 --> 01:31:24.780
of NPR money.

01:31:24.780 --> 01:31:28.260
It's really just for the
satellite, but the stations rely

01:31:28.260 --> 01:31:31.840
on it a lot particularly
the small rural stations.

01:31:31.840 --> 01:31:35.160
And that's an important
thing to keep in mind

01:31:35.160 --> 01:31:39.000
that these are people
who really are desperate

01:31:39.000 --> 01:31:41.370
for this kind of information.

01:31:41.370 --> 01:31:45.660
And sometimes it's also the
only emergency signal, you know?

01:31:45.660 --> 01:31:52.470
All of that and so I think
that the fact of the service is

01:31:52.470 --> 01:31:57.670
so widespread and diverse and
so well listened to by people

01:31:57.670 --> 01:32:00.700
in all areas of American life

01:32:00.700 --> 01:32:02.900
that I feel very
confident about the future.

01:32:02.900 --> 01:32:06.010
But I do think it
requires resources.

01:32:06.010 --> 01:32:07.740
&gt;&gt; Sherry Rockefeller:
I was going to say

01:32:07.740 --> 01:32:09.870
that the last two
years, the last year

01:32:09.870 --> 01:32:14.300
and a half have proven more
than ever indeed for what we do.

01:32:14.300 --> 01:32:21.140
It is so complex, depressing
too many, hopeful to those

01:32:21.140 --> 01:32:22.740
who thought they
were electing someone

01:32:22.740 --> 01:32:24.670
who would stand for them.

01:32:24.670 --> 01:32:28.340
But the country is
changing so fast.

01:32:28.340 --> 01:32:31.660
The political system is
practically impossible

01:32:31.660 --> 01:32:33.490
to understand.

01:32:33.490 --> 01:32:37.410
We despair of being
ungovernable,

01:32:37.410 --> 01:32:41.380
but who brings some sense
and order and rationale

01:32:41.380 --> 01:32:45.810
to what happened today and
this week and this year,

01:32:45.810 --> 01:32:52.620
plus analysis, plus thoughtful,
complex sensitive ideas

01:32:52.620 --> 01:32:55.010
about what might
happen in the future.

01:32:55.010 --> 01:32:58.700
We are doing that in a
way that nobody else is.

01:32:58.700 --> 01:33:02.770
And if we just stay true to our
mission, stick to the straight

01:33:02.770 --> 01:33:05.270
and narrow I think
we've got a great future

01:33:05.270 --> 01:33:06.570
in news and public affairs.

01:33:06.570 --> 01:33:08.370
&gt;&gt; I agree 100%.

01:33:08.370 --> 01:33:15.710
[ Applause ]

01:33:15.710 --> 01:33:18.970
&gt;&gt; Dick Cavett: I'm sorry,
two vaudevillians competing.

01:33:24.040 --> 01:33:25.930
&gt;&gt; Jim Lehrer: I was
just going to say amen

01:33:25.930 --> 01:33:27.310
and add a couple of lines.

01:33:27.310 --> 01:33:32.890
The basic need for
the Free Press was set

01:33:32.890 --> 01:33:34.440
up by the founders.

01:33:34.440 --> 01:33:39.060
And the key to our democratic
society is an informed

01:33:39.060 --> 01:33:41.020
electorate, an informed public.

01:33:41.020 --> 01:33:45.820
The only device that the
founders created by the -

01:33:45.820 --> 01:33:48.430
through the first
amendment was the free press.

01:33:48.430 --> 01:33:50.930
That's the device for
people to get information

01:33:50.930 --> 01:33:54.910
to cast informed votes and
all levels of government.

01:33:54.910 --> 01:33:59.500
And we are - but we in
public broadcasting,

01:33:59.500 --> 01:34:03.690
but we in journalism, we
who facilitate journalism,

01:34:03.690 --> 01:34:06.160
we who practice it and
we who participate in it

01:34:06.160 --> 01:34:10.150
at any level are part
of a democratic process

01:34:10.150 --> 01:34:13.850
that is particularly critical
right now with this explosion

01:34:13.850 --> 01:34:17.330
of information that's
coming out, with the Tsunami

01:34:17.330 --> 01:34:20.140
of electronic this
and that gadget,

01:34:20.140 --> 01:34:21.440
and all this kind of stuff.

01:34:21.440 --> 01:34:27.040
This is a critical time and I
agree with what Sharon said,

01:34:27.040 --> 01:34:31.100
we must not lose sight
of what our purpose is.

01:34:31.100 --> 01:34:33.330
And it isn't about
making people laugh,

01:34:33.330 --> 01:34:35.800
it isn't about people
making - make them cry.

01:34:35.800 --> 01:34:40.420
It's about keeping them
informed enough to function

01:34:40.420 --> 01:34:45.510
as informed people in this
country, informed citizens.

01:34:45.510 --> 01:34:51.050
[ Applause ]

