01:39:38.460 --> 01:39:40.090
Pat, take it away.

01:39:40.090 --> 01:39:41.900
&gt;&gt; Pat Aufderheide: What
a great pleasure it is.

01:39:41.900 --> 01:39:44.220
I feel like my entire
life is passing before me

01:39:44.220 --> 01:39:47.100
as I look around the crowd.

01:39:47.100 --> 01:39:49.250
But this - to be on a panel

01:39:49.250 --> 01:39:53.900
with these people is
really extraordinary.

01:39:53.900 --> 01:39:57.240
Each of the people
here has been able

01:39:57.240 --> 01:40:03.050
to not nearly make
great documentary.

01:40:03.050 --> 01:40:06.140
But create a future
for a different kind

01:40:06.140 --> 01:40:09.300
of documentary then was ever
possible on any other kind

01:40:09.300 --> 01:40:11.920
of television to be made.

01:40:11.920 --> 01:40:20.190
And each of them has contributed
differently to - todoing that

01:40:20.190 --> 01:40:23.510
and also in some cases
supporting each other,

01:40:23.510 --> 01:40:26.520
which is really - doesn't
- I dno't want to know

01:40:26.520 --> 01:40:27.820
if I'm giving away secrets here,

01:40:27.820 --> 01:40:31.470
but that doesn't always
happen in public television.

01:40:31.470 --> 01:40:35.350
Anyway, and I've had the
pleasure of working with some

01:40:35.350 --> 01:40:40.100
of these people as well
because as Karen mentioned

01:40:40.100 --> 01:40:42.870
over the last decade Peter
Yazzie and I have been working

01:40:42.870 --> 01:40:46.770
with different organizations to
make fair use more available,

01:40:46.770 --> 01:40:51.760
particularly in archival
ways to makers.

01:40:51.760 --> 01:40:54.900
And public TV broadcasters
including some

01:40:54.900 --> 01:40:59.680
of these people have really
been incredibly supportive

01:40:59.680 --> 01:41:05.130
and early adopters in being able
to make better use of material,

01:41:05.130 --> 01:41:09.920
third party material
to tell America's story

01:41:09.920 --> 01:41:11.820
in so many different ways.

01:41:11.820 --> 01:41:14.010
I want to start first
with Clayborne Carson.

01:41:14.010 --> 01:41:16.910
So Clayborne Carson
is the founder,

01:41:16.910 --> 01:41:18.990
director of the Martin
Luther King, Jr. research

01:41:18.990 --> 01:41:20.600
and education institute.

01:41:20.600 --> 01:41:27.340
He was the senior advisor for
Eyes on the Prize at a time

01:41:27.340 --> 01:41:32.120
when no one thought
it could be made.

01:41:32.120 --> 01:41:37.280
I would like to ask each of you
starting with Clayborne to talk

01:41:37.280 --> 01:41:43.290
about what - what - what did you
have in mind for these series,

01:41:43.290 --> 01:41:46.220
each of you have
this experience.

01:41:46.220 --> 01:41:51.400
The series that ended up really
providing a template for how

01:41:51.400 --> 01:41:54.170
to do things in the future
for filmmakers and had -

01:41:54.170 --> 01:41:56.390
really hadn't been done.

01:41:56.390 --> 01:41:57.950
&gt;&gt; Clayborne Carson:
Well to start out one

01:41:57.950 --> 01:42:00.230
of the things that's so
interesting to listen

01:42:00.230 --> 01:42:01.890
to the previous panel is

01:42:01.890 --> 01:42:05.560
that you know just yesterday
I was lecturing at Stanford

01:42:05.560 --> 01:42:09.030
to my students who
were born well

01:42:09.030 --> 01:42:11.060
after all this had happened,

01:42:11.060 --> 01:42:14.600
and I think that
they were telling me

01:42:14.600 --> 01:42:17.730
about a period before
I came on the scene.

01:42:17.730 --> 01:42:21.110
And so I suddenly felt
young, younger in the sense

01:42:21.110 --> 01:42:26.100
that when I was - I got a
call from Henry Hampton.

01:42:26.100 --> 01:42:28.760
And, who should be here I -

01:42:28.760 --> 01:42:32.750
unfortunately passed
away way too early.

01:42:32.750 --> 01:42:37.090
But he was the visionary
of Eyes on the Prize.

01:42:37.090 --> 01:42:41.350
And I had just accepted
an invitation

01:42:41.350 --> 01:42:45.100
from Coretta Scott King to edit
Martin Luther King's papers.

01:42:45.100 --> 01:42:48.340
So, it wasn't like I
was looking for work.

01:42:48.340 --> 01:42:51.480
I - I realized that this
was going to take decades

01:42:51.480 --> 01:42:56.410
and it has taken decades to
edit and publish his papers.

01:42:56.410 --> 01:43:02.950
But what he was - he talked
about his idea for a series.

01:43:02.950 --> 01:43:06.210
And I think one of the
themes that I see running

01:43:06.210 --> 01:43:10.030
through all the discussions
this afternoon is

01:43:10.030 --> 01:43:14.630
about democratization
of information

01:43:14.630 --> 01:43:17.320
and the interpretation
of history.

01:43:17.320 --> 01:43:22.690
Of the way in which ifyou think
back to the days before PBS,

01:43:22.690 --> 01:43:30.730
before NPR, before the
modern documentary style most

01:43:30.730 --> 01:43:34.270
information about the past
came from a few sources.

01:43:34.270 --> 01:43:42.470
If you saw a documentary
it was usually made by a -

01:43:42.470 --> 01:43:46.270
well they didn't have large
scale documentaries made

01:43:46.270 --> 01:43:48.900
by anything other than
large corporations.

01:43:48.900 --> 01:43:52.980
A lot of them, things
like CBS Reports,

01:43:52.980 --> 01:43:56.850
things like that were done
by the commercial networks.

01:43:56.850 --> 01:44:00.840
And what he was proposing was
to do something very radical.

01:44:00.840 --> 01:44:04.810
And that is to get away
from the notion of history

01:44:04.810 --> 01:44:09.570
as a master narrative told
by a handful of people

01:44:09.570 --> 01:44:11.900
and written in textbooks.

01:44:11.900 --> 01:44:16.210
And everyone kind of took
that as authoritative.

01:44:16.210 --> 01:44:18.830
One of the first things he
said is there's not going

01:44:18.830 --> 01:44:22.920
to be any what we now
call talking heads

01:44:22.920 --> 01:44:24.920
in Eyes on the Prize.

01:44:24.920 --> 01:44:29.560
That our job was not to
come there and pontificate

01:44:29.560 --> 01:44:33.500
and the four of us who were
the senior advisors were all

01:44:33.500 --> 01:44:34.800
really young.

01:44:34.800 --> 01:44:36.880
And I don't think we
would have welcomed

01:44:36.880 --> 01:44:38.870
that role in the first place.

01:44:38.870 --> 01:44:42.330
But what our job was to go

01:44:42.330 --> 01:44:49.410
and find how history was made
during the 1960's, 50's and 60's

01:44:49.410 --> 01:44:53.690
and to go to the sources
and find those people

01:44:53.690 --> 01:44:55.530
and let them tell the story

01:44:55.530 --> 01:45:00.930
of how they made history,
not to interpret it.

01:45:00.930 --> 01:45:02.890
And that was a -

01:45:02.890 --> 01:45:04.190
&gt;&gt; It was a breakthrough -

01:45:04.190 --> 01:45:06.650
&gt;&gt; Clayborne Carson: It was a
breakthrough because even now

01:45:06.650 --> 01:45:10.190
when you look at documentaries
you see that many of them kind

01:45:10.190 --> 01:45:12.270
of go back to that notion

01:45:12.270 --> 01:45:15.580
by having the authoritative
historian kind

01:45:15.580 --> 01:45:18.380
of give this interpretation
that's going

01:45:18.380 --> 01:45:20.330
to guide you through.

01:45:20.330 --> 01:45:23.130
And - but there's
this other story

01:45:23.130 --> 01:45:28.300
of these ordinary
people who make history.

01:45:28.300 --> 01:45:33.390
And the real joy of
doing it was that for us

01:45:33.390 --> 01:45:39.230
as historians we were in our own
work, you know my first book was

01:45:39.230 --> 01:45:41.210
on the student on violent
coordinating committee

01:45:41.210 --> 01:45:43.100
which was not about King.

01:45:43.100 --> 01:45:45.920
It was kind of the
counter king story.

01:45:45.920 --> 01:45:50.550
So, I welcome that kind
of an approach and I think

01:45:50.550 --> 01:45:53.920
that has influenced
the documentaries

01:45:53.920 --> 01:45:57.310
that have been made since
then, that many of them do take

01:45:57.310 --> 01:46:01.130
up that maddle of
allowing ordinary people

01:46:01.130 --> 01:46:05.270
to tell the story
of making history.

01:46:05.270 --> 01:46:08.750
&gt;&gt; Pat Aufderheide: And from
what you're telling is we'll net

01:46:08.750 --> 01:46:12.590
- so one characteristic of this
is ordinary people telling this

01:46:12.590 --> 01:46:15.740
story and also in
an oral history way.

01:46:15.740 --> 01:46:19.730
I mean there was so much rich
oral history that had not been -

01:46:19.730 --> 01:46:22.570
that would have escaped
us forever that was done.

01:46:22.570 --> 01:46:23.870
&gt;&gt; Clayborne Carson:
And now it's interesting

01:46:23.870 --> 01:46:25.640
because I could go
into my classroom

01:46:25.640 --> 01:46:31.910
as I did just this week
and use those interviews.

01:46:31.910 --> 01:46:34.600
I rarely use Eyes on the
Prize in the classroom,

01:46:34.600 --> 01:46:37.930
butI use the interviews that
we did for Eyes on the Prize.

01:46:37.930 --> 01:46:43.660
And often that works so much
better in the sense of it will

01:46:43.660 --> 01:46:44.960
like get it to the point

01:46:44.960 --> 01:46:48.380
where it fits what I
want to talk about.

01:46:48.380 --> 01:46:52.660
I want to talk about Coretta
Scott King for example.

01:46:52.660 --> 01:46:55.690
There's this wonderful interview
we did, extended interview

01:46:55.690 --> 01:47:01.400
with her that maybe we used
at most five minutes of it

01:47:01.400 --> 01:47:03.900
over the Eyes on the Prize.

01:47:03.900 --> 01:47:07.500
And I find that my
students are so drawn

01:47:07.500 --> 01:47:12.340
to the just seeing her
talk about ordinary things,

01:47:12.340 --> 01:47:17.850
you know what was it like
talking to the President

01:47:17.850 --> 01:47:22.770
of the United States when
your husband is in jail

01:47:22.770 --> 01:47:25.460
and you've never spoken
to him before and he calls

01:47:25.460 --> 01:47:29.730
on the phone, and your
young son answers the phone

01:47:29.730 --> 01:47:31.770
and starts babbling away.

01:47:31.770 --> 01:47:33.460
And you have to kind
of get him off

01:47:33.460 --> 01:47:35.750
and say the President is there.

01:47:35.750 --> 01:47:41.080
That kind of story is going
to get through and stick

01:47:41.080 --> 01:47:43.940
in the minds of students
far more

01:47:43.940 --> 01:47:48.320
than simply me giving a
lecture about Martin Luther King

01:47:48.320 --> 01:47:51.590
and going to jail and writing
the letter from Birmingham jail.

01:47:51.590 --> 01:47:52.890
&gt;&gt; Pat Aufderheide: Something
else that I think was

01:47:52.890 --> 01:47:54.790
so important about Eyes
on the Prize in terms

01:47:54.790 --> 01:47:57.890
of standard setting was that
I think it was John Else

01:47:57.890 --> 01:47:59.660
but probably strongly
supported by Henry

01:47:59.660 --> 01:48:03.090
and others really arguing
that every single image had

01:48:03.090 --> 01:48:05.670
to be exactly what
you claimed it was.

01:48:05.670 --> 01:48:09.640
It couldn't be like something
that looks sort of like that,

01:48:09.640 --> 01:48:11.840
which was very common.

01:48:11.840 --> 01:48:16.170
&gt;&gt; Clayborne Carson: Yeah
there was no reconstruction.

01:48:16.170 --> 01:48:21.400
We had to - and in fact that was
when - there's a story actually

01:48:21.400 --> 01:48:24.940
that kind of illustrates that.

01:48:24.940 --> 01:48:28.350
We were interviewing
Ralph Abernathy

01:48:28.350 --> 01:48:30.620
about the march on Washington.

01:48:30.620 --> 01:48:35.190
And he told this wonderful
story about coming back

01:48:35.190 --> 01:48:37.680
after that day at the March.

01:48:37.680 --> 01:48:43.370
I was there too and
[Inaudible] particular meeting

01:48:43.370 --> 01:48:45.210
when he talked about coming back

01:48:45.210 --> 01:48:47.870
after all the people
had departed.

01:48:47.870 --> 01:48:51.710
And in the evening seeing
the rustling of the -

01:48:51.710 --> 01:48:55.280
you know the papers and
all the leftover things

01:48:55.280 --> 01:48:59.380
and then he says it was
just the most beautiful day

01:48:59.380 --> 01:49:01.470
of my entire life.

01:49:01.470 --> 01:49:05.290
And I remember David
Garrow kind of saying

01:49:05.290 --> 01:49:10.300
that it couldn't have
happened that way.

01:49:10.300 --> 01:49:14.860
Why? Because we know where
Ralph Abernathy was every moment

01:49:14.860 --> 01:49:20.320
of that day and so we had
this debate about whether

01:49:20.320 --> 01:49:25.300
to trust his recollection
as opposed

01:49:25.300 --> 01:49:28.590
to our historical
reconstruction.

01:49:28.590 --> 01:49:32.480
And we decided to use it.

01:49:32.480 --> 01:49:35.550
We said - history
might not have happened

01:49:35.550 --> 01:49:39.760
that way, maybe it should have.

01:49:39.760 --> 01:49:46.010
&gt;&gt; Pat Aufderheide: Well let me
jump to David if you don't mind.

01:49:46.010 --> 01:49:50.490
Who I - I remember when he
was the brash young Australian

01:49:50.490 --> 01:49:51.790
who was here -

01:49:51.790 --> 01:49:53.090
&gt;&gt; David Fanning:
South African -

01:49:53.090 --> 01:49:54.390
&gt;&gt; Pat Aufderheide:
South African, sorry.

01:49:54.390 --> 01:49:55.690
Sorry, you know us Americans,

01:49:55.690 --> 01:49:58.020
what's the difference
with other countries.

01:49:58.020 --> 01:50:00.220
&gt;&gt; David Fanning:
We draw the lines.

01:50:00.220 --> 01:50:01.920
&gt;&gt; Pat Aufderheide: Brash
young South African here

01:50:01.920 --> 01:50:03.820
to bring us a whole new -

01:50:03.820 --> 01:50:07.590
new format that was
possibly too challenging

01:50:07.590 --> 01:50:10.340
for public television.

01:50:10.340 --> 01:50:11.640
&gt;&gt; David Fanning: You
know I'm a creature of -

01:50:11.640 --> 01:50:13.380
I'm a baby of public television.

01:50:13.380 --> 01:50:16.330
I walked into a public
television station in 1973

01:50:16.330 --> 01:50:19.580
in Huntington Beach as a young
filmmaker from South Africa

01:50:19.580 --> 01:50:21.840
by way of London and the BBC.

01:50:21.840 --> 01:50:24.930
And I walked in and volunteered.

01:50:24.930 --> 01:50:27.400
I got my hands on the tools,
that camera and that [Inaudible]

01:50:27.400 --> 01:50:31.530
that were there and began
working with Peter McGee

01:50:31.530 --> 01:50:35.240
at WJBH found me ther ein
1977 and brought me to Boston

01:50:35.240 --> 01:50:38.220
to start a series called World,

01:50:38.220 --> 01:50:40.210
which was an international
documentary series.

01:50:40.210 --> 01:50:42.150
And the idea was to do a series

01:50:42.150 --> 01:50:44.750
about the world as
others see it.

01:50:44.750 --> 01:50:46.390
And it was this wonderful idea.

01:50:46.390 --> 01:50:48.680
I came to WGBH to
find a place that was

01:50:48.680 --> 01:50:52.650
as extraordinary institution
that was dedicated to ideas.

01:50:52.650 --> 01:50:55.070
And I had never been around
anything quite like it.

01:50:55.070 --> 01:50:57.610
It was also that each of
the people that were working

01:50:57.610 --> 01:50:59.900
in the different genre's
from science to history

01:50:59.900 --> 01:51:09.090
to even Julia Child who was in
the back corner of our offices,

01:51:09.090 --> 01:51:13.150
were doing things because of
they cared about the ideas.

01:51:13.150 --> 01:51:18.210
And it was extraordinary
privilege and it is to this day.

01:51:18.210 --> 01:51:21.850
This amazing privilege that the
reason there's a front line is

01:51:21.850 --> 01:51:26.540
because we were trusted with
enough resources for long enough

01:51:26.540 --> 01:51:31.050
to work it out, to try to figure
out how to do the best work.

01:51:31.050 --> 01:51:33.620
And the privilege of being
able to give that resource

01:51:33.620 --> 01:51:36.780
and to say how you get to
spend it and justify it.

01:51:36.780 --> 01:51:40.120
And if you can't make the
best film you could make

01:51:40.120 --> 01:51:42.860
about this subject,
then don't make it.

01:51:42.860 --> 01:51:44.260
And it was as simple as that.

01:51:44.260 --> 01:51:47.550
It wasn't me, it was all the
talented people that I could go

01:51:47.550 --> 01:51:51.080
out and feret out and
bring to public television.

01:51:51.080 --> 01:51:54.490
I tried that out with
World, we did 60 films.

01:51:54.490 --> 01:51:58.770
And along the way but there was
a moment when I sat in a meeting

01:51:58.770 --> 01:52:01.340
at the corporation of public
broadcasting with a man

01:52:01.340 --> 01:52:05.950
who must be remembered Louis
Freedman was then the head

01:52:05.950 --> 01:52:11.560
of programming and
he walked into it

01:52:11.560 --> 01:52:15.030
and he said he was inundated
with thousands of proposals,

01:52:15.030 --> 01:52:16.930
and he just couldn't
sort through it all

01:52:16.930 --> 01:52:20.080
and he made a decision
to do three big strands.

01:52:20.080 --> 01:52:22.990
One was going to be drama and
it became America Playhouse.

01:52:22.990 --> 01:52:25.810
The second was childrens
and it became Wonder Works

01:52:25.810 --> 01:52:30.100
and the third was a news
and documentary idea.

01:52:30.100 --> 01:52:32.890
And I walked in with World
looking for a little bit

01:52:32.890 --> 01:52:35.840
of funding to do eight
shows for the next season

01:52:35.840 --> 01:52:39.610
and he made me sit down at his
table with a sandwich and figure

01:52:39.610 --> 01:52:43.170
out what the budget for a 36
week series would look like.

01:52:43.170 --> 01:52:46.610
And we counted it up
to 3 million dollars

01:52:46.610 --> 01:52:50.740
at the time in 1970 - 1981.

01:52:50.740 --> 01:52:55.310
And we came up with that figure
and said we could probably do it

01:52:55.310 --> 01:52:57.880
for that much money; and he
said "Great I'm going to put

01:52:57.880 --> 01:52:59.350
out a request for proposals".

01:52:59.350 --> 01:53:00.650
And he put out proposals

01:53:00.650 --> 01:53:05.200
to various people including our
friends at WET or proposed it

01:53:05.200 --> 01:53:08.280
and we proposed it
and we got the money.

01:53:08.280 --> 01:53:11.200
And the guarantee was that
we would have the money

01:53:11.200 --> 01:53:12.770
for three years.

01:53:12.770 --> 01:53:14.930
If we could persuade
the stations

01:53:14.930 --> 01:53:16.760
to match the money progressively

01:53:16.760 --> 01:53:18.120
over the course of
the three years.

01:53:18.120 --> 01:53:22.040
It was a visionary idea and you
left us the freedom to do that.

01:53:22.040 --> 01:53:27.500
And we made our mistakes and
we you know, bumped our heads

01:53:27.500 --> 01:53:31.450
and we did some good things
and we found some smart people

01:53:31.450 --> 01:53:33.140
and slowly this idea grew.

01:53:33.140 --> 01:53:37.790
It grew of simply that idea;
so to Lewis, to Peter McGee

01:53:37.790 --> 01:53:40.390
who found me on the beach in
Huntington Beach and brought me

01:53:40.390 --> 01:53:43.840
to Boston, you know are the
people I thank for Frontline.

01:53:43.840 --> 01:53:45.710
That's what made it happen.

01:53:45.710 --> 01:53:49.240
And it really has
been as simple as that

01:53:49.240 --> 01:53:51.270
and as complicated as that.

01:53:51.270 --> 01:53:52.570
And -

01:53:52.570 --> 01:53:53.870
&gt;&gt; Pat Aufderheide:
Although Frontline has -

01:53:53.870 --> 01:53:58.880
it developed almost a brand that
you really did put your stamp

01:53:58.880 --> 01:54:02.740
on a kind of documentary
that became a style

01:54:02.740 --> 01:54:04.150
of making documentaries.

01:54:04.150 --> 01:54:05.450
&gt;&gt; David Fanning:
Well I don't know,

01:54:05.450 --> 01:54:06.750
you see I think there
were lots and lots

01:54:06.750 --> 01:54:08.220
of different styles
of films within them.

01:54:08.220 --> 01:54:10.900
They were observational films,
they were repertorial films,

01:54:10.900 --> 01:54:14.970
they were investigative
films, they were films

01:54:14.970 --> 01:54:18.720
like you know Marian Marzynski's
wonderful six hours called

01:54:18.720 --> 01:54:23.200
Shtetl and they were
extraordinarily different films

01:54:23.200 --> 01:54:24.500
that came about.

01:54:24.500 --> 01:54:27.300
And I always thought that
we needed to make a series

01:54:27.300 --> 01:54:31.450
that young and older
producers, reporters

01:54:31.450 --> 01:54:35.850
and filmmakers would look at
and say "I can learn from that".

01:54:35.850 --> 01:54:37.150
And the people who come to me

01:54:37.150 --> 01:54:38.840
and say "How do you
make these films?

01:54:38.840 --> 01:54:40.330
I'd like to get into
documentaries".

01:54:40.330 --> 01:54:43.820
I say just watch a lot of them
and try to deconstruct them

01:54:43.820 --> 01:54:47.200
and look for the different ones
that suit you for who you are

01:54:47.200 --> 01:54:49.280
and the kind of film you make.

01:54:49.280 --> 01:54:51.880
Because ultimately these
are works of authorship.

01:54:51.880 --> 01:54:54.460
And if you encourage authors
and then encourage them

01:54:54.460 --> 01:54:56.650
because they do good work
by giving them another film

01:54:56.650 --> 01:55:00.420
to make then you begin to buid
a body of work at the time.

01:55:00.420 --> 01:55:05.830
And Frontline has intiially -
Judy was anchoring the series

01:55:05.830 --> 01:55:09.520
after Jessica Savage
in the first season.

01:55:09.520 --> 01:55:12.870
But there's a certain point
we felt like we would sort

01:55:12.870 --> 01:55:17.300
of take the extra time and
we began to use Will Lyman

01:55:17.300 --> 01:55:20.430
as a voice and we made
that strategic decision

01:55:20.430 --> 01:55:22.410
that you would hear this
- there'd be something

01:55:22.410 --> 01:55:24.810
in the quality of the
words or the qualitiy

01:55:24.810 --> 01:55:26.410
of the story telling
would say ah ha that's

01:55:26.410 --> 01:55:27.710
that different thing.

01:55:27.710 --> 01:55:31.790
That's that show and so
there was a value to that.

01:55:31.790 --> 01:55:34.630
There are people who
qustion that Will is kind

01:55:34.630 --> 01:55:39.750
of old fashioned and the
patriarchy and all kinds

01:55:39.750 --> 01:55:41.780
of reasons that black people
would say we should be using

01:55:41.780 --> 01:55:43.530
other voices, and we do.

01:55:43.530 --> 01:55:46.980
But ultimately you needed t have
some kind of connective tissue

01:55:46.980 --> 01:55:48.970
at times that would
hold a string

01:55:48.970 --> 01:55:50.720
through the sets of films.

01:55:50.720 --> 01:55:52.690
&gt;&gt; Pat Aufderheide: So you're
arguing if you could have some

01:55:52.690 --> 01:55:56.970
of these marking features
then you could have a lot more

01:55:56.970 --> 01:55:58.920
freedom, artistic
freedom in other areas.

01:55:58.920 --> 01:56:00.220
&gt;&gt; David Fanning:
Freedom without it,

01:56:00.220 --> 01:56:02.090
but yet you'd still - there
would be something other

01:56:02.090 --> 01:56:04.390
than an anthology series
and the most important thing

01:56:04.390 --> 01:56:06.680
about it was it was going
to be a work of journalism.

01:56:06.680 --> 01:56:09.170
It wasn't going to be
an anthology series made

01:56:09.170 --> 01:56:11.820
by independent filmmakers
who would come to us

01:56:11.820 --> 01:56:13.690
with films pretty much
made and we would do -

01:56:13.690 --> 01:56:17.440
we would actually initiate
and we would subject them

01:56:17.440 --> 01:56:20.020
to the rigors of an
editorial process,

01:56:20.020 --> 01:56:23.950
which mean that the journalism
had to be transparent,

01:56:23.950 --> 01:56:27.180
we needed to go right into
it at any point and be able

01:56:27.180 --> 01:56:30.630
to understand the source
materials inside that film,

01:56:30.630 --> 01:56:33.570
and that was at the heart of -

01:56:33.570 --> 01:56:35.560
&gt;&gt; Pat Aufderheide: Margaret
Drain, American Experience.

01:56:35.560 --> 01:56:37.390
&gt;&gt; Margaret Drain:
I also wanted to add

01:56:37.390 --> 01:56:41.110
that there is another binding
agent in front line and I think

01:56:41.110 --> 01:56:45.230
when I came to GBH I discovered
this because I had come from CBS

01:56:45.230 --> 01:56:48.620
where I worked at CBS
Reports and then a couple

01:56:48.620 --> 01:56:51.090
of iterations of magazine shows.

01:56:51.090 --> 01:56:57.380
And CBS Reports closed and
shut down because TV Guide.

01:56:57.380 --> 01:57:00.420
You remember TV Guide,
an artifact of the past,

01:57:00.420 --> 01:57:02.320
ran a front page story -

01:57:02.320 --> 01:57:05.970
I mean a cover story saying
the documentary is dead.

01:57:05.970 --> 01:57:09.410
And this was in 1985 I think.

01:57:09.410 --> 01:57:10.710
&gt;&gt; Pat Aufderheide: That's

01:57:10.710 --> 01:57:12.010
when documentary was
still a bad word.

01:57:12.010 --> 01:57:13.310
&gt;&gt; Margaret Drain:
It was a bad word.

01:57:13.310 --> 01:57:16.280
So everybody went scurrying
and I got a great job offer

01:57:16.280 --> 01:57:22.130
from WGBH again from Peter McGee
who really needs to be mentioned

01:57:22.130 --> 01:57:25.260
as many times as
posisble because he sort

01:57:25.260 --> 01:57:28.450
of set the standards at WGBH.

01:57:28.450 --> 01:57:33.360
And they wanted - Peter and
Judy Clayton was the original

01:57:33.360 --> 01:57:37.690
executive producer, wanted
to do a history series

01:57:37.690 --> 01:57:39.670
but the binding agent

01:57:39.670 --> 01:57:42.770
in the history series
was good story telling.

01:57:42.770 --> 01:57:45.430
It had to have a beginning,
a middle and an end.

01:57:45.430 --> 01:57:47.720
Narrative, narrative, narrative.

01:57:47.720 --> 01:57:50.310
We even constructed the
documentaries and acts

01:57:50.310 --> 01:57:54.280
which was something that most
documentarians had not been

01:57:54.280 --> 01:57:57.270
doing, you know they - they had

01:57:57.270 --> 01:58:00.350
on commercial television you had
a lot of documentaries that were

01:58:00.350 --> 01:58:03.940
like NBC White Paper
and ABC - I forget what

01:58:03.940 --> 01:58:05.240
that series was called.

01:58:05.240 --> 01:58:06.540
And they were surveys.

01:58:06.540 --> 01:58:08.920
They were mostly surveys
from the top down.

01:58:08.920 --> 01:58:11.660
They weren't stories, they
weren't actual stories

01:58:11.660 --> 01:58:16.590
where you had characters that
you could follow and I think

01:58:16.590 --> 01:58:20.120
that was an element that
was emphsized at GBH

01:58:20.120 --> 01:58:23.090
and in particular I
know American Experience

01:58:23.090 --> 01:58:26.540
because as we were talking
before you want to hear

01:58:26.540 --> 01:58:29.240
from as many people as possible
who are as close to the subject

01:58:29.240 --> 01:58:33.000
as possible and then
construct it very carefully

01:58:33.000 --> 01:58:35.920
to have a story arc.

01:58:35.920 --> 01:58:38.040
What happened then,
what happened next,

01:58:38.040 --> 01:58:41.710
what happened after that?

01:58:41.710 --> 01:58:43.530
&gt;&gt; Pat Aufderheide: So
you're - let's point out then

01:58:43.530 --> 01:58:48.050
that public television
is - the real innovator

01:58:48.050 --> 01:58:49.960
of this character
driven story model

01:58:49.960 --> 01:58:53.810
that now is standard
expectation for documentary.

01:58:53.810 --> 01:58:56.040
&gt;&gt; Margaret Drain: Yeah I think
so because I mean I don't want

01:58:56.040 --> 01:58:57.600
to take the credit for
it because it was -

01:58:57.600 --> 01:58:59.580
I didn't invent the
narrative style.

01:58:59.580 --> 01:59:03.920
But it was something that was
embraced wholeheartedly by WGBH

01:59:03.920 --> 01:59:07.840
and they gave all of us the
resources to figure it out.

01:59:07.840 --> 01:59:09.720
Because when you tell
-when you're in the process

01:59:09.720 --> 01:59:12.440
of telling a story you need time
to figure out what the story is,

01:59:12.440 --> 01:59:15.520
who the main characters are, who
the secondary characters are,

01:59:15.520 --> 01:59:18.770
where the at break is,
what's going to happen next,

01:59:18.770 --> 01:59:22.760
how to conclude it and
without being - you don't have

01:59:22.760 --> 01:59:25.610
to tel lthe entire story you
know, because everybody used

01:59:25.610 --> 01:59:27.860
to agonize about
what's left out.

01:59:27.860 --> 01:59:30.600
Well if you did your job
properly no one would even

01:59:30.600 --> 01:59:32.790
notice that you left
anything out.

01:59:32.790 --> 01:59:37.820
They would just - our philosophy
was just go narrow and go deep,

01:59:37.820 --> 01:59:40.130
go narrow and go deep
and get characters.

01:59:40.130 --> 01:59:42.450
But I do want to comment on
something you said before

01:59:42.450 --> 01:59:45.950
about getting first hand
witnesses, because I admired

01:59:45.950 --> 01:59:49.830
that in Henry Hampton's
Shop and Eyes on the Prize

01:59:49.830 --> 01:59:51.750
and I thought it was terrific.

01:59:51.750 --> 01:59:55.670
We had a challenge
because our mandate was

01:59:55.670 --> 01:59:59.390
to tell all American History you
know prior - we had to go back

01:59:59.390 --> 02:00:01.320
into the 18th century and
even the 17th century.

02:00:01.320 --> 02:00:03.100
And we were terrified.

02:00:03.100 --> 02:00:06.260
We actually avoided anything
that was pre-archival

02:00:06.260 --> 02:00:09.200
because we didn't know how to
deal with it at the beginning.

02:00:09.200 --> 02:00:13.190
And you can't find witnesses
who are - we did a show -

02:00:13.190 --> 02:00:16.130
one of our first shows was
on the 1906 earthquake,

02:00:16.130 --> 02:00:17.450
San Francisco earthquake.

02:00:17.450 --> 02:00:22.140
We barely got a couple of people
to make an appearance and we -

02:00:22.140 --> 02:00:26.120
as soon as we found them we
shot them immediately, you know

02:00:26.120 --> 02:00:27.420
and put them in the bank.

02:00:27.420 --> 02:00:28.900
Because we didn't even
know we were going

02:00:28.900 --> 02:00:31.360
to go ahead with this storoy.

02:00:31.360 --> 02:00:33.790
But it was a real
stretch for us and we had

02:00:33.790 --> 02:00:38.540
to challenge ourselves to go
back into the 19th century

02:00:38.540 --> 02:00:43.450
and even back into revolutionary
period, so we relied

02:00:43.450 --> 02:00:46.500
on since we're here talking
about the archives letters,

02:00:46.500 --> 02:00:50.260
diaries, first hand accounts
that could then be employed

02:00:50.260 --> 02:00:53.370
in many different
ways to recall maybe -

02:00:53.370 --> 02:00:56.160
maybe it was the
Donner party, you know?

02:00:56.160 --> 02:00:59.780
I mean there's no first hand
witnesses in the Donner party.

02:00:59.780 --> 02:01:04.650
One of our most successful
films and what did we rely on?

02:01:04.650 --> 02:01:08.480
We relied on diaries
and letters.

02:01:08.480 --> 02:01:09.920
&gt;&gt; Pat Aufderheide: So
one of the things that is

02:01:09.920 --> 02:01:17.760
so I think impressive about what
both of your series ended up -

02:01:17.760 --> 02:01:19.060
and all of your work

02:01:19.060 --> 02:01:23.010
in documentaries did was
I think create a sense

02:01:23.010 --> 02:01:24.730
of trust among the stations.

02:01:24.730 --> 02:01:27.210
For something that they
had dreaded and feared ever

02:01:27.210 --> 02:01:31.860
since the days of NET which
was before there was a PBS.

02:01:31.860 --> 02:01:34.910
And you know shows
like the redliningshow

02:01:34.910 --> 02:01:38.370
that made Nixon decide he should
defund public broadcasting.

02:01:38.370 --> 02:01:42.520
So you sort of created a
sense of quality, dignity,

02:01:42.520 --> 02:01:46.740
realibility, turnkey and so on.

02:01:46.740 --> 02:01:51.990
Something else that is actually
really interesting to me is

02:01:51.990 --> 02:01:55.960
that public television and
building upon that has been able

02:01:55.960 --> 02:02:01.440
to actually foster
a kind of -and

02:02:01.440 --> 02:02:04.230
as you descrbied
it anthology show

02:02:04.230 --> 02:02:08.170
for independent voices as well.

02:02:08.170 --> 02:02:11.730
And impressively I have to
say thank you to David Fanning

02:02:11.730 --> 02:02:15.050
for being so supportive
of anthology shows as well

02:02:15.050 --> 02:02:19.160
as these executive
produced journalism series.

02:02:19.160 --> 02:02:23.300
And Stephen Gong who
is here from the Center

02:02:23.300 --> 02:02:30.130
for Asian American Media, one
of the minority consortiua

02:02:30.130 --> 02:02:34.060
of public - CPB, is also a
veteran independent filmmaker

02:02:34.060 --> 02:02:37.210
and somebody who supports
independent filmmakers

02:02:37.210 --> 02:02:40.540
and has also been involved
in creating archives

02:02:40.540 --> 02:02:42.230
that we can all draw on.

02:02:42.230 --> 02:02:47.190
So, I'd love to hear you talk a
little bit about the filmmaking

02:02:47.190 --> 02:02:50.160
that goes to fuel the
two big anthology series,

02:02:50.160 --> 02:02:53.280
POV and Independent Lens
and just like let me say,

02:02:53.280 --> 02:02:55.880
board member of ITVS, yes.

02:02:55.880 --> 02:02:58.690
&gt;&gt; Stephen Gong:
Actually ifI could,

02:02:58.690 --> 02:03:01.700
I'd like to make a reference
to the panels we heard earlier

02:03:01.700 --> 02:03:06.390
because the seeds of the
minority consortia independent

02:03:06.390 --> 02:03:09.730
and diverse filmmakers really
goes back to the same era

02:03:09.730 --> 02:03:11.680
of the great society; so many

02:03:11.680 --> 02:03:14.880
of these entities were
founded in the 70's.

02:03:14.880 --> 02:03:18.840
And it came out of both
civil rights and in many

02:03:18.840 --> 02:03:22.110
of our cases Hugo Morales
touched on this also.

02:03:22.110 --> 02:03:25.320
The changing - rapidly changing
demographics of the country

02:03:25.320 --> 02:03:28.120
which will start to be
recognized even then.

02:03:28.120 --> 02:03:31.970
The Hart-Celler Act, the
Immigration Act was rewritten

02:03:31.970 --> 02:03:36.350
in 1965 and even though it would
take the rest - a generation,

02:03:36.350 --> 02:03:37.960
it has reshaped America.

02:03:37.960 --> 02:03:40.340
So in this time period
I'm talking

02:03:40.340 --> 02:03:44.090
about from the 60's till now,
the Asia America community went

02:03:44.090 --> 02:03:47.740
from 1% of the population
and now we're 6%,

02:03:47.740 --> 02:03:50.820
we're over 20 million
and the fastest growing.

02:03:50.820 --> 02:03:53.690
And Hugo mentioned
the statistics

02:03:53.690 --> 02:03:55.530
for the Latino community.

02:03:55.530 --> 02:03:57.610
S the premise that we all had

02:03:57.610 --> 02:04:01.640
as this whole enterprise
was getting underway was

02:04:01.640 --> 02:04:05.010
where would these voices
of other communities

02:04:05.010 --> 02:04:10.470
for whom our presence in
media over all was an absence

02:04:10.470 --> 02:04:12.180
or was one of stereotypes.

02:04:12.180 --> 02:04:14.980
So for Asian Americans you know

02:04:14.980 --> 02:04:18.530
in entertainment media we are
only you know the villains

02:04:18.530 --> 02:04:21.430
in war movies or we're house
boys or we're gangsters

02:04:21.430 --> 02:04:24.260
in China Town or laundry men.

02:04:24.260 --> 02:04:29.400
And yet we have this inspiration
of the Civil Rights movement

02:04:29.400 --> 02:04:32.460
to recognize how important
it was for us to be able

02:04:32.460 --> 02:04:35.180
to participate in society.

02:04:35.180 --> 02:04:38.580
So, the mechanism for us
in the minority consortium

02:04:38.580 --> 02:04:40.960
and the wisdom of
the corporatino

02:04:40.960 --> 02:04:43.580
for public broadcasting
was to help insure

02:04:43.580 --> 02:04:46.500
that there was a
pipeline of programming by

02:04:46.500 --> 02:04:50.030
and about these new
minority communities.

02:04:50.030 --> 02:04:53.720
And we've been doing this
between 35 and 40 years all

02:04:53.720 --> 02:04:57.170
of us, the five members
of the organization.

02:04:57.170 --> 02:04:59.670
One of the things that I
- one of the first points

02:04:59.670 --> 02:05:01.610
that I wanted to make
though and response now

02:05:01.610 --> 02:05:06.610
to your question was that we
have learned something deeper

02:05:06.610 --> 02:05:12.330
in this construct that it
was important ot include the

02:05:12.330 --> 02:05:16.480
perspectives of people of
color in telling diverse kinds

02:05:16.480 --> 02:05:21.550
of stories, be they about
history or social issues

02:05:21.550 --> 02:05:24.630
or even our cultural history.

02:05:24.630 --> 02:05:30.100
And I think at first we thought
we were presenting authentic

02:05:30.100 --> 02:05:33.710
images that our own
communities could recognize.

02:05:33.710 --> 02:05:36.790
So one piece that's really
important is you can't fully

02:05:36.790 --> 02:05:39.130
participate in the
society unless

02:05:39.130 --> 02:05:40.470
in some ways you see yourself

02:05:40.470 --> 02:05:43.190
and your story is
told in the society.

02:05:43.190 --> 02:05:46.900
The second poitn I think we came
to undersatnd relatively quickly

02:05:46.900 --> 02:05:49.280
after that was that these
stories needed to be

02:05:49.280 --> 02:05:53.370
for all Americans though and not
just for our own communities.

02:05:53.370 --> 02:05:55.660
The Asian American community
would be a good example

02:05:55.660 --> 02:05:59.050
because we're so diverse
and so different in language

02:05:59.050 --> 02:06:03.420
and cultural backgrounds that
in some ways you're an expert

02:06:03.420 --> 02:06:10.080
and know culture in a sense in
this construct of Asia America.

02:06:10.080 --> 02:06:13.260
But I would say in the recent
years and this is where I want

02:06:13.260 --> 02:06:17.830
to end my thoughts on
this, I think we now -

02:06:17.830 --> 02:06:21.240
where we are today in
this quesiton of really

02:06:21.240 --> 02:06:25.230
who is an American and what is
it that makes America great.

02:06:25.230 --> 02:06:29.620
It's clear that I think in
some ways we tood for granted

02:06:29.620 --> 02:06:30.920
that there was an acceptance.

02:06:30.920 --> 02:06:33.480
That diversity was an
important and a key factor

02:06:33.480 --> 02:06:36.630
of the American experience.

02:06:36.630 --> 02:06:40.290
But it is vital that we
stand in for this notion

02:06:40.290 --> 02:06:44.030
of what this country can
be and that we're not just

02:06:44.030 --> 02:06:45.920
about our racial stories.

02:06:45.920 --> 02:06:49.340
You know diversity is within
each of our communities as well.

02:06:49.340 --> 02:06:51.040
And Ithink that's
th elarger piece

02:06:51.040 --> 02:06:53.340
to reshift the way we all talk

02:06:53.340 --> 02:06:56.140
about what is our
common history.

02:06:56.140 --> 02:06:58.290
The way we examine things

02:06:58.290 --> 02:07:02.060
and I think we're still
exploring what these different

02:07:02.060 --> 02:07:05.430
points of view mean and it's
a journey we'll all need to be

02:07:05.430 --> 02:07:09.770
on because we don't have the
guide stone of a you know,

02:07:09.770 --> 02:07:13.840
sort of White European
male dominated

02:07:13.840 --> 02:07:15.630
through line of history.

02:07:15.630 --> 02:07:17.110
&gt;&gt; Pat Aufderheide:
Thank you very much.

02:07:17.110 --> 02:07:20.500
Does anybody want to
jump in before I -

02:07:20.500 --> 02:07:22.620
&gt;&gt; Clayborne Carson: I think
one of the points I'd make is

02:07:22.620 --> 02:07:26.440
that all of us in some
ways are beneficiaries

02:07:26.440 --> 02:07:33.680
of the technological changes
and that have lessoned the cost

02:07:33.680 --> 02:07:38.300
and the - some would
say even the skill level

02:07:38.300 --> 02:07:39.810
to get it to filmmaking.

02:07:39.810 --> 02:07:46.600
So, that it has become much,
much easier to do what you know

02:07:46.600 --> 02:07:48.070
like a film like Eyes

02:07:48.070 --> 02:07:51.770
on the Prize today you
could probably do it

02:07:51.770 --> 02:07:53.480
for much less money,

02:07:53.480 --> 02:07:57.230
simply because the equipment
would b eso much less,

02:07:57.230 --> 02:08:00.340
the editing euqipment,
all of that sort of thing.

02:08:00.340 --> 02:08:03.770
And I think that looking
forward into the future,

02:08:03.770 --> 02:08:10.470
what I see coming out of
African American filmmaking is

02:08:10.470 --> 02:08:15.860
that proliferation is kind
of pulling us in you know,

02:08:15.860 --> 02:08:19.030
even within the African
American community.

02:08:19.030 --> 02:08:24.440
Now you have gay
filmmakers, black filmmakers

02:08:24.440 --> 02:08:27.790
who might be trying to
describe that experience.

02:08:27.790 --> 02:08:33.010
Ou have so many - so much
diversity within each

02:08:33.010 --> 02:08:36.710
of these communities
that one thing I fear is

02:08:36.710 --> 02:08:40.900
that it's very difficult
to get a sense in a -

02:08:40.900 --> 02:08:44.380
right now for example
I've been involved in more

02:08:44.380 --> 02:08:48.620
than two dozen documentary
films about black American life

02:08:48.620 --> 02:08:52.350
and most of it 20th century.

02:08:52.350 --> 02:08:57.050
And it seems like the pace
of that keeps increasing

02:08:57.050 --> 02:09:00.840
and I think ther
eis that concern,

02:09:00.840 --> 02:09:05.270
that we're losing a sense
of even the commonality

02:09:05.270 --> 02:09:10.060
of being black, must
less being American.

02:09:10.060 --> 02:09:15.940
And maybe that's good because
otherwise you would not have a

02:09:15.940 --> 02:09:19.350
sense that these
communities exist.

02:09:19.350 --> 02:09:25.190
But in terms of trying to get
a sense of it you know for many

02:09:25.190 --> 02:09:29.230
of my students I teach - in fact
I'll be teaching next quarter a

02:09:29.230 --> 02:09:32.090
course on Black independent
film.

02:09:32.090 --> 02:09:40.980
And I find that maybe one
student might have seen some

02:09:40.980 --> 02:09:46.410
of these fairly famous
films, Charles Burnett,

02:09:46.410 --> 02:09:51.250
people who have really
made major contributions.

02:09:51.250 --> 02:09:54.460
They haven't evne
seen early Spike Lee.

02:09:54.460 --> 02:09:59.520
So it's - they might have
seen Malcolm X, but that's it.

02:09:59.520 --> 02:10:04.160
So I thikn that one of the
problems wer're going to have is

02:10:04.160 --> 02:10:08.050
that there are audiences
but it's going to be smaller

02:10:08.050 --> 02:10:09.840
and smaller rather
than larger and larger.

02:10:09.840 --> 02:10:11.140
&gt;&gt; Pat Aufderheide:

02:10:11.140 --> 02:10:13.920
Let me actually address
the changing market place

02:10:13.920 --> 02:10:17.840
for documentaries and I'd love
to have any of yoru responses.

02:10:17.840 --> 02:10:23.920
This is a point at which Netflix
is busy giving people $450,000

02:10:23.920 --> 02:10:28.150
to make [Inaudible]
and oops sorry,

02:10:28.150 --> 02:10:31.490
and is launching entire lines.

02:10:31.490 --> 02:10:36.670
You've got Vice and Vulture
doing instant video journalism.

02:10:36.670 --> 02:10:40.660
You've got buzz feed explainers
apparently educating an entire

02:10:40.660 --> 02:10:42.600
new generation.

02:10:42.600 --> 02:10:46.100
And you've got cable channels
just stuffed with wall

02:10:46.100 --> 02:10:51.040
to wall something that looks
sort of like maybe documentary.

02:10:51.040 --> 02:10:54.280
And you have a legacy
that's been built up largely

02:10:54.280 --> 02:10:58.780
through the hard work of
public television that is -

02:10:58.780 --> 02:11:00.770
that honors the notion
of documentary

02:11:00.770 --> 02:11:03.870
as like a really
authentic true thing.

02:11:03.870 --> 02:11:08.960
At the same time you have an
enormous proliferation and in -

02:11:08.960 --> 02:11:11.630
weeping into the
marketplace of Netflix,

02:11:11.630 --> 02:11:13.720
Amazon and so many more.

02:11:13.720 --> 02:11:19.010
So what's the role now of
public television documentary.

02:11:19.010 --> 02:11:22.270
You know surely not
the only game in town.

02:11:22.270 --> 02:11:29.840
Expensive, oh my God compared
to like almost any other kind -

02:11:29.840 --> 02:11:36.000
source for documentary and
relatively slow compared to some

02:11:36.000 --> 02:11:38.440
of the others, what's the role?

02:11:38.440 --> 02:11:40.020
No pressure?

02:11:40.020 --> 02:11:42.640
But if you could
provide us the answer -

02:11:42.640 --> 02:11:46.510
&gt;&gt; David Fanning: It's
an enormous challenge.

02:11:46.510 --> 02:11:48.550
I think one of the great
challenges is going

02:11:48.550 --> 02:11:51.440
to be you know how do you
pick your way through all

02:11:51.440 --> 02:11:54.000
of this stuff and know what's
true and what's trustworthy

02:11:54.000 --> 02:11:57.620
and people maybe won't
care about that as much.

02:11:57.620 --> 02:12:00.730
There's going to be an enormous
amount of material that's

02:12:00.730 --> 02:12:02.420
out there in the
world being produced

02:12:02.420 --> 02:12:04.370
in all these different areas.

02:12:04.370 --> 02:12:07.590
And it's going to be
manipulated and used

02:12:07.590 --> 02:12:10.560
because this is the most
manipulative of media.

02:12:10.560 --> 02:12:13.310
And it's going to be - and so
we're going to have a harder

02:12:13.310 --> 02:12:17.720
and harder time trying to
figure out what we can trust.

02:12:17.720 --> 02:12:23.410
The trust brand and
the trust brand goes

02:12:23.410 --> 02:12:29.380
to very expensive you know
high octane documentaries made

02:12:29.380 --> 02:12:34.760
with big budgets for HBO, and
for Net Flix and others as well.

02:12:34.760 --> 02:12:40.420
It's very easy to put your hand
on the scale in documentaries

02:12:40.420 --> 02:12:44.780
and to be able to manipulate
this medium towards certain

02:12:44.780 --> 02:12:46.080
points of view.

02:12:46.080 --> 02:12:49.680
There is nothing easier
than to kind of you know,

02:12:49.680 --> 02:12:55.560
Michael Moore's famous film of
Fahrenheit 911 in the sort of -

02:12:55.560 --> 02:12:59.050
the use - getting
Wolfowicz and being able

02:12:59.050 --> 02:13:02.120
to sorto get those
seequences, fish in a barrrel.

02:13:02.120 --> 02:13:04.880
It's not hard to do,
it's very easy to be able

02:13:04.880 --> 02:13:08.530
to manipulate archival material
and to use it in different ways,

02:13:08.530 --> 02:13:10.620
to lay a voice over it.

02:13:10.620 --> 02:13:14.420
So we have a deep worry I think
behind all of this as to where -

02:13:14.420 --> 02:13:18.020
as to what lies behind it
and where do you have trust?

02:13:18.020 --> 02:13:22.010
Anything that we can hold onto
is to say that we really believe

02:13:22.010 --> 02:13:23.640
that you can trust us.

02:13:23.640 --> 02:13:27.130
And the way in which you
trust us is the body of work

02:13:27.130 --> 02:13:30.890
and the way in which we keep
doing it and also to make it

02:13:30.890 --> 02:13:32.480
as transparent as possible.

02:13:32.480 --> 02:13:37.180
So, we made - for me one of the
great err moments in the life

02:13:37.180 --> 02:13:39.700
of [Inaudible] was 1995,
we just done a film

02:13:39.700 --> 02:13:42.770
on Waco, the inside story.

02:13:42.770 --> 02:13:47.910
And we'd done all these
interviews with major FBI guys

02:13:47.910 --> 02:13:50.200
who were part of
negotiating with Koresh.

02:13:50.200 --> 02:13:53.990
We even had the audio tapes
of the actual negotiations

02:13:53.990 --> 02:13:57.120
and I kept saying "Can't
we put these audio tapes,

02:13:57.120 --> 02:13:59.200
make a radio show"
and somebody said

02:13:59.200 --> 02:14:00.650
"You can put it on the web".

02:14:00.650 --> 02:14:01.950
What's that?

02:14:01.950 --> 02:14:07.940
1995 we built a - we
built a website for Waco,

02:14:07.940 --> 02:14:10.970
the Inside Story with
that archival material.

02:14:10.970 --> 02:14:13.880
Plus I said, "Well can't we
put the whole film on there"

02:14:13.880 --> 02:14:16.820
and they said, "You
can't do that yet".

02:14:16.820 --> 02:14:19.470
And so thenwe put
the interviews up.

02:14:19.470 --> 02:14:21.810
And all the interviews
for these were -

02:14:21.810 --> 02:14:25.160
and that website exists today.

02:14:25.160 --> 02:14:28.520
People still actually write to
us about that website from '95.

02:14:28.520 --> 02:14:31.800
And then from then on once we
began publishing all of the -

02:14:31.800 --> 02:14:33.770
edited longer versions

02:14:33.770 --> 02:14:37.860
of the primary source
materials behind the front line,

02:14:37.860 --> 02:14:41.690
so that last week,
second film that ran

02:14:41.690 --> 02:14:46.040
of Putin's revenge there
