02:29:41.050 --> 02:29:43.330
in America at that time.

02:29:43.330 --> 02:29:46.690
And I would just - I think
it would be really useful

02:29:46.690 --> 02:29:50.740
if you would put Sesame Street
in the context of those times

02:29:50.740 --> 02:29:54.740
and tell us a little bit about
what led to its creation.

02:29:54.740 --> 02:29:56.610
&gt;&gt; Lloyd Morrisett:
Well for those of you

02:29:56.610 --> 02:30:02.830
who are expecting
Elmo, I'm not Elmo.

02:30:02.830 --> 02:30:05.550
I think to talk about
the origins

02:30:05.550 --> 02:30:08.930
of Sesame Street
you have to recreat

02:30:08.930 --> 02:30:16.350
in your minds the
events of that decade.

02:30:16.350 --> 02:30:20.130
And I'm going to list them here
and I'm going to read the list

02:30:20.130 --> 02:30:22.920
because I don't want
to leave anything out.

02:30:22.920 --> 02:30:28.890
1960, television may have given
Senator John F. Kennedy the edge

02:30:28.890 --> 02:30:31.350
he needed to defeat
Vice President Nixon

02:30:31.350 --> 02:30:35.490
in the first televised
presidential debate.

02:30:35.490 --> 02:30:40.730
Kennedy wins the election
by a margin of 113,000 votes

02:30:40.730 --> 02:30:43.730
out of 69 million votes cast.

02:30:43.730 --> 02:30:50.320
1961, FCC chairman Newton
Minow makes his famous speech

02:30:50.320 --> 02:30:54.270
declaring that television
is a vast wasteland.

02:30:54.270 --> 02:31:00.700
1962, 90% of Americans
own a television set,

02:31:00.700 --> 02:31:04.270
ABC begins broadcasting
in color.

02:31:04.270 --> 02:31:06.350
The Federal government
funds first funds -

02:31:06.350 --> 02:31:10.590
the Federal Government
funds public broadcasting

02:31:10.590 --> 02:31:14.490
through the education
television facilities act.

02:31:14.490 --> 02:31:24.160
June of 1962, President Kennedy
federalizes Alabama's national

02:31:24.160 --> 02:31:26.920
guard and orders
Governor George Wallace

02:31:26.920 --> 02:31:31.630
to allow two black students to
be enrolled at the university.

02:31:37.040 --> 02:31:41.840
Just recounting these events
I find them very emotional.

02:31:43.250 --> 02:31:49.460
In January of 1962 Martin
Luther King delivers his

02:31:49.460 --> 02:31:52.820
"I have a Dream" speech.

02:31:52.820 --> 02:31:59.300
In August more than 200,000
Americans march on Washington

02:31:59.300 --> 02:32:01.310
in support of Civil Rights.

02:32:01.310 --> 02:32:08.040
1964 the 24th Amendment

02:32:08.040 --> 02:32:13.860
to the Constitution makes US
Poll taxes unconstitutional.

02:32:14.950 --> 02:32:19.560
March 1964 President Johnson
declares the war on poverty.

02:32:19.560 --> 02:32:22.920
He signs an Economic
Opportunity Act in August

02:32:22.920 --> 02:32:26.030
and appoints R. Sargent
Shriver to head the new Office

02:32:26.030 --> 02:32:28.530
of Economic Opportunity.

02:32:28.530 --> 02:32:32.340
Again in 1964 President
Johnson signs the bill

02:32:32.340 --> 02:32:33.900
enacting Medicare.

02:32:33.900 --> 02:32:38.440
The Great Society is underway.

02:32:38.440 --> 02:32:43.440
In August of 1964 Congress
approves the Tonkin Gulf

02:32:43.440 --> 02:32:46.480
Resolution authorizing
Presidnet Johnson

02:32:46.480 --> 02:32:50.490
to take all necessary measures
to repel any armed attack

02:32:50.490 --> 02:32:52.960
against forces of
the United States

02:32:52.960 --> 02:32:56.150
and to prevent further
aggression.

02:32:56.150 --> 02:33:01.840
December of 1964 President
Johnson announes a substantial

02:33:01.840 --> 02:33:05.430
increase in USA to South Vietnam

02:33:05.430 --> 02:33:08.090
to restrain mounting
infiltration of men

02:33:08.090 --> 02:33:10.310
and equipment by
the Hanoi Regime

02:33:10.310 --> 02:33:12.560
in support of the Vietcong.

02:33:12.560 --> 02:33:18.510
In 1965 January in the State

02:33:18.510 --> 02:33:22.500
of the Union message President
Johnson outlines program

02:33:22.500 --> 02:33:26.910
for the Great society that will
eliminate poverty in America.

02:33:26.910 --> 02:33:31.200
In February Dr. Martin
Luther King is arrested

02:33:31.200 --> 02:33:33.500
in Soma, Alabama.

02:33:40.500 --> 02:33:43.970
In February also Malcolm
X is assassinated.

02:33:48.040 --> 02:33:52.020
Coincidentally during
National Brotherhood week.

02:33:52.020 --> 02:33:56.020
June of 1965 Congress
authorizes the use

02:33:56.020 --> 02:33:58.240
of ground troops in Vietnam.

02:33:58.240 --> 02:34:00.890
A complete ground
offensive is underway

02:34:00.890 --> 02:34:03.990
and the Vietcong will collapse

02:34:03.990 --> 02:34:09.400
in a few weeks said President
Johnson's national security

02:34:09.400 --> 02:34:13.130
advisor, Walt Russell,
not months but weeks.

02:34:13.130 --> 02:34:17.080
125,000 troops are in Vietnam.

02:34:18.170 --> 02:34:22.950
In August of that year the
Voting Rights Act becomes law.

02:34:22.950 --> 02:34:26.500
And in August of that year
the Carnegie Commission

02:34:26.500 --> 02:34:30.450
on educational television begins
its landmark study of broadcast.

02:34:30.450 --> 02:34:37.740
In 1967 public broadcasting
laboratory airs

02:34:37.740 --> 02:34:40.000
over national educational
television.

02:34:40.000 --> 02:34:43.660
It is a Sunday night
magazine program designed

02:34:43.660 --> 02:34:48.550
to showcase the relevance and
importance of public television.

02:34:49.780 --> 02:34:52.640
We'll come back to that because
that was a much more important

02:34:52.640 --> 02:34:55.180
historically in public
broadcasting then is

02:34:55.180 --> 02:34:56.680
generally recognized.

02:34:56.680 --> 02:35:05.490
In March of 1968
President Johnson announces

02:35:05.490 --> 02:35:10.890
that he will not accept the
nomination for another term.

02:35:10.890 --> 02:35:14.650
His presidency has become
another casualty of Vietnam War.

02:35:14.650 --> 02:35:20.840
Ini 1968 in April Martin
Luther King is assassinated.

02:35:27.070 --> 02:35:31.420
In 1969 regular national public
broadcasting television program

02:35:31.420 --> 02:35:34.720
begins five nights a week.

02:35:34.720 --> 02:35:39.620
In November of that year
Sesame Street goes on the air.

02:35:42.460 --> 02:35:47.580
Now as you can tell from
my emotions this was a very

02:35:47.580 --> 02:35:49.690
turbulent time.

02:35:49.690 --> 02:35:56.000
It strongly affected all of us,
all of us who were alive then.

02:35:56.000 --> 02:36:02.660
And it was out of that in part,
that Sesame Street was born.

02:36:02.660 --> 02:36:09.100
We started working
on the idea in 1966.

02:36:09.100 --> 02:36:12.970
And the people that came
to us to help Dave Connell

02:36:12.970 --> 02:36:15.910
for example our executive
vice president,

02:36:15.910 --> 02:36:21.140
Joan Cooney obviously joined
me and the original idea.

02:36:21.140 --> 02:36:28.510
All of us were very affected
by the events I've discussed.

02:36:28.510 --> 02:36:32.930
And so Sesame Street was in
part, born out of a belief

02:36:32.930 --> 02:36:35.370
in Civil Rights that we all had.

02:36:35.370 --> 02:36:41.530
The fact that it appeared

02:36:41.530 --> 02:36:46.820
on public television was
somewhat of an accident.

02:36:46.820 --> 02:36:48.910
When we first started
to raise money for it

02:36:48.910 --> 02:36:55.510
in 1966 Doc Howe had become
commissioner of Education

02:36:55.510 --> 02:36:58.410
and he had been formerly
president, superintendent

02:36:58.410 --> 02:36:59.760
of schools in Scarsdale.

02:36:59.760 --> 02:37:05.910
And he was one of the first
people we talked to about it.

02:37:05.910 --> 02:37:11.130
He - after some deliberation
overruled his staff and said

02:37:11.130 --> 02:37:14.070
that he would find
4 million dollars

02:37:14.070 --> 02:37:17.960
to help us get on the air.

02:37:17.960 --> 02:37:21.830
So, with that 4 million
dollars plus the million dollars

02:37:21.830 --> 02:37:26.880
that Carnegie had already put
up we had 5 million dollars.

02:37:26.880 --> 02:37:34.320
Lou Housman was Doc Howe's
point person in liasoning

02:37:34.320 --> 02:37:37.960
between the Office of
Education and what was going

02:37:37.960 --> 02:37:40.600
to become Sesame Workshop.

02:37:40.600 --> 02:37:45.020
Lou came out of NBC television
and he strongly believed

02:37:45.020 --> 02:37:48.930
that the program should be
on commercial television.

02:37:48.930 --> 02:37:50.500
He said "Where are
the people going,

02:37:50.500 --> 02:37:51.880
they're on commercial
television.

02:37:51.880 --> 02:37:54.780
That's where you have to be".

02:37:54.780 --> 02:38:02.520
So, we took that advice
seriously and I met with NBC,

02:38:02.520 --> 02:38:09.010
CBS, Lou W Broadcasting
and got very nice -

02:38:09.010 --> 02:38:13.560
a very nice reception
but no money.

02:38:13.560 --> 02:38:15.340
No air time.

02:38:15.340 --> 02:38:18.660
The program was fully funded
but we couldn't understand,

02:38:18.660 --> 02:38:22.340
I couldn't understand
in my naivette why

02:38:22.340 --> 02:38:27.020
with a fully funded program
we couldn't have any air time.

02:38:27.020 --> 02:38:29.660
Later I realized and
I've realized it ever

02:38:29.660 --> 02:38:33.080
since that the advertising
part weren't interested

02:38:33.080 --> 02:38:35.920
in having those minutes
sold that way.

02:38:35.920 --> 02:38:37.270
They wanted to raise money

02:38:37.270 --> 02:38:39.740
around the program
and they couldn't.

02:38:39.740 --> 02:38:44.340
So the commercial broadcasters
turned us down and just

02:38:44.340 --> 02:38:48.130
at that point the public
broadcasting act had been signed

02:38:48.130 --> 02:38:51.330
and public broadcasting
needed programming.

02:38:51.330 --> 02:38:56.640
We needed air time, it was a - I
won't say it was made in Heaven,

02:38:56.640 --> 02:39:03.520
but it was certainly made
by an accident of history.

02:39:03.520 --> 02:39:09.800
So, the - the things that
made it possible in addition

02:39:09.800 --> 02:39:12.860
to the ones that
I've already cited,

02:39:12.860 --> 02:39:17.280
are that the people essentially
who created the climate

02:39:17.280 --> 02:39:19.160
to accept the idea

02:39:19.160 --> 02:39:23.110
of a children's television
program were all in their place.

02:39:23.110 --> 02:39:27.790
John Gardener had been my boss
at Carnegie, was a good friend.

02:39:27.790 --> 02:39:31.660
Doc Howe had also
become a friend.

02:39:31.660 --> 02:39:38.170
Other people who were
not directly involved

02:39:38.170 --> 02:39:42.090
in the origins, but created
the climate in Washington

02:39:42.090 --> 02:39:43.480
that made it possible.

02:39:43.480 --> 02:39:47.130
Newton Minow was one, he's
been a friend the rest

02:39:47.130 --> 02:39:49.270
of his life for me.

02:39:49.270 --> 02:39:55.220
Henry Gellar who some of you
may remember, was an ardent fan

02:39:55.220 --> 02:39:58.860
of the publics use
of broadcasting

02:39:58.860 --> 02:40:03.590
and not giving it away free
to commercial broadcasters.

02:40:03.590 --> 02:40:06.030
The other person I'd mention,

02:40:06.030 --> 02:40:08.910
whose name has already
come up is Doug Cater.

02:40:08.910 --> 02:40:13.370
Doug Cater was Lyndon Johnson's
special assistant for education.

02:40:13.370 --> 02:40:15.670
He shepherded the
Public Broadcasting Act

02:40:15.670 --> 02:40:20.170
through the process of
getting it to Congress

02:40:20.170 --> 02:40:23.930
and he was also a great
friend of the kidns of htings

02:40:23.930 --> 02:40:26.280
that we were trying to do.

02:40:26.280 --> 02:40:33.920
Joan Cooney had been at NBC and
then she had been at channel 13

02:40:33.920 --> 02:40:37.620
where she was a commercial
- not a commercial,

02:40:37.620 --> 02:40:42.310
a documentary producer and
had three good documentaries

02:40:42.310 --> 02:40:44.050
to her name.

02:40:44.050 --> 02:40:48.850
So, essentially not only
had the climate of opinion

02:40:48.850 --> 02:40:54.540
in the country been fertilized
I'll say by the events

02:40:54.540 --> 02:40:58.780
of the 1960's, but the
particular people I've mentioend

02:40:58.780 --> 02:41:02.190
were all interested
in the public's use

02:41:02.190 --> 02:41:06.070
of public facilities
and public education.

02:41:06.070 --> 02:41:10.810
They are what made the
idea become possible.

02:41:10.810 --> 02:41:12.310
I think I'll stop
there Jennifer.

02:41:12.310 --> 02:41:13.610
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: Terrific.

02:41:13.610 --> 02:41:15.410
Terrific now thank you.

02:41:15.410 --> 02:41:21.810
[ Applause ]

02:41:21.810 --> 02:41:26.410
Paula. Your work exemplifies
informal educaiton.

02:41:26.410 --> 02:41:29.540
You've helped popularize
and demystify science

02:41:29.540 --> 02:41:32.780
and science educaiton
and you've given exposure

02:41:32.780 --> 02:41:38.240
to some scientists that has made
them as popular as rock stars,

02:41:38.240 --> 02:41:40.460
Neil deGrasse Tyson,
Brian Greene,

02:41:40.460 --> 02:41:44.450
I mean you know it's easy
to go places and people go

02:41:44.450 --> 02:41:49.260
"Oh wow Brian Greene,
string theory".

02:41:49.260 --> 02:41:54.550
And so it's - and then you've
also shown us women and people

02:41:54.550 --> 02:41:58.000
of color in the sciences
routinely throughout

02:41:58.000 --> 02:42:00.180
your series.

02:42:00.180 --> 02:42:06.230
With NOVA what's the origin, how
do we get from there to here?

02:42:06.230 --> 02:42:07.530
&gt;&gt; Paula Apsell: That's good.

02:42:07.530 --> 02:42:10.390
I first of all just want to say
I'm just awed to be setting next

02:42:10.390 --> 02:42:13.580
to Lloyd because my daughter
Natalie is here with me today

02:42:13.580 --> 02:42:18.930
and I just can see in my mind's
eye, this makes me emotional.

02:42:18.930 --> 02:42:21.450
And she and her sisters
little girls woud be sitting

02:42:21.450 --> 02:42:24.530
on that couch every
single day at 4:00,

02:42:24.530 --> 02:42:26.010
their thumbs in their mouth.

02:42:26.010 --> 02:42:28.340
A bomb could have
gone off in that room

02:42:28.340 --> 02:42:29.880
and they would not have moved.

02:42:29.880 --> 02:42:31.870
And what they learned

02:42:31.870 --> 02:42:35.740
from Sesame Street way beyond
the importance of the letters,

02:42:35.740 --> 02:42:39.300
the lessons about life,
about ethics, about morality,

02:42:39.300 --> 02:42:42.750
about how you treat other
people of all different kinds,

02:42:42.750 --> 02:42:45.210
even if they're not
familiar to you,

02:42:45.210 --> 02:42:48.970
and now as everyone
knows I have a grandson.

02:42:48.970 --> 02:42:54.700
And he watches the science
kid and also Sesame Street

02:42:54.700 --> 02:42:56.610
and the other programs on PBS.

02:42:56.610 --> 02:43:00.770
So, as well as being a content
generator, I'm a recipient

02:43:00.770 --> 02:43:07.260
of all the good things that PBS
does for kids and educationally,

02:43:07.260 --> 02:43:10.430
and it's just - really
it's just overwhelming.

02:43:10.430 --> 02:43:14.400
I feel so fortunate
to be a part of this.

02:43:14.400 --> 02:43:16.210
Now on to NOVA.

02:43:16.210 --> 02:43:19.350
So, education is in NOVA's DNA.

02:43:19.350 --> 02:43:22.860
We've been producing content
for teachers and students

02:43:22.860 --> 02:43:25.970
for as long as we've been
on PBS, and that's 44 years

02:43:25.970 --> 02:43:28.580
which is an eternity
in television.

02:43:28.580 --> 02:43:31.010
And now I have to
mention another man

02:43:31.010 --> 02:43:33.040
that I think is a
really great person

02:43:33.040 --> 02:43:36.710
and that is Michael
Lambersino who started NOVA.

02:43:36.710 --> 02:43:40.450
Michael just had -

02:43:40.450 --> 02:43:42.880
[ Applause ]

02:43:42.880 --> 02:43:47.790
Michael just had a really
good idea, very simple.

02:43:47.790 --> 02:43:50.580
His idea was sciecne is
not a collection of facts,

02:43:50.580 --> 02:43:54.640
it's a story and if you tell
the story with characters

02:43:54.640 --> 02:43:57.620
and with visuals then
people will watch

02:43:57.620 --> 02:44:00.370
and they will learn,
but they will enjoy.

02:44:00.370 --> 02:44:04.490
And it will change their
opinion about science and make -

02:44:04.490 --> 02:44:08.100
help them to undersatnd what
an important part of our lives

02:44:08.100 --> 02:44:12.280
and what an important, I
would say cultural institution

02:44:12.280 --> 02:44:14.690
that it is really a thrill

02:44:14.690 --> 02:44:19.120
to get a better understanding
of our world.

02:44:19.120 --> 02:44:24.460
And Michael always knew that
it was very important for NOVA

02:44:24.460 --> 02:44:26.210
to go to teachers as well,

02:44:26.210 --> 02:44:28.790
and they should have
supplementary materials

02:44:28.790 --> 02:44:31.290
that would help them use
NOVA in the classroom.

02:44:31.290 --> 02:44:35.910
So for years and years and
years we made teachers plans,

02:44:35.910 --> 02:44:38.350
which had all sorts of
suggestions and tips

02:44:38.350 --> 02:44:40.500
and activities for
the classroom.

02:44:40.500 --> 02:44:45.340
But teaching changes, education
changes and technology changes.

02:44:45.340 --> 02:44:50.120
And nowit began as teachers
domain at WGBH went to PBS

02:44:50.120 --> 02:44:52.690
as PBS learning media.

02:44:52.690 --> 02:44:56.900
A fabulous digital
library, the central hub

02:44:56.900 --> 02:45:00.980
for all the educational content
produced by all the PBS brands

02:45:00.980 --> 02:45:03.480
and it now reaches more

02:45:03.480 --> 02:45:07.410
than 2 million educators,
which is amazing.

02:45:07.410 --> 02:45:10.420
And WGBH is the stem
lead for PBS LM

02:45:10.420 --> 02:45:16.140
and NOVA itself has contributed
more then 900 resources,

02:45:16.140 --> 02:45:18.930
mainly video clips,
lots of animation

02:45:18.930 --> 02:45:23.970
and these are all contextualized
with teaching standards

02:45:23.970 --> 02:45:27.630
and discussion questions
and background essays

02:45:27.630 --> 02:45:31.120
and we promote these
clips really rigorously

02:45:31.120 --> 02:45:33.890
to teachers at conferences.

02:45:33.890 --> 02:45:38.720
We also create new digital
content like NOVA labs,

02:45:38.720 --> 02:45:42.530
which is a platform of
science games and interactives

02:45:42.530 --> 02:45:44.830
that uses real scientific data.

02:45:44.830 --> 02:45:48.790
And these are actually, they
were originally designed

02:45:48.790 --> 02:45:53.700
for teens to use at home and
not as an in school activity,

02:45:53.700 --> 02:45:56.920
but they turned out to be
really popular with teachers,

02:45:56.920 --> 02:46:00.970
which use them all the time
and actually assign them

02:46:00.970 --> 02:46:03.170
to their students
to do as homework.

02:46:03.170 --> 02:46:06.690
So to date, that platform
has engaged nearly more

02:46:06.690 --> 02:46:09.130
than 4 million unique viewers.

02:46:09.130 --> 02:46:12.950
And our education lab, and
I just find this amazing,

02:46:12.950 --> 02:46:18.040
is NOVA's most visited page,
so I find that amazing.

02:46:18.040 --> 02:46:22.100
We have an upcoming two
hour program on black holes,

02:46:22.100 --> 02:46:25.620
which is hosted by
astrophysicist Janna Levin

02:46:25.620 --> 02:46:30.230
and to go with that we create
an iPad app that invites players

02:46:30.230 --> 02:46:34.250
to navigate the cosmos
by hurling stars

02:46:34.250 --> 02:46:36.340
at various celestial objects.

02:46:36.340 --> 02:46:40.760
Kind of like Angry Birds
but it's for the universe.

02:46:40.760 --> 02:46:46.640
But that's - that's our what we
call our educational content,

02:46:46.640 --> 02:46:51.950
whether it's informal or formal
but science is for everyone.

02:46:51.950 --> 02:46:57.800
And so is NOVA, and so of course
I love it when people tell me

02:46:57.800 --> 02:47:00.660
"I went into science
or engineering

02:47:00.660 --> 02:47:02.980
as a result of watching NOVA".

02:47:02.980 --> 02:47:07.830
But really we want to stoke
curiosity and excitement

02:47:07.830 --> 02:47:10.520
about science in
people of all ages.

02:47:10.520 --> 02:47:14.120
So we have a very
rich historic archive

02:47:14.120 --> 02:47:17.750
that chronicles scientific
research over four decades.

02:47:17.750 --> 02:47:20.780
If you want ot know the
origins of genetic engineering

02:47:20.780 --> 02:47:24.950
or how artificial intelligence
got started you know you can

02:47:24.950 --> 02:47:28.500
really - we've been covering
that throughout the 20th century

02:47:28.500 --> 02:47:32.910
and now 21st century on NOVA
and at any given time we have

02:47:32.910 --> 02:47:37.180
about 100 full length
programs available to everyone

02:47:37.180 --> 02:47:40.090
to watch online on
PBS.org for free.

02:47:40.090 --> 02:47:43.030
And we also reach out
into the community.

02:47:43.030 --> 02:47:49.660
We've created a coalition of
science café's more than 400

02:47:49.660 --> 02:47:54.340
of them and we ourselves,
every month at WGBH studio,

02:47:54.340 --> 02:47:57.920
at the Boston Public Library,
we hold a science café

02:47:57.920 --> 02:47:59.620
for anyone who wants to come.

02:47:59.620 --> 02:48:02.040
And these science
café's are usually held

02:48:02.040 --> 02:48:04.780
at non-traditional settings.

02:48:04.780 --> 02:48:07.370
They're a chance for
people to actually interact

02:48:07.370 --> 02:48:10.400
with real scientists and
it's really kind of amazing

02:48:10.400 --> 02:48:14.620
to know how many people in their
daily life don't get a chance

02:48:14.620 --> 02:48:17.070
to really meet a
scientist and talk to them.

02:48:17.070 --> 02:48:21.380
And I think that's why
people get very wrong ideas

02:48:21.380 --> 02:48:24.750
about sicentisits
and about science.

02:48:24.750 --> 02:48:28.540
And so - and people
really enjoy these settings

02:48:28.540 --> 02:48:29.840
when they're held.

02:48:29.840 --> 02:48:32.620
And an example of this is
we also of our reaching

02:48:32.620 --> 02:48:36.680
out into the community is our
program school of the future,

02:48:36.680 --> 02:48:40.440
which actually looked at the
issue of educational equity

02:48:40.440 --> 02:48:45.840
and what kinds of new techniques
and technologies can be used

02:48:45.840 --> 02:48:47.840
to help equalize things.

02:48:47.840 --> 02:48:54.000
We organzed 293 communtiy
screenings at K12 settings,

02:48:54.000 --> 02:48:58.410
at community organizations
and really all over the place.

02:48:58.410 --> 02:49:02.680
And people came and they really
engaged in the discussion

02:49:02.680 --> 02:49:06.180
of how education can be
made better for everyone.

02:49:06.180 --> 02:49:08.840
And finally and this
really touches the point

02:49:08.840 --> 02:49:13.500
that you made Jennier, we want
people from all backgrounds

02:49:13.500 --> 02:49:17.270
to appreciate the importance
of science in our lives

02:49:17.270 --> 02:49:19.150
and the crucial role

02:49:19.150 --> 02:49:22.600
that science literacy
plays in a democracy.

02:49:22.600 --> 02:49:26.210
And now CPB with their
help, we've been able

02:49:26.210 --> 02:49:30.350
to develop short form video that
explains the science behind many

02:49:30.350 --> 02:49:33.720
of the stories that are
dominating the news cycle.

02:49:33.720 --> 02:49:38.580
If you - embedded on all
of our work is the mmandate

02:49:38.580 --> 02:49:42.150
that we have on public media
to reflect the diversity

02:49:42.150 --> 02:49:45.440
of all people and
experiences in our country.

02:49:45.440 --> 02:49:50.670
We are 100% committed to
increasing diversitiy in front

02:49:50.670 --> 02:49:52.690
of and behind the camera

02:49:52.690 --> 02:49:56.090
by actively cultivating
both producers

02:49:56.090 --> 02:49:57.760
and scientists of color.

02:49:57.760 --> 02:50:01.410
And I really invite you to
take a look at any current NOVA

02:50:01.410 --> 02:50:04.150
and you'll be able ot
see what we're doing.

02:50:04.150 --> 02:50:06.160
But equally important to that,

02:50:06.160 --> 02:50:10.150
we're actually expanding the
scope of the stories we tell,

02:50:10.150 --> 02:50:16.070
focusing more on the ways that
science impacts social jsutice.

02:50:16.070 --> 02:50:19.740
Our episode last spring
Poison Water, about the Flint,

02:50:19.740 --> 02:50:22.690
Michigan water crisis
is an exmaple of that

02:50:22.690 --> 02:50:26.800
with all its associated
digital educational content.

02:50:26.800 --> 02:50:32.680
I also believe that this really
illustrated the importance

02:50:32.680 --> 02:50:38.010
of education being embedded in
a production unit like NOVA.

02:50:38.010 --> 02:50:42.350
Our education director Ralph
Bukay who taught biology

02:50:42.350 --> 02:50:46.380
in an inner city high school in
Philadephia and can really share

02:50:46.380 --> 02:50:48.410
that experience with all of us.

02:50:48.410 --> 02:50:51.490
He has a leadership
role in our unit

02:50:51.490 --> 02:50:54.820
and not only does this
integration drive many

02:50:54.820 --> 02:50:57.370
of our initiatives,
but the lessons

02:50:57.370 --> 02:51:02.580
that we learn educational and
digital and broadcast go back

02:51:02.580 --> 02:51:08.010
and forth and they are all
enriched by this integration

02:51:08.010 --> 02:51:12.130
and that helps us better to
serve the American people.

02:51:12.130 --> 02:51:13.930
Thank you.

02:51:13.930 --> 02:51:19.640
[ Applause ]

02:51:19.640 --> 02:51:22.150
&gt;&gt; Jennier Lawson: Kathryn
you've studied children's

02:51:22.150 --> 02:51:26.310
television and Sesame
Street in real depth.

02:51:26.310 --> 02:51:29.160
And you've learned a lot
about the role of the series

02:51:29.160 --> 02:51:32.470
in educating pre-schoolers
but through your work

02:51:32.470 --> 02:51:34.580
and through the particular
angles

02:51:34.580 --> 02:51:37.180
that you have approached Sesame
Street you've learned a lot

02:51:37.180 --> 02:51:39.960
about our society as well.

02:51:39.960 --> 02:51:43.050
And could you share some of
your observations with us?

02:51:43.050 --> 02:51:44.350
&gt;&gt; Kathryn Ostrofsky:
Yeah I think I'm here

02:51:44.350 --> 02:51:47.900
to represent the generation
that did grow up on PBS

02:51:47.900 --> 02:51:52.300
and my education of course
started with Sesame Street

02:51:52.300 --> 02:51:53.970
and is continuing
with Sesame Street

02:51:53.970 --> 02:51:56.260
through my graduate school
and now in my teaching.

02:51:56.260 --> 02:52:00.530
I just never stopped
watching it.

02:52:00.530 --> 02:52:05.470
So I've been asked to talk about
public broadcasting as history,

02:52:05.470 --> 02:52:09.890
and that's why I use Sesame
Street as a historical source.

02:52:09.890 --> 02:52:12.490
But so much of public
broadcasting of course,

02:52:12.490 --> 02:52:14.650
can be used as historical
sources.

02:52:14.650 --> 02:52:17.400
And the way that we
often think about that is

02:52:17.400 --> 02:52:21.460
that public broadcasting
recorded our past,

02:52:21.460 --> 02:52:24.320
the public affairs
shows, the talk shows,

02:52:24.320 --> 02:52:29.540
recordings of great
performances are now an archive

02:52:29.540 --> 02:52:30.840
of our history.

02:52:30.840 --> 02:52:33.730
And that is true,
but as a scholar

02:52:33.730 --> 02:52:36.830
and as a teacher I am
more intersted in thinking

02:52:36.830 --> 02:52:39.530
about the ways that public
broadcasting is our history

02:52:39.530 --> 02:52:42.080
because it is a forum,
it is a vehicle,

02:52:42.080 --> 02:52:44.690
a tool for which we seek
to understand our past

02:52:44.690 --> 02:52:46.650
and our present and
shape our future.

02:52:46.650 --> 02:52:49.190
I think this is a tehme that's
been running throughout all the

02:52:49.190 --> 02:52:51.740
panel this afternoon, the theme

02:52:51.740 --> 02:52:56.180
of democratization
and interactivity.

02:52:56.180 --> 02:53:00.640
So this happens from both
angles, from the producers

02:53:00.640 --> 02:53:03.160
as well from the audiences.

02:53:03.160 --> 02:53:06.530
From the producers, the way that
they approach their programs

02:53:06.530 --> 02:53:09.450
and Laird just doesn't report
the news, he analyzes it.

02:53:09.450 --> 02:53:12.320
Dick Cavett doesn't just
ask boilerplate questions

02:53:12.320 --> 02:53:14.590
of celebrities, he engages
them in a conversation

02:53:14.590 --> 02:53:18.020
that can take any turn.

02:53:19.720 --> 02:53:24.410
Even almost coming
to physical blows.

02:53:24.410 --> 02:53:27.680
Lloyd Morrisett and Jim Gance
Cooney did not just television

02:53:27.680 --> 02:53:30.510
to teach letters and numbers,
they designed a program

02:53:30.510 --> 02:53:33.050
that reflected the
cultural sensibilities

02:53:33.050 --> 02:53:37.200
of the urban minority children
that they hoped to serve.

02:53:37.200 --> 02:53:40.860
And they built the program
to be able to evolve

02:53:40.860 --> 02:53:42.910
and to be responsive

02:53:42.910 --> 02:53:45.380
to society's changing
educational needs

02:53:45.380 --> 02:53:47.040
and cultural needs.

02:53:47.040 --> 02:53:51.110
So, all of these progrms are
- they're not just series

02:53:51.110 --> 02:53:54.240
of short conversations
or presentations,

02:53:54.240 --> 02:53:58.790
rather they are decades long
conversations between producers

02:53:58.790 --> 02:54:03.300
and audiences about
issues that matter to us.

02:54:03.300 --> 02:54:08.690
So public broadcasting
creates in particualr,

02:54:08.690 --> 02:54:12.620
creates a really rich
record of these discussions

02:54:12.620 --> 02:54:16.100
of these long conversations
because it's funding comes

02:54:16.100 --> 02:54:17.400
from the government

02:54:17.400 --> 02:54:21.480
and philanthropic foundations
and viewers like you.

02:54:21.480 --> 02:54:28.650
They producers and stations
constantly have to articulate

02:54:28.650 --> 02:54:31.350
to their audiences and to their
funders what they're doing,

02:54:31.350 --> 02:54:34.560
why they're doing it like that
and what impact it's having.

02:54:34.560 --> 02:54:38.150
It creates a paper trail that
is amazing for historians.

02:54:38.150 --> 02:54:44.270
Because public broadcasting
is for the people

02:54:44.270 --> 02:54:48.060
and it's mobilizing this
technology not for advertisers

02:54:48.060 --> 02:54:51.060
but for the audiences
themselves, the audiences,

02:54:51.060 --> 02:54:55.790
educators, social activities
have through the years felt

02:54:55.790 --> 02:54:59.580
that they could and should
make their voices heard

02:54:59.580 --> 02:55:03.490
in public media as a
collaborative effort

02:55:03.490 --> 02:55:07.830
to improve programs or to use
public broadcasting as a tool

02:55:07.830 --> 02:55:09.830
for broader social change.

02:55:09.830 --> 02:55:13.510
So they do talk back
to their televisions

02:55:13.510 --> 02:55:16.020
as Nicholas Johnson suggested.

02:55:16.020 --> 02:55:20.660
So in the case of Sesame Street
for instance, the producers

02:55:20.660 --> 02:55:25.410
and the audiences agreed that
the show should provide models

02:55:25.410 --> 02:55:28.870
for ideal community
interactions.

02:55:28.870 --> 02:55:34.450
But as Lloyd was just talking
about there's a lot going

02:55:34.450 --> 02:55:36.020
on in the 60's and 70's.

02:55:36.020 --> 02:55:39.740
There's Civil Rights, cultural
pride movements proliferating

02:55:39.740 --> 02:55:42.360
and fragmenting in the 1970's.

02:55:42.360 --> 02:55:46.020
So, all of these people who
are invested in Sesame Street

02:55:46.020 --> 02:55:50.370
in some way don't agree on what
that ideal community should look

02:55:50.370 --> 02:55:54.340
like or sound like, how
those people should behave.

02:55:54.340 --> 02:55:57.710
So, cast members,
staff, parents, critics,

02:55:57.710 --> 02:56:00.690
advocacy groups like the
National Organization of Women

02:56:00.690 --> 02:56:05.800
and the UCLA Chicano Studies
Center had ongoing discussions

02:56:05.800 --> 02:56:08.240
about characters - how
characters should speak,

02:56:08.240 --> 02:56:12.330
what musical guests to
feature, how to represent

02:56:12.330 --> 02:56:16.230
and celebrate diversity without
perpetuating stereotypes.

02:56:16.230 --> 02:56:18.480
And there was no easy answers

02:56:18.480 --> 02:56:21.780
and luckily Sesame Street is a
variety show so they could sort

02:56:21.780 --> 02:56:24.970
of experiment with
all these things

02:56:24.970 --> 02:56:28.260
at the same time
and see what worked.

02:56:28.260 --> 02:56:34.140
So - but this engagement with
social issues also happens long

02:56:34.140 --> 02:56:38.100
after the programs first air.

02:56:38.100 --> 02:56:42.440
And it's - it has
become cliché to say

02:56:42.440 --> 02:56:47.250
that documetnaries bringthe past
to life, but they certainly do

02:56:47.250 --> 02:56:52.410
in my classroom, not
just metaphorically

02:56:52.410 --> 02:56:55.740
but these programs
often have the power

02:56:55.740 --> 02:56:58.470
to continue the traditions
that they discuss.

02:56:58.470 --> 02:57:00.100
The first episode
of Eyes on the Prize

02:57:00.100 --> 02:57:03.940
for example is called Awakenings
and it shows how media coverage

02:57:03.940 --> 02:57:08.400
of the lynchings, lynching of
Emmett Till and the sham trial

02:57:08.400 --> 02:57:17.120
that allowed his murderers to
go free led to a published -

02:57:17.120 --> 02:57:20.710
public consciousness about
the conditions of Jim Crowe

02:57:20.710 --> 02:57:23.640
and inspired Civil
Rights actions.

02:57:23.640 --> 02:57:26.800
Watching the documentary itself
is a consciousness raising

02:57:26.800 --> 02:57:29.080
experience for my students

02:57:29.080 --> 02:57:33.280
and there is no more
powerful demonstration for why

02:57:33.280 --> 02:57:37.130
so many people risked their
lives for Civil Rights.

02:57:37.130 --> 02:57:39.270
One episode of the
American Experience series

02:57:39.270 --> 02:57:43.110
on Latino Americans
covers the 1968 walk outs

02:57:43.110 --> 02:57:46.350
through which Chicano high
school students took control

02:57:46.350 --> 02:57:49.820
of their education and sought
to understand their place -

02:57:49.820 --> 02:57:51.680
the place of themselves
and their families

02:57:51.680 --> 02:57:54.660
in American history
and American society.

02:57:54.660 --> 02:57:56.120
And for one of my
students a couple

02:57:56.120 --> 02:57:59.860
of years ago she had heard about
the walk outs from her mother

02:57:59.860 --> 02:58:05.790
who had participated in them,
but to see those events depicted

02:58:05.790 --> 02:58:12.020
on national television, in a
US history survey class did the

02:58:12.020 --> 02:58:16.980
same thing for her, it inspired
her to take her own education

02:58:16.980 --> 02:58:21.320
into her own hands and figure
out her place in society.

02:58:21.320 --> 02:58:26.070
So, public television, we're
here talking about preservation.

02:58:26.070 --> 02:58:30.410
Public television and radio
need to be preserved not just

02:58:30.410 --> 02:58:33.550
because they have recorded
history, because they continue

02:58:33.550 --> 02:58:37.630
to be the material that
we use every day to engage

02:58:37.630 --> 02:58:43.510
with our past or our
future, shape our future.

02:58:43.510 --> 02:58:48.740
[ Applause ]

02:58:48.740 --> 02:58:50.670
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: I think your
comments underscore what has

02:58:50.670 --> 02:58:53.190
been said too at some
of the other panels

02:58:53.190 --> 02:58:56.970
about the incredible
importance of the material,

02:58:56.970 --> 02:59:00.510
not just during the time
that it is broadcast

02:59:00.510 --> 02:59:03.740
but it's archival
value into the future.

02:59:03.740 --> 02:59:06.580
Before we come back
to preservation,

02:59:06.580 --> 02:59:10.630
I'd like to go back to Lloyd for
a quick question that relates

02:59:10.630 --> 02:59:12.920
to your background
in psychology too,

02:59:12.920 --> 02:59:18.330
and that is that for example a
national study recently revealed

02:59:18.330 --> 02:59:21.810
that 50% of American
children under the age

02:59:21.810 --> 02:59:25.500
of 18 have experienced
a traumatic event

02:59:25.500 --> 02:59:27.540
such as witnessing violent acts

02:59:27.540 --> 02:59:30.610
or experiencing natural
disasters.

02:59:30.610 --> 02:59:36.110
Last month Sesame Street, Sesame
Workshop launched an initiatve

02:59:36.110 --> 02:59:40.010
to help children cope with
these traumatic experiences.

02:59:40.010 --> 02:59:44.600
And Sesame Street puppets have
often in the past been used

02:59:44.600 --> 02:59:47.950
to help children talk
about events like a death

02:59:47.950 --> 02:59:50.160
in a family or divorce.

02:59:50.160 --> 02:59:55.140
And when you and Joan
were starting Sesame,

02:59:55.140 --> 03:00:00.240
did you envision this kind of
therapeutic role for the series

03:00:00.240 --> 03:00:03.910
in its early days, or is
that something that evolved?

03:00:03.910 --> 03:00:06.320
&gt;&gt; Lloyd Morrisett: It evolved.

03:00:06.320 --> 03:00:09.560
The early days question
we were tasked

03:00:09.560 --> 03:00:13.580
with answering can
television teach anything?

03:00:13.580 --> 03:00:18.820
We had to answer
that with a positive

03:00:18.820 --> 03:00:20.570
in order to gain more funding.

03:00:20.570 --> 03:00:26.570
That was the hard work of it.

03:00:26.570 --> 03:00:31.560
So initially we concentrated
on things that were taught

03:00:31.560 --> 03:00:34.990
in school, needed to be
taught in school, letters

03:00:34.990 --> 03:00:37.510
and numbers and so on.

03:00:37.510 --> 03:00:40.470
And could be easily measured;
those were the things

03:00:40.470 --> 03:00:43.230
that we were really
trying to look out.

03:00:43.230 --> 03:00:46.360
And fortunately the study
that came out showed

03:00:46.360 --> 03:00:49.650
that people watched
more learned more.

03:00:49.650 --> 03:00:52.800
With that start and with the
confidence that we were going

03:00:52.800 --> 03:00:57.040
to be able to continue once we
got a second season funding,

03:00:57.040 --> 03:01:00.450
we then began to broaden
the curriculum to take

03:01:00.450 --> 03:01:03.810
into account some of the things
that you're talking about.

03:01:03.810 --> 03:01:13.140
Although the real change
probably came much later.

03:01:13.140 --> 03:01:19.020
The military families project
was probably the most imoprtant

03:01:19.020 --> 03:01:21.320
change in that regard.

03:01:21.320 --> 03:01:26.180
And now of course as you
mentioned traumatic events,

03:01:26.180 --> 03:01:31.240
abuse, autism would
be another example

03:01:31.240 --> 03:01:35.080
where we would not have been
able to do that initially,

03:01:35.080 --> 03:01:40.660
but as the program evolved we
have been able to do more of it.

03:01:40.660 --> 03:01:41.960
&gt;&gt; Paula Apsell:
I'd like to address

03:01:41.960 --> 03:01:45.260
that issue can public
television teach anything;

03:01:45.260 --> 03:01:48.850
I think it's really an important
question and very important

03:01:48.850 --> 03:01:51.830
for NOVA in a way
because part of our -

03:01:51.830 --> 03:01:56.410
we're always discussing was
we were you know 40 years ago

03:01:56.410 --> 03:01:59.990
and we're still discussing
it is our primary function

03:01:59.990 --> 03:02:01.950
to educate and to entertain.

03:02:01.950 --> 03:02:03.250
We're always kind of talking

03:02:03.250 --> 03:02:06.010
about how you blend
those two things.

03:02:06.010 --> 03:02:09.620
But when you think back to
your own sceicne classes

03:02:09.620 --> 03:02:13.880
and how the teacher was
always talking aobut things

03:02:13.880 --> 03:02:17.720
that you couldn't understand
what he or she was talking

03:02:17.720 --> 03:02:20.120
about because you
couldn't visualize it.

03:02:20.120 --> 03:02:23.770
You had absolutely no
frame of reference for it.

03:02:23.770 --> 03:02:31.500
And I think this one of the huge
values to PBS learning media

03:02:31.500 --> 03:02:37.150
and to their whole -
their huge stem collectin

03:02:37.150 --> 03:02:41.670
because it helps -
it provides visuals.

03:02:41.670 --> 03:02:43.930
So when you're talking about
a volcano and what's going

03:02:43.930 --> 03:02:46.070
on in the molten magma
under the earth -

03:02:46.070 --> 03:02:48.540
I mean who really knows what
that means when you're a kid

03:02:48.540 --> 03:02:51.100
and you've never
lived near a volcano

03:02:51.100 --> 03:02:52.710
and you've never seen one.

03:02:52.710 --> 03:02:54.710
But here you can
have an animation

03:02:54.710 --> 03:02:58.530
and it can be contextualized
by your teacher

03:02:58.530 --> 03:03:02.510
because there are -
the archive helps.

03:03:02.510 --> 03:03:06.650
So I really I just hink
in terms of science,

03:03:06.650 --> 03:03:10.040
visuals are just so important.

03:03:10.040 --> 03:03:14.960
They also help both kids
and everyone take the world

03:03:14.960 --> 03:03:16.550
from another perspective.

03:03:16.550 --> 03:03:20.520
The design to show you things
that you can't see for yourself

03:03:20.520 --> 03:03:24.710
and that in a way,
expands your world.

03:03:24.710 --> 03:03:28.980
And that to me, is just
really one of the benefits

03:03:28.980 --> 03:03:33.550
of the educational uses of
our material and of the fact

03:03:33.550 --> 03:03:36.910
that we are fortunate enough to
be able to produce these things

03:03:36.910 --> 03:03:38.710
and have the resources to do

