for a number of years.

03:08:37.120 --> 03:08:39.900
And I want to start with you
Lloyd and just going back

03:08:39.900 --> 03:08:43.760
to the question did
Sesame Workshop

03:08:43.760 --> 03:08:48.340
as a children's television
workshop, what efforts were made

03:08:48.340 --> 03:08:53.700
in the sort of earlier years in
trying to go beyond preschoolers

03:08:53.700 --> 03:08:57.890
and to reach the
pre-teens and teenagers?

03:08:57.890 --> 03:08:59.190
&gt;&gt; Lloyd Morrisett: Well

03:08:59.190 --> 03:09:03.010
as Paula has mentione din
producing a television show you

03:09:03.010 --> 03:09:06.210
have to atract the audience as
well as teach them something.

03:09:06.210 --> 03:09:10.320
And so Sesame Street was
designed in the beginning -

03:09:10.320 --> 03:09:13.840
I need to start that again.

03:09:13.840 --> 03:09:17.230
The viewing conditions in 1969
are extremely different then

03:09:17.230 --> 03:09:18.530
they are today.

03:09:18.530 --> 03:09:22.330
In 1969 typically families
had one television set,

03:09:22.330 --> 03:09:26.480
the family watched together
and the parents could act

03:09:26.480 --> 03:09:29.490
as an intermediary between
what was on the television set

03:09:29.490 --> 03:09:31.760
and what the child learned.

03:09:31.760 --> 03:09:35.030
You say, "Johnny
did you see that A"?

03:09:35.030 --> 03:09:37.390
or "Johnny take a look
at what's coming up next,

03:09:37.390 --> 03:09:41.670
it's going to be like" and
that gets Johnny's attention

03:09:41.670 --> 03:09:45.700
to something on the set that
you want to teach about.

03:09:45.700 --> 03:09:53.320
Now I think at the - I saw
that maybe 90% of adolescents

03:09:53.320 --> 03:09:56.930
and above have smart phones.

03:09:56.930 --> 03:10:02.610
Television sets are numerous and
often the child at whatever age,

03:10:02.610 --> 03:10:07.450
two or three even controls
the set himself or herself.

03:10:07.450 --> 03:10:11.710
So the problem of
maintaining an audience

03:10:11.710 --> 03:10:13.630
and know what audience
you're really trying

03:10:13.630 --> 03:10:15.590
to reach is much harder.

03:10:15.590 --> 03:10:18.450
I don't think we've
figured it out yet.

03:10:18.450 --> 03:10:20.710
But we certianly had the
idea from the beginning

03:10:20.710 --> 03:10:23.080
that the adults had to be
atracted to the program

03:10:23.080 --> 03:10:24.380
as well as the children.

03:10:24.380 --> 03:10:28.770
&gt;&gt; Paul Apsell: I used to like
- 4:00 I was pretty tired.

03:10:28.770 --> 03:10:32.240
I'd sit there and we'd
watch Sesame Street.

03:10:32.240 --> 03:10:34.450
It appealed to adults as well.

03:10:34.450 --> 03:10:37.170
I mean I felt like
there were two levels

03:10:37.170 --> 03:10:38.770
that it was operating on.

03:10:38.770 --> 03:10:40.070
&gt;&gt; Lloyd Morrisett: Laugh in,

03:10:40.070 --> 03:10:43.940
which some of you may remember
was a very important precursor

03:10:43.940 --> 03:10:45.370
to what we did.

03:10:45.370 --> 03:10:50.690
We used a lot of the Laugh In
techniques in the early shows.

03:10:50.690 --> 03:10:52.240
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: I think
it very definitely did.

03:10:52.240 --> 03:10:56.060
The one piece that I remember
is I think it was Patti Labelle

03:10:56.060 --> 03:11:01.240
singing "I love my X, I
miss my X" and there's

03:11:01.240 --> 03:11:04.520
of course the letter
X on the screen.

03:11:04.520 --> 03:11:08.010
But the look in her eyes
suggested otherwise.

03:11:10.080 --> 03:11:13.860
So it definitely seemed as if
it was very consciously designed

03:11:13.860 --> 03:11:15.160
to -

03:11:15.160 --> 03:11:16.460
&gt;&gt; Lloyd Morrisett: It
was, no question of that.

03:11:16.460 --> 03:11:20.610
The writers particularly
enjoyed doing that.

03:11:20.610 --> 03:11:22.500
They liked to write one liners

03:11:22.500 --> 03:11:25.800
and kids didn't get
it, but the adults did.

03:11:25.800 --> 03:11:27.740
&gt;&gt; Paula Apsell: In
terms of the ages,

03:11:27.740 --> 03:11:32.610
yes but I mean we all
worry in public media

03:11:32.610 --> 03:11:34.190
about an aging audience.

03:11:34.190 --> 03:11:37.900
I mean it's like
discussed constantly

03:11:37.900 --> 03:11:40.050
and we're sweating constantly.

03:11:40.050 --> 03:11:41.370
We try to really figure it

03:11:41.370 --> 03:11:43.780
out how we can appeal
to younger people.

03:11:43.780 --> 03:11:47.860
One thing we find is that
we have a very different

03:11:47.860 --> 03:11:50.080
audience online.

03:11:50.080 --> 03:11:52.440
That the audience
online is much younger.

03:11:52.440 --> 03:11:57.030
And so the idea is that the
uadience online we do know

03:11:57.030 --> 03:11:59.460
that they love to watch our
shows on their computer.

03:11:59.460 --> 03:12:02.400
They love short form video, I
guess that's the whole thing

03:12:02.400 --> 03:12:04.290
about the attention
span, I don't know.

03:12:04.290 --> 03:12:08.720
But they also like to
watch our short form videos

03:12:08.720 --> 03:12:12.170
and if we take them off, oh
our lawyers are right there.

03:12:12.170 --> 03:12:15.170
But I have to say in two
minutes they're pirated and put

03:12:15.170 --> 03:12:18.550
on You Tube and you take them
down and they go back up.

03:12:18.550 --> 03:12:20.690
It's like a pop up,
whack a mole.

03:12:20.690 --> 03:12:23.240
It is really amazing,
so they really -

03:12:23.240 --> 03:12:26.510
I think this is a key to us.

03:12:26.510 --> 03:12:29.750
Young people we know
do not have televisions

03:12:29.750 --> 03:12:31.670
and watch television that much.

03:12:31.670 --> 03:12:35.340
They watch on their phone,
they watch on their computer.

03:12:35.340 --> 03:12:42.470
The hope is that they
will, youngsters do grow up

03:12:42.470 --> 03:12:46.870
and very often they have
families and their life changes

03:12:46.870 --> 03:12:51.540
and it starts to - and they
start to realize the value

03:12:51.540 --> 03:12:57.220
of public media and they start
to join their local station.

03:12:57.220 --> 03:13:01.650
And I think that there is,
maybe I'm just an optimist.

03:13:01.650 --> 03:13:06.010
But I think if we can
keep reaching out to them

03:13:06.010 --> 03:13:08.300
and hold them close to us

03:13:08.300 --> 03:13:12.910
by various different
forms ofwhat we do,

03:13:12.910 --> 03:13:18.240
we will migrate them in
a direction that many

03:13:18.240 --> 03:13:20.720
of them will be watching
our programs.

03:13:20.720 --> 03:13:23.080
Maybe that's just optimistic.

03:13:23.080 --> 03:13:26.870
&gt;&gt; Kathryn Ostrofsky: I think
there's an uptapped potential

03:13:26.870 --> 03:13:32.540
for that middle audience
between childrens and adults.

03:13:32.540 --> 03:13:35.950
Certainly my students,
they're adults but they -

03:13:35.950 --> 03:13:41.350
one of the things that I try
to do with the documetnaries

03:13:41.350 --> 03:13:45.560
that I show in class is to
not just show a documentary

03:13:45.560 --> 03:13:46.860
but do something with it.

03:13:46.860 --> 03:13:48.160
And there are a few
documentaries

