of the agencies what was
going wrong with their pipes.

03:18:48.710 --> 03:18:50.680
And then to see themselves
reflected

03:18:50.680 --> 03:18:55.100
in a documentary how
they had taken a role

03:18:55.100 --> 03:18:59.380
in their own survival
and the survival

03:18:59.380 --> 03:19:01.470
of their children I think
they were really amazed

03:19:01.470 --> 03:19:03.870
and I think it gave
them a different feeling

03:19:03.870 --> 03:19:05.410
about public media.

03:19:05.410 --> 03:19:09.510
That it became theirs and
you know it's not easy.

03:19:09.510 --> 03:19:12.670
They're not zillions of topics
that you can do it with,

03:19:12.670 --> 03:19:14.710
but I think it's imperative.

03:19:14.710 --> 03:19:16.010
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson:
I want to come back

03:19:16.010 --> 03:19:19.380
to Lloyd's really
appropriate question

03:19:19.380 --> 03:19:23.150
about preserving public
media for the future.

03:19:23.150 --> 03:19:27.560
And but before I do that, I want
to just also get your thoughts

03:19:27.560 --> 03:19:29.490
and we have just a quick minute.

03:19:29.490 --> 03:19:34.090
I want to get your thoughts
about beyond the screen.

03:19:34.090 --> 03:19:36.620
Because we've talked
about public broadcasting

03:19:36.620 --> 03:19:39.570
and we're talking about
broadcasting and I know that all

03:19:39.570 --> 03:19:44.260
of you are aware of public
media and you do your work

03:19:44.260 --> 03:19:47.260
on so many other
platforms as well.

03:19:47.260 --> 03:19:51.570
And I just would welcome your
speaking about the importance

03:19:51.570 --> 03:19:54.600
of public media on those
additional platforms.

03:19:54.600 --> 03:19:57.890
I think that you've
spoken to that you know

03:19:57.890 --> 03:20:02.360
in a very articulate way Paula
about what NOVA has been doing.

03:20:02.360 --> 03:20:06.880
But other thoughts
about beyond broadcast?

03:20:06.880 --> 03:20:11.760
&gt;&gt; Lloyd Morrisett: We now
get an enormous number of hits

03:20:11.760 --> 03:20:15.790
on You Tube where we've
provided a lot of clips

03:20:15.790 --> 03:20:18.480
so that's the reuse of something
that's been done before

03:20:18.480 --> 03:20:21.920
but is a very useful one.

03:20:21.920 --> 03:20:24.980
&gt;&gt; Kathryn Ostrofsky: Thoughtful
curation of the things

03:20:24.980 --> 03:20:30.320
that are available really
helps the professors who are

03:20:30.320 --> 03:20:34.720
at most colleges and
univresities that have a lot

03:20:34.720 --> 03:20:37.740
of students and not a lot
of time to prepare outside

03:20:37.740 --> 03:20:39.870
of their fields in teaching;

03:20:39.870 --> 03:20:43.930
so I would say it's
extremely important.

03:20:43.930 --> 03:20:46.110
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: So the
thoughtful curation comes

03:20:46.110 --> 03:20:49.050
into places like witih
PBS learning media.

03:20:49.050 --> 03:20:52.230
I assume where then there's
already the thought given

03:20:52.230 --> 03:20:55.640
to what age group, what
level, what the topic is,

03:20:55.640 --> 03:20:59.030
all of these - nicely
tagged and everything.

03:20:59.030 --> 03:21:01.050
&gt;&gt; Kathryn Ostrofsky: Yes
tagged, properly tagged

03:21:01.050 --> 03:21:08.630
and if there are any interactive
things that can go along with -

03:21:08.630 --> 03:21:13.750
there used to be an interactive
game of pretending you were

03:21:13.750 --> 03:21:15.430
in the gold rush and
taking on a character

03:21:15.430 --> 03:21:16.740
and seeing if you survived.

03:21:16.740 --> 03:21:19.290
And it took about two minutes
to play and it went along

03:21:19.290 --> 03:21:21.410
with the documentary
for the gold rush.

03:21:21.410 --> 03:21:22.710
I can't find it anymore.

03:21:22.710 --> 03:21:24.930
I hope it's there.

03:21:24.930 --> 03:21:27.900
It may have moved or it
may have just been old,

03:21:27.900 --> 03:21:29.490
and that's of course a problem.

03:21:29.490 --> 03:21:31.720
&gt;&gt; Paula Apsell: You have to
ask the 10 year olds to find it

03:21:31.720 --> 03:21:36.060
for you, they won't
have any problem at all.

03:21:36.060 --> 03:21:38.970
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: So as a
final question just to come back

03:21:38.970 --> 03:21:43.770
to this all important point
of - of we're at the end

03:21:43.770 --> 03:21:46.010
of this wonderful day and all

03:21:46.010 --> 03:21:49.370
of these really very,
very rich panels.

03:21:49.370 --> 03:21:55.410
What about presrving
public media for the future?

03:21:56.490 --> 03:21:57.790
&gt;&gt; Lloyd Morrisett:
I would worry most

03:21:57.790 --> 03:22:04.270
about just not having
the budget go up.

03:22:04.270 --> 03:22:06.670
Costs are going up
for everything else

03:22:06.670 --> 03:22:10.180
and there are a lot of things
that budget can be used for

03:22:10.180 --> 03:22:12.850
and we just keep it the same.

03:22:12.850 --> 03:22:17.230
So in my view the strategy
is slow starvation.

03:22:17.230 --> 03:22:21.800
&gt;&gt; Paula Apsell: I
don't want to starve.

03:22:21.800 --> 03:22:23.500
As I always say, I'm

03:22:23.500 --> 03:22:26.780
on the spending side
and I like that side.

03:22:26.780 --> 03:22:28.450
But here is what I worry about,

03:22:28.450 --> 03:22:31.300
and you just mentioned something
I thinkis very important,

03:22:31.300 --> 03:22:35.700
which is the non
broadcast aspect of series

03:22:35.700 --> 03:22:37.130
like the ones that we do.

03:22:37.130 --> 03:22:39.730
And I know my documentary
friends

03:22:39.730 --> 03:22:42.400
from the previous panel
were really aprpeciate news

03:22:42.400 --> 03:22:43.710
and all of ours.

03:22:43.710 --> 03:22:48.230
When we started our website
in 1996 we just figured okay,

03:22:48.230 --> 03:22:50.840
we'll just take the same
stuff and we'll put it online

03:22:50.840 --> 03:22:53.940
and maybe we'll you
know, put a few you know,

03:22:53.940 --> 03:23:00.700
it felt like it was just going
to be a free edition to NOVA.

03:23:00.700 --> 03:23:06.020
Now it's own mouth to
feed and it's getting

03:23:06.020 --> 03:23:08.300
to be a gigantic mouth.

03:23:08.300 --> 03:23:12.660
And sothe quesiton is and it's
so important because it is a way

03:23:12.660 --> 03:23:15.310
to attract so many people
who are not going ot turn

03:23:15.310 --> 03:23:17.020
on the television set.

03:23:17.020 --> 03:23:21.810
And I think we certainly find
it's much harder to raise money

03:23:21.810 --> 03:23:24.930
for digital then it is to
raise money for broadcast.

03:23:24.930 --> 03:23:29.220
So I think that's something
we really have to figure out

03:23:29.220 --> 03:23:31.450
and figure out with
the foundations

03:23:31.450 --> 03:23:34.910
and the other funders that
have supported public media

03:23:34.910 --> 03:23:36.440
in the past.

03:23:36.440 --> 03:23:41.560
Because this is the
new world, this is it.

03:23:41.560 --> 03:23:46.020
&gt;&gt; Kathryn Ostrofsky: Oftentimes
academics and broadcasters

03:23:46.020 --> 03:23:48.610
and archivists live
in different worlds,

03:23:48.610 --> 03:23:51.200
so I think we need more
events like this to bring all

03:23:51.200 --> 03:23:55.720
of us together and that's
the first step conversations

03:23:55.720 --> 03:23:57.490
like the ones we've had today.

03:23:57.490 --> 03:23:59.510
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Lawson: Thank you.

03:23:59.510 --> 03:24:06.460
[ Applause ]

03:24:06.460 --> 03:24:08.780
&gt;&gt; We have one more
element to this panel.

03:24:08.780 --> 03:24:13.150
We're going to let Newt
Minow have the last word,

03:24:13.150 --> 03:24:17.370
but before we do, first of
all my thanks to all of you

03:24:17.370 --> 03:24:20.870
and to you Jennifer for
the work on this panel.

03:24:20.870 --> 03:24:24.450
I hope you have found this
afternoon as fascinating

03:24:24.450 --> 03:24:28.630
as I have, being with these
founders of public media

03:24:28.630 --> 03:24:31.700
and creators of some
of the most iconic

03:24:31.700 --> 03:24:35.500
and imoprtant content
in public media.

03:24:35.500 --> 03:24:38.960
And I'd be remis if I didn't
take us back at the very end

03:24:38.960 --> 03:24:42.990
to the other meaning of the
word preserve and to talk just -

03:24:42.990 --> 03:24:45.140
say a few words abou
the American archive

03:24:45.140 --> 03:24:46.530
of public broadcasting.

03:24:46.530 --> 03:24:49.150
Although I can't be quite as
articulate as Kathryn was.

03:24:49.150 --> 03:24:57.100
I think, but we - this is
really the archive of our times.

03:24:57.100 --> 03:25:00.130
Not just our national
times as you've heard

03:25:00.130 --> 03:25:03.580
as Jennifer alluded
to, but alsothe times

03:25:03.580 --> 03:25:06.600
of our communities,
geographically

03:25:06.600 --> 03:25:09.230
around the country
from coast to coast.

03:25:09.230 --> 03:25:14.330
And culturally and believe me
local commercial broadcasters

03:25:14.330 --> 03:25:18.310
have not been able to
preserve their archives.

03:25:18.310 --> 03:25:22.570
It's - it has been too expensive
for them, you know they had

03:25:22.570 --> 03:25:27.850
to reuse those tapes or couldn't
spend the staff time given news

03:25:27.850 --> 03:25:31.410
cycles and especially
now given news cycles,

03:25:31.410 --> 03:25:33.280
endless news cycles.

03:25:33.280 --> 03:25:36.670
So commercial broadcasters
really have not,

03:25:36.670 --> 03:25:39.850
with a few exceptions been able
to preserve their archives.

03:25:39.850 --> 03:25:41.530
It just wasn't their
business plan.

03:25:41.530 --> 03:25:44.520
So it's more important
than ever that commercial -

03:25:44.520 --> 03:25:48.310
that public media
preserve its archives

03:25:48.310 --> 03:25:52.070
and it's also a very critical
part of our mission that we make

03:25:52.070 --> 03:25:53.990
that archive accessible.

03:25:53.990 --> 03:25:57.500
It's been part of the core
mission of public media

03:25:57.500 --> 03:26:00.500
from the very beginning that
we make our work available

03:26:00.500 --> 03:26:03.240
to everyone, no matter
where they are,

03:26:03.240 --> 03:26:06.710
no matter what their means
are, their ability to pay

03:26:06.710 --> 03:26:09.660
and especially in
this universe now

03:26:09.660 --> 03:26:12.820
where almost everything
is behind a paywall

03:26:12.820 --> 03:26:14.720
in media elsewhere.

03:26:14.720 --> 03:26:19.060
So I'm very proud of the
progress we've been makign

03:26:19.060 --> 03:26:21.330
through the American Archive
of Public Broadcasting

03:26:21.330 --> 03:26:25.610
to put tehse works up online
and make them accessible.

